INSERT INTO verses (book_id, chapter, verse, text, version) VALUES
(30, 22, 24, '"Son of man, give the people of Israel this message: In the day of my indignation, you will become like an uncleared wilderness or a desert without rain.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 25, 'Your princes plot conspiracies just as lions stalk their prey. They devour innocent people, seizing treasures and extorting wealth. They increase the number of widows in the land.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 26, 'Your priests have violated my laws and defiled my holy things. To them there is no difference between what is holy and what is not. And they do not teach my people the difference between what is ceremonially clean and unclean. They disregard my Sabbath days so that my holy name is greatly dishonored among them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 27, 'Your leaders are like wolves, who tear apart their victims. They actually destroy people''s lives for profit!', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 28, 'And your prophets announce false visions and speak false messages. They say, `My message is from the Sovereign LORD,'' when the LORD hasn''t spoken a single word to them. They repair cracked walls with whitewash!', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 29, 'Even common people oppress the poor, rob the needy, and deprive foreigners of justice.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 30, '"I looked for someone who might rebuild the wall of righteousness that guards the land. I searched for someone to stand in the gap in the wall so I wouldn''t have to destroy the land, but I found no one.', 'NLT'),
(30, 22, 31, 'So now I will pour out my fury on them, consuming them in the fire of my anger. I will heap on them the full penalty for all their sins, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 1, 'This message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 2, '"Son of man, once there were two sisters who were daughters of the same mother.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 3, 'They became prostitutes in Egypt. Even as young girls, they allowed themselves to be fondled and caressed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 4, 'The older girl was named Oholah, and her sister was Oholibah. I married them, and they bore me sons and daughters. I am speaking of Samaria and Jerusalem, for Oholah is Samaria and Oholibah is Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 5, '"Then Oholah lusted after other lovers instead of me, and she gave her love to the Assyrians, her neighbors.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 6, 'They were all attractive young men, captains and commanders dressed in handsome blue, dashing about on their horses.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 7, 'And so she prostituted herself with the most desirable men of Assyria, worshiping their idols and defiling herself.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 8, 'For when she left Egypt, she did not leave her spirit of prostitution behind. She was still as lewd as in her youth, when the Egyptians satisfied their lusts with her and robbed her of her virginity.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 9, 'And so I handed her over to her Assyrian lovers, whom she desired so much.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 10, 'They stripped her and killed her and took away her children as their slaves. Her name was known to every woman in the land as a sinner who had received what she deserved.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 11, '"Yet even though Oholibah saw what had happened to Oholah, her sister, she followed right in her footsteps. And she was even more depraved, abandoning herself to her lust and prostitution.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 12, 'She fawned over her Assyrian neighbors, those handsome young men on fine horses, those captains and commanders in handsome uniforms--all of them desirable.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 13, 'I saw the way she was going, defiling herself just like her older sister.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 14, '"Then she carried her prostitution even further. She fell in love with pictures that were painted on a wall--pictures of Babylonian military officers, outfitted in striking red uniforms.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 15, 'Handsome belts encircled their waists, and flowing turbans crowned their heads. They were dressed like chariot officers from the land of Babylonia.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 16, 'When she saw these paintings, she longed to give herself to them, so she sent messengers to Babylonia to invite them to come to her.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 17, 'So they came and committed adultery with her, defiling her in the bed of love. But later, she became disgusted with them and broke off their relationship.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 18, '"So I became disgusted with Oholibah, just as I was with her sister, because she flaunted herself before them and gave herself to satisfy their lusts.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 19, 'But that didn''t bother her. She turned to even greater prostitution, remembering her youth when she was a prostitute in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 20, 'She lusted after lovers whose attentions were gross and bestial.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 21, 'And so, Oholibah, you celebrated your former days as a young girl in Egypt, when you first allowed yourself to be fondled and caressed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 22, '"Therefore, Oholibah, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will send your lovers against you--those very nations from which you turned away in disgust.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 23, 'For the Babylonians will come with all the Chaldeans from Pekod and Shoa and Koa. And all the Assyrians will come with them--handsome young captains, commanders, chariot officers, and other high-ranking officers, riding their horses.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 24, 'They will all come against you from the north with chariots, wagons, and a great army fully prepared for attack. They will take up positions on every side, surrounding you with men armed for battle. And I will hand you over to them so they can do with you as they please.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 25, 'I will turn my jealous anger against you, and they will deal furiously with you. They will cut off your nose and ears, and any survivors will then be slaughtered by the sword. Your children will be taken away as captives, and everything that is left will be burned.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 26, 'They will strip you of your beautiful clothes and jewels.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 27, 'In this way, I will put a stop to the lewdness and prostitution you brought from Egypt. You will never again cast longing eyes on those things or fondly remember your time in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 28, '"For this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will surely hand you over to your enemies, to those you loathe.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 29, 'They will deal with you in hatred and rob you of all you own, leaving you naked and bare. The shame of your prostitution will be exposed to all the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 30, 'You brought all this on yourself by prostituting yourself to other nations, defiling yourself with all their idols.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 31, 'Because you have followed in your sister''s footsteps, I will punish you with the same terrors that destroyed her.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 32, '"Yes, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: You will drink from the same cup of terror as your sister--a cup that is large and deep. And all the world will mock and scorn you in your desolation.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 33, 'You will reel like a drunkard beneath the awful blows of sorrow and distress, just as your sister Samaria did.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 34, 'In deep anguish you will drain that cup of terror to the very bottom. Then you will smash it to pieces and beat your breast in anguish. For I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 35, 'And because you have forgotten me and turned your back on me, says the Sovereign LORD, you must bear the consequences of all your lewdness and prostitution."', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 36, 'The LORD said to me, "Son of man, you must accuse Oholah and Oholibah of all their awful deeds.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 37, 'They have committed both adultery and murder--adultery by worshiping idols and murder by burning their children as sacrifices on their altars.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 38, 'Then after doing these terrible things, they defiled my Temple and violated my Sabbath day!', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 39, 'On the very day that they murdered their children in front of their idols, they boldly came into my Temple to worship! They came in and defiled my house!', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 40, '"You sisters sent messengers to distant lands to get men. Then when they arrived, you bathed yourselves, painted your eyelids, and put on your finest jewels for them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 41, 'You sat with them on a beautifully embroidered couch and put my incense and my oil on a table that was spread before you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 42, 'From your room came the sound of many men carousing. They were lustful men and drunkards from the wilderness, who put bracelets on your wrists and beautiful crowns on your heads.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 43, 'Then I said, `If they really want to sleep with worn-out, old prostitutes like these, let them!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 44, 'And that is what they did. They slept with Oholah and Oholibah, these shameless prostitutes, with all the zest of lustful young men.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 45, 'But righteous people will judge these sister cities for what they really are--adulteresses and murderers. They will sentence them to all the punishment they deserve.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 46, '"Now this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Bring an army against them and hand them over to be terrorized and plundered.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 47, 'For their enemies will stone them and kill them with swords. They will butcher their sons and daughters and burn their homes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 48, 'In this way, I will put an end to lewdness and idolatry in the land, and my judgment will be a warning to others not to follow their wicked example.', 'NLT'),
(30, 23, 49, 'You will be fully repaid for all your prostitution--your worship of idols. Yes, you will suffer the full penalty! Then you will know that I am the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 1, 'On January 15, during the ninth year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 2, '"Son of man, write down today''s date, because on this very day the king of Babylon is beginning his attack against Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 3, 'Then show these rebels an illustration; give them a message from the Sovereign LORD. Put a pot of water on the fire to boil.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 4, 'Fill it with choice meat--the rump and the shoulder and all the most tender cuts.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 5, 'Use only the best sheep from the flock and heap fuel on the fire beneath the pot. Bring the pot to a boil, and cook the bones along with the meat.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 6, '"Now this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Destruction is certain for Jerusalem, the city of murderers! She is a pot filled with corruption. So take the meat out chunk by chunk in whatever order it comes,', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 7, 'for her wickedness is evident to all. She murders boldly, leaving blood on the rocks for all to see. She doesn''t even try to cover it!', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 8, 'So I will splash her blood on a rock as an open expression of my anger and vengeance against her.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 9, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Destruction is certain for Jerusalem, the city of murderers! I myself will pile up the fuel beneath her.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 10, 'Yes, heap on the wood! Let the fire roar to make the pot boil. Cook the meat well with many spices. Then empty the pot and burn the bones.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 11, 'Now set the empty pot on the coals to scorch away the filth and corruption.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 12, 'But it''s hopeless; the corruption remains. So throw it into the fire!', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 13, 'It is the filth and corruption of your lewdness and idolatry. And now, because I tried to cleanse you but you refused, you will remain filthy until my fury against you has been satisfied.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 14, 'I, the LORD, have spoken! The time has come and I won''t hold back; I will not change my mind. You will be judged on the basis of all your wicked actions, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 15, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 16, '"Son of man, I am going to take away your dearest treasure. Suddenly she will die. Yet you must not show any sorrow. Do not weep; let there be no tears.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 17, 'You may sigh but only quietly. Let there be no wailing at her grave. Do not uncover your head or take off your sandals. Do not perform the rituals of mourning or accept any food brought to you by consoling friends."', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 18, 'So I proclaimed this to the people the next morning, and in the evening my wife died. The next morning I did everything I had been told to do.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 19, 'Then the people asked, "What does all this mean? What are you trying to tell us?"', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 20, 'So I said to them, "A message came to me from the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 21, 'and I was told to give this message to the people of Israel. This is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will desecrate my Temple, the source of your security and pride. Your sons and daughters in Judea will be slaughtered by the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 22, 'Then you will do as Ezekiel has done. You will not mourn in public or console yourselves by eating the food brought to you by sympathetic friends.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 23, 'Your heads must remain covered, and your sandals must not be taken off. You will not mourn or weep, but you will waste away because of your sins. You will mourn privately for all the evil you have done.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 24, 'Ezekiel is an example for you to follow; you will do as he has done. And when that time comes, you will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 25, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Son of man, on the day I take away their stronghold--their joy and glory, their heart''s desire, their dearest treasure--I will also take away their sons and daughters.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 26, 'And on that day a refugee from Jerusalem will come to you in Babylon and tell you what has happened.', 'NLT'),
(30, 24, 27, 'And when he arrives, your voice will suddenly return so you can talk to him, and you will be a symbol for these people. Then they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 2, '"Son of man, look toward the land of Ammon and prophesy against its people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 3, 'Give the Ammonites this message from the Sovereign LORD: Hear the word of the Sovereign LORD! Because you scoffed when my Temple was desecrated, mocked Israel in her desolation, and laughed at Judah as she went away into exile,', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 4, 'I will allow nomads from the eastern deserts to overrun your country. They will set up their camps among you and pitch their tents on your land. They will harvest all your fruit and steal your livestock.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 5, 'And I will turn the city of Rabbah into a pasture for camels, and all the land of the Ammonites into an enclosure for sheep. Then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 6, '"And the Sovereign LORD says: Because you clapped and stamped and cheered with glee at the destruction of my people,', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 7, 'I will lift up my fist against you. I will give you as plunder to many nations. I will cut you off from being a nation and destroy you completely. Then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 8, '"And the Sovereign LORD says: Because the people of Moab have said that Judah is just like all the other nations,', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 9, 'I will open up their eastern flank and wipe out their glorious frontier cities--Beth-jeshimoth, Baal-meon, and Kiriathaim.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 10, 'And I will hand Moab over to nomads from the eastern deserts, just as I handed over Ammon. Yes, the Ammonites will no longer be counted among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 11, 'And in the same way, I will bring my judgment down on the Moabites. Then they will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 12, '"And the Sovereign LORD says: The people of Edom have sinned greatly by avenging themselves against the people of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 13, 'Therefore, says the Sovereign LORD, I will raise my fist of judgment against Edom. I will wipe out their people, cattle, and flocks with the sword. I will make a wasteland of everything from Teman to Dedan.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 14, 'By the hand of my people of Israel, I will accomplish this. They will carry out my furious vengeance, and Edom will know it is from me. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 15, '"And the Sovereign LORD says: The people of Philistia have acted against Judah out of revenge and long-standing contempt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 16, 'Therefore, says the Sovereign LORD, I will raise my fist of judgment against the land of the Philistines. I will wipe out the Kerethites and utterly destroy the people who live by the sea.', 'NLT'),
(30, 25, 17, 'I will execute terrible vengeance against them to rebuke them for what they have done. And when I have inflicted my revenge, then they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 1, 'On February 3, during the twelfth year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 2, '"Son of man, Tyre has rejoiced over the fall of Jerusalem, saying, `Ha! She who controlled the rich trade routes to the east has been broken, and I am the heir! Because she has been destroyed, I will become wealthy!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 3, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I am your enemy, O Tyre, and I will bring many nations against you, like the waves of the sea crashing against your shoreline.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 4, 'They will destroy the walls of Tyre and tear down its towers. I will scrape away its soil and make it a bare rock!', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 5, 'The island of Tyre will become uninhabited. It will be a place for fishermen to spread their nets, for I have spoken, says the Sovereign LORD. Tyre will become the prey of many nations,', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 6, 'and its mainland villages will be destroyed by the sword. Then they will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 7, '"For the Sovereign LORD says: I will bring King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon--the king of kings from the north--against Tyre with his cavalry, chariots, and great army.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 8, 'First he will destroy your mainland villages. Then he will attack you by building a siege wall, constructing a ramp, and raising a roof of shields against you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 9, 'He will pound your walls with battering rams and demolish your towers with sledgehammers.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 10, 'The hooves of his cavalry will choke the city with dust, and your walls will shake as the horses gallop through your broken gates, pulling chariots behind them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 11, 'His horsemen will trample every street in the city. They will butcher your people, and your famous pillars will topple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 12, '"They will plunder all your riches and merchandise and break down your walls. They will destroy your lovely homes and dump your stones and timbers and even your dust into the sea.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 13, 'I will stop the music of your songs. No more will the sound of harps be heard among your people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 14, 'I will make your island a bare rock, a place for fishermen to spread their nets. You will never be rebuilt, for I, the LORD, have spoken! This is the word of the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 15, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says to Tyre: The whole coastline will tremble at the sound of your fall, as the screams of the wounded echo in the continuing slaughter.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 16, 'All the seaport rulers will step down from their thrones and take off their royal robes and beautiful clothing. They will sit on the ground trembling with horror at what they have seen.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 17, 'Then they will wail for you, singing this funeral song: `O famous island city, once ruler of the sea, how you have been destroyed! Your people, with their naval power, once spread fear around the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 18, 'Now the coastlands tremble at your fall. The islands are dismayed as you pass away.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 19, '"For the Sovereign LORD says: I will make Tyre an uninhabited ruin. You will sink beneath the terrible waves of enemy attack. Great seas will swallow you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 20, 'I will send you to the pit to lie there with those who descended there long ago. Your city will lie in ruins, buried beneath the earth, like those in the pit who have entered the world of the dead. Never again will you be given a position of respect here in the land of the living.', 'NLT'),
(30, 26, 21, 'I will bring you to a terrible end, and you will be no more. You will be looked for, but you will never be found. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 2, '"Son of man, sing a funeral song for Tyre,', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 3, 'that mighty gateway to the sea, the trading center of the world. Give Tyre this message from the Sovereign LORD: You claimed, O Tyre, to be perfect in beauty.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 4, 'You extended your boundaries into the sea. Your builders made you glorious!', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 5, 'You were like a great ship built of the finest cypress from Senir. They took a cedar from Lebanon to make a mast for you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 6, 'They carved oars for you from the oaks of Bashan. They made your deck of pine wood, brought from the southern coasts of Cyprus. Then they inlaid it with ivory.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 7, 'Your sails were made of Egypt''s finest linen, and they flew as a banner above you. You stood beneath blue and purple awnings made bright with dyes from the coasts of Elishah.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 8, '"Your oarsmen came from Sidon and Arvad; your helmsmen were skilled men from Tyre itself.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 9, 'Wise old craftsmen from Gebal did all the caulking. Ships came with goods from every land to barter for your trade.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 10, 'Men from distant Persia, Lydia, and Libya served in your great army. They hung their shields and helmets on your walls, giving you great honor.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 11, 'Men from Arvad and from Helech stood on your walls as sentinels. Your towers were manned by men from Gammad. Their shields hung on your walls, perfecting your splendor.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 12, '"Tarshish was your agent, trading your wares in exchange for silver, iron, tin, and lead.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 13, 'Merchants from Greece, Tubal, and Meshech brought slaves and bronze dishes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 14, 'From Togarmah came riding horses, chariot horses, and mules. All these things were exchanged for your manufactured goods.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 15, 'Merchants came to you from Dedan. Numerous coastlands were your captive markets; they brought payment in ivory tusks and ebony wood.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 16, '"Aram sent merchants to buy your wares. They traded turquoise, purple dyes, embroidery, fine linen, and jewelry of coral and rubies.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 17, 'Judah and Israel traded for your wares, offering wheat from Minnith, early figs, honey, oil, and balm.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 18, 'Damascus traded for your rich variety of goods, bringing wine from Helbon and white wool from Zahar.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 19, 'Greeks from Uzal came to trade for your merchandise. Wrought iron, cassia, and calamus were bartered for your wares.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 20, 'Dedan traded their expensive saddle blankets with you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 21, '"The Arabians and the princes of Kedar brought lambs and rams and goats in trade for your goods.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 22, 'The merchants of Sheba and Raamah came with all kinds of spices, jewels, and gold in exchange for your wares.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 23, 'Haran, Canneh, Eden, Sheba, Asshur, and Kilmad came with their merchandise, too.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 24, 'They brought choice fabrics to trade--blue cloth, embroidery, and many-colored carpets bound with cords and made secure.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 25, 'The ships of Tarshish were your ocean caravans. Your island warehouse was filled to the brim!', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 26, '"But look! Your oarsmen are rowing your ship of state into a hurricane! Your mighty vessel flounders in the heavy eastern gale. You are shipwrecked in the heart of the sea!', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 27, 'Everything is lost--your riches and wares, your sailors and helmsmen, your ship builders, merchants, and warriors. On that day of vast ruin, everyone on board sinks into the depths of the sea.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 28, '"Your cities by the sea tremble as your helmsmen cry out in terror.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 29, 'All the oarsmen abandon their ships; the sailors and helmsmen come to stand on the shore.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 30, 'They weep bitterly as they throw dust on their heads and roll in ashes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 31, 'They shave their heads in grief because of you and dress themselves in sackcloth. They weep for you with bitter anguish and deep mourning.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 32, 'As they wail and mourn, they sing this sad funeral song: `Was there ever such a city as Tyre, now silent at the bottom of the sea?', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 33, 'The merchandise you traded satisfied the needs of many nations. Kings at the ends of the earth were enriched by your trade.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 34, 'Now you are a wrecked ship, broken at the bottom of the sea. All your merchandise and your crew have passed away with you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 35, 'All who live along the coastlands are appalled at your terrible fate. Their kings are filled with horror and look on with twisted faces.', 'NLT'),
(30, 27, 36, 'The merchants of the nations shake their heads at the sight of you, for you have come to a horrible end and will be no more.''"', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 2, '"Son of man, give the prince of Tyre this message from the Sovereign LORD: In your great pride you claim, `I am a god! I sit on a divine throne in the heart of the sea.'' But you are only a man and not a god, though you boast that you are like a god.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 3, 'You regard yourself as wiser than Daniel and think no secret is hidden from you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 4, 'With your wisdom and understanding you have amassed great wealth--gold and silver for your treasuries.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 5, 'Yes, your wisdom has made you very rich, and your riches have made you very proud.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 6, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Because you think you are as wise as a god,', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 7, 'I will bring against you an enemy army, the terror of the nations. They will suddenly draw their swords against your marvelous wisdom and defile your splendor!', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 8, 'They will bring you down to the pit, and you will die there on your island home in the heart of the sea, pierced with many wounds.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 9, 'Will you then boast, `I am a god!'' to those who kill you? To them you will be no god but merely a man!', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 10, 'You will die like an outcast at the hands of foreigners. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 11, 'Then this further message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 12, '"Son of man, weep for the king of Tyre. Give him this message from the Sovereign LORD: You were the perfection of wisdom and beauty.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 13, 'You were in Eden, the garden of God. Your clothing was adorned with every precious stone--red carnelian, chrysolite, white moonstone, beryl, onyx, jasper, sapphire, turquoise, and emerald--all beautifully crafted for you and set in the finest gold. They were given to you on the day you were created.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 14, 'I ordained and anointed you as the mighty angelic guardian. You had access to the holy mountain of God and walked among the stones of fire.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 15, '"You were blameless in all you did from the day you were created until the day evil was found in you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 16, 'Your great wealth filled you with violence, and you sinned. So I banished you from the mountain of God. I expelled you, O mighty guardian, from your place among the stones of fire.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 17, 'Your heart was filled with pride because of all your beauty. You corrupted your wisdom for the sake of your splendor. So I threw you to the earth and exposed you to the curious gaze of kings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 18, 'You defiled your sanctuaries with your many sins and your dishonest trade. So I brought fire from within you, and it consumed you. I let it burn you to ashes on the ground in the sight of all who were watching.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 19, 'All who knew you are appalled at your fate. You have come to a terrible end, and you are no more."', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 20, 'Then another message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 21, '"Son of man, look toward the city of Sidon and prophesy against it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 22, 'Give the people of Sidon this message from the Sovereign LORD: I am your enemy, O Sidon, and I will reveal my glory by what happens to you. When I bring judgment against you and reveal my holiness among you, everyone watching will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 23, 'I will send a plague against you, and blood will be spilled in your streets. The attack will come from every direction, and your people will lie slaughtered within your walls. Then everyone will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 24, 'No longer will Israel''s scornful neighbors prick and tear at her like thorns and briers. For then they will know that I am the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 25, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: The people of Israel will again live in their own land, the land I gave my servant Jacob. For I will gather them from the distant lands where I have scattered them. I will reveal to the nations of the world my holiness among my people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 28, 26, 'They will live safely in Israel and build their homes and plant their vineyards. And when I punish the neighboring nations that treated them with contempt, they will know that I am the LORD their God."', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 1, 'On January 7, during the tenth year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 2, '"Son of man, turn toward Egypt and prophesy against Pharaoh the king and all the people of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 3, 'Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: I am your enemy, O Pharaoh, king of Egypt--you great monster, lurking in the streams of the Nile. For you have said, `The Nile River is mine; I made it for myself!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 4, 'I will put hooks in your jaws and drag you out on the land with fish sticking to your scales.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 5, 'I will leave you and all your fish stranded in the desert to die. You will lie unburied on the open ground, for I have given you as food to the wild animals and birds.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 6, '"All the people of Egypt will discover that I am the LORD, for you collapsed like a reed when Israel looked to you for help.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 7, 'Israel leaned on you, but like a cracked staff, you splintered and stabbed her in the armpit. When she put her weight on you, you gave way, and her back was thrown out of joint.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 8, 'So now the Sovereign LORD says: I will bring an army against you, O Egypt, and destroy both people and animals.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 9, 'The land of Egypt will become a desolate wasteland, and the Egyptians will know that I am the LORD. "Because you said, `The Nile River is mine; I made it,''', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 10, 'I am now the enemy of both you and your river. I will utterly destroy the land of Egypt, from Migdol to Aswan, as far south as the border of Ethiopia.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 11, 'For forty years not a soul will pass that way, neither people nor animals. It will be completely uninhabited.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 12, 'I will make Egypt desolate, and it will be surrounded by other desolate nations. Its cities will be empty and desolate for forty years, surrounded by other desolate cities. I will scatter the Egyptians to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 13, '"But the Sovereign LORD also says: At the end of the forty years I will bring the Egyptians home again from the nations to which they have been scattered.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 14, 'I will restore the prosperity of Egypt and bring its people back to the land of Pathros in southern Egypt from which they came. But Egypt will remain an unimportant, minor kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 15, 'It will be the lowliest of all the nations, never again great enough to rise above its neighbors.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 16, '"Then Israel will no longer be tempted to trust in Egypt for help. Egypt''s shattered condition will remind Israel of how sinful she was to trust Egypt in earlier days. Then Israel will know that I alone am the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 17, 'On April 26, during the twenty-seventh year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 18, '"Son of man, the army of King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon fought so hard against Tyre that the warriors'' heads were rubbed bare and their shoulders were raw and blistered. Yet Nebuchadnezzar and his army won no plunder to compensate them for all their work.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 19, 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will give the land of Egypt to Nebuchadnezzar, king of Babylon. He will carry off their wealth, plundering everything they have to pay his army.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 20, 'Yes, I have given him the land of Egypt as a reward for his work, says the Sovereign LORD, because he was working for me when he destroyed Tyre.', 'NLT'),
(30, 29, 21, '"And the day will come when I will cause the ancient glory of Israel to revive, and then at last your words will be respected. Then they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 1, 'This is another message that came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 2, '"Son of man, prophesy and give this message from the Sovereign LORD: Weep,', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 3, 'for the terrible day is almost here--the day of the LORD! It is a day of clouds and gloom, a day of despair for the nations!', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 4, 'A sword will come against Egypt, and those who are slaughtered will cover the ground. Their wealth will be carried away and their foundations destroyed. The land of Ethiopia will be ravished.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 5, 'Ethiopia, Libya, Lydia, and Arabia, with all their other allies, will be destroyed in that war.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 6, '"For this is what the LORD says: All of Egypt''s allies will fall, and the pride of their power will end. From Migdol to Aswan they will be slaughtered by the sword, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 7, 'Egypt will be desolate, surrounded by desolate nations, and its cities will be in ruins, surrounded by other ruined cities.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 8, 'And the people of Egypt will know that I am the LORD when I have set Egypt on fire and destroyed all their allies.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 9, 'At that time I will send swift messengers in ships to terrify the complacent Ethiopians. Great panic will come upon them on that day of Egypt''s certain destruction.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 10, '"For this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Through King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon, I will destroy the hordes of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 11, 'He and his armies--ruthless among the nations--have been sent to demolish the land. They will make war against Egypt until slaughtered Egyptians cover the ground.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 12, 'I will dry up the Nile River and hand the land over to wicked men. I will destroy the land of Egypt and everything in it, using foreigners to do it. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 13, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will smash the idols of Egypt and the images at Memphis. There will be no rulers left in Egypt; anarchy will prevail throughout the land!', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 14, 'I will destroy Pathros, Zoan, and Thebes, and they will lie in ruins, burned up by my anger.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 15, 'I will pour out my fury on Pelusium, the strongest fortress of Egypt, and I will stamp out the people of Thebes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 16, 'Yes, I will set fire to all Egypt! Pelusium will be racked with pain; Thebes will be torn apart; Memphis will live in constant terror.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 17, 'The young men of Heliopolis and Bubastis will die in battle, and the women will be taken away as slaves.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 18, 'When I come to break the proud strength of Egypt, it will be a dark day for Tahpanhes, too. A dark cloud will cover Tahpanhes, and its daughters will be led away as captives.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 19, 'And so I will greatly punish Egypt, and they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 20, 'On April 29, during the eleventh year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 21, '"Son of man, I have broken the arm of Pharaoh, the king of Egypt. His arm has not been put in a cast so that it may heal. Neither has it been bound up with a splint to make it strong enough to hold a sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 22, 'Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I am the enemy of Pharaoh, the king of Egypt! I will break both of his arms--the good arm along with the broken one--and I will make his sword clatter to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 23, 'I will scatter the Egyptians to many lands throughout the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 24, 'I will strengthen the arms of Babylon''s king and put my sword in his hand. But I will break the arms of Pharaoh, king of Egypt, and he will lie there mortally wounded, groaning in pain.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 25, 'I will strengthen the arms of the king of Babylon, while the arms of Pharaoh fall useless to his sides. And when I put my sword in the hand of Babylon''s king and he brings it against the land of Egypt, Egypt will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 30, 26, 'I will scatter the Egyptians among the nations. Then they will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 1, 'On June 21, during the eleventh year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 2, '"Son of man, give this message to Pharaoh, king of Egypt, and all his people: To whom would you compare your greatness?', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 3, 'You are as Assyria was--a great and mighty nation. Assyria, too, was once like a cedar of Lebanon, full of thick branches that cast deep forest shade with its top high among the clouds.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 4, 'Deep springs watered it and helped it to grow tall and luxuriant. The water was so abundant that there was enough for all the trees nearby.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 5, 'This great tree towered above all the other trees around it. It prospered and grew long thick branches because of all the water at its roots.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 6, 'The birds nested in its branches, and in its shade all the wild animals gave birth to their young. All the great nations of the world lived in its shadow.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 7, 'It was strong and beautiful, for its roots went deep into abundant water.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 8, 'This tree became taller than any of the other cedars in the garden of God. No cypress had branches equal to it; no plane tree had boughs to compare. No tree in the garden of God came close to it in beauty.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 9, 'Because of the magnificence I gave this tree, it was the envy of all the other trees of Eden, the garden of God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 10, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Because it became proud and arrogant, and because it set itself so high above the others, reaching to the clouds,', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 11, 'I handed it over to a mighty nation that destroyed it as its wickedness deserved. I myself discarded it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 12, 'A foreign army--the terror of the nations--cut it down and left it fallen on the ground. Its branches were scattered across the mountains and valleys and ravines of the land. All those who lived beneath its shadow went away and left it lying there.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 13, 'The birds roosted on its fallen trunk, and the wild animals lay among its branches.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 14, 'Let no other nation proudly exult in its own prosperity, though it be higher than the clouds, for all are doomed. They will land in the pit along with all the proud people of the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 15, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: When Assyria went down into the grave, I made the deep places mourn, and I restrained the mighty waters. I clothed Lebanon in black and caused the trees of the field to wilt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 16, 'I made the nations shake with fear at the sound of its fall, for I sent it down to the grave with all the others like it. And all the other proud trees of Eden, the most beautiful and the best of Lebanon, the ones whose roots went deep into the water, were relieved to find it there with them in the pit.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 17, 'Its allies, too, were all destroyed and had passed away. They had gone down to the grave--all those nations that had lived in its shade.', 'NLT'),
(30, 31, 18, '"O Egypt, to which of the trees of Eden will you compare your strength and glory? You, too, will be brought down to the pit with all these other nations. You will lie there among the outcasts who have died by the sword. This will be the fate of Pharaoh and all his teeming hordes. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 1, 'On March 3, during the twelfth year of King Jehoiachin''s captivity, this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 2, '"Son of man, mourn for Pharaoh, king of Egypt, and give him this message: You think of yourself as a strong young lion among the nations, but you are really just a sea monster, heaving around in your own rivers, stirring up mud with your feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 3, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will send many people to catch you in my net and haul you out of the water.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 4, 'I will leave you stranded on the land to die. All the birds of the heavens will land on you, and the wild animals of the whole earth will gorge themselves on you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 5, 'I will cover the hills with your flesh and fill the valleys with your bones.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 6, 'I will drench the earth with your gushing blood all the way to the mountains, filling the ravines to the brim.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 7, 'When I blot you out, I will veil the heavens and darken the stars. I will cover the sun with a cloud, and the moon will not give you its light.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 8, 'Yes, I will bring darkness everywhere across your land. Even the brightest stars will become dark above you. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 9, '"And when I bring your shattered remains to distant nations that you have never seen, I will disturb many hearts.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 10, 'Yes, I will bring terror to many lands, and their kings will be terrified because of all I do to you. They will shudder in fear for their lives as I brandish my sword before them on the day of your fall.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 11, '"For this is what the Sovereign LORD says: The sword of the king of Babylon will come against you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 12, 'I will destroy you with the swords of mighty warriors--the terror of the nations. They will shatter the pride of Egypt, and all its hordes will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 13, 'I will destroy all your flocks and herds that graze beside the streams. Never again will people or animals disturb those waters with their feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 14, 'Then I will let the waters of Egypt become calm again, and they will flow as smoothly as olive oil, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 15, 'And when I destroy Egypt and wipe out everything you have and strike down all your people, then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 16, 'Yes, this is the funeral song they will sing for Egypt. Let all the nations mourn for Egypt and its hordes. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 17, 'On March 17, during the twelfth year, another message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 18, '"Son of man, weep for the hordes of Egypt and for the other mighty nations. For I will send them down to the world below in company with those who descend to the pit.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 19, 'Say to them, `O Egypt, are you lovelier than the other nations? No! So go down to the pit and lie there among the outcasts.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 20, 'The Egyptians will fall with the many who have died by the sword, for the sword is drawn against them. Egypt will be dragged away to its judgment.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 21, 'Down in the grave mighty leaders will mockingly welcome Egypt and its allies, saying, `They have come down; they lie among the outcasts, all victims of the sword.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 22, '"Assyria lies there surrounded by the graves of all its people, those who were slaughtered by the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 23, 'Their graves are in the depths of the pit, and they are surrounded by their allies. These mighty men who once struck terror in the hearts of people everywhere are now dead at the hands of their enemies.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 24, '"Elam lies there buried with its hordes who descended as outcasts to the world below. They terrorized the nations while they lived, but now they lie in the pit and share the humiliation of those who have gone to the world of the dead.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 25, 'They have a resting place among the slaughtered, surrounded by the graves of all their people. Yes, they terrorized the nations while they lived, but now they lie in shame in the pit, all of them outcasts, slaughtered by the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 26, '"Meshech and Tubal are there, surrounded by the graves of all their hordes. They once struck terror into the hearts of all people. But now they are outcasts, all victims of the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 27, 'They are not buried in honor like the fallen heroes of the outcasts, who went down to the grave with their weapons--their shields covering their bodies, and their swords beneath their heads. They brought terror to everyone while they were still alive.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 28, '"You too, Egypt, will lie crushed and broken among the outcasts, all victims of the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 29, '"Edom is there with its kings and princes. Mighty as they were, they also lie among those killed by the sword, with the outcasts who have gone down to the pit.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 30, 'All the princes of the north and the Sidonians are there, all victims of the sword. Once a terror, they now lie there in shame. They lie there as outcasts with all the other dead who have descended to the pit.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 31, '"When Pharaoh arrives, he will be relieved to find that he is not alone in having his entire army killed, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 32, 32, 'For I have caused my terror to fall upon all the living. And Pharaoh and his hordes will lie there among the outcasts who have died by the sword. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 1, 'Once again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 2, '"Son of man, give your people this message: When I bring an army against a country, the people of that land choose a watchman.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 3, 'When the watchman sees the enemy coming, he blows the alarm to warn the people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 4, 'Then if those who hear the alarm refuse to take action--well, it is their own fault if they die.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 5, 'They heard the warning but wouldn''t listen, so the responsibility is theirs. If they had listened to the warning, they could have saved their lives.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 6, 'But if the watchman sees the enemy coming and doesn''t sound the alarm to warn the people, he is responsible for their deaths. They will die in their sins, but I will hold the watchman accountable.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 7, '"Now, son of man, I am making you a watchman for the people of Israel. Therefore, listen to what I say and warn them for me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 8, 'If I announce that some wicked people are sure to die and you fail to warn them about changing their ways, then they will die in their sins, but I will hold you responsible for their deaths.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 9, 'But if you warn them to repent and they don''t repent, they will die in their sins, but you will not be held responsible.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 10, '"Son of man, give the people of Israel this message: You are saying, `Our sins are heavy upon us; we are wasting away! How can we survive?''', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 11, 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, I take no pleasure in the death of wicked people. I only want them to turn from their wicked ways so they can live. Turn! Turn from your wickedness, O people of Israel! Why should you die?', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 12, '"Son of man, give your people this message: The good works of righteous people will not save them if they turn to sin, nor will the sins of evil people destroy them if they repent and turn from their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 13, 'When I tell righteous people that they will live, but then they sin, expecting their past righteousness to save them, then none of their good deeds will be remembered. I will destroy them for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 14, 'And suppose I tell some wicked people that they will surely die, but then they turn from their sins and do what is just and right.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 15, 'For instance, they might give back a borrower''s pledge, return what they have stolen, and obey my life-giving laws, no longer doing what is evil. If they do this, then they will surely live and not die.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 16, 'None of their past sins will be brought up again, for they have done what is just and right, and they will surely live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 17, '"Your people are saying, `The Lord is not just,'' but it is they who are not just.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 18, 'For again I say, when righteous people turn to evil, they will die.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 19, 'But if wicked people turn from their wickedness and do what is just and right, they will live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 20, 'O people of Israel, you are saying, `The Lord is not just.'' But I will judge each of you according to your deeds."', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 21, 'On January 8, during the twelfth year of our captivity, a man who had escaped from Jerusalem came to me and said, "The city has fallen!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 22, 'The previous evening the LORD had taken hold of me and opened my mouth, so I would be able to speak when this man arrived the next morning.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 23, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 24, '"Son of man, the scattered remnants of Judah living among the ruined cities keep saying, `Abraham was only one man, and yet he gained possession of the entire land! We are many; surely the land should be given to us as a possession.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 25, 'Now give these people this message from the Sovereign LORD: You eat meat with blood in it, you worship idols, and you murder the innocent. Do you really think the land should be yours?', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 26, 'Murderers! Idolaters! Adulterers! Should the land belong to you?', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 27, '"Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: As surely as I live, those living in the ruins will die by the sword. Those living in the open fields will be eaten by wild animals. Those hiding in the forts and caves will die of disease.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 28, 'I will destroy the land and demolish her pride. Her arrogant power will come to an end. The mountains of Israel will be so ruined that no one will even travel through them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 29, 'When I have ruined the land because of their disgusting sins, then they will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 30, '"Son of man, your people are whispering behind your back. They talk about you in their houses and whisper about you at the doors, saying, `Come on, let''s have some fun! Let''s go hear the prophet tell us what the LORD is saying!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 31, 'So they come pretending to be sincere and sit before you listening. But they have no intention of doing what I tell them. They express love with their mouths, but their hearts seek only after money.', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 32, 'You are very entertaining to them, like someone who sings love songs with a beautiful voice or plays fine music on an instrument. They hear what you say, but they don''t do it!', 'NLT'),
(30, 33, 33, 'But when all these terrible things happen to them--as they certainly will--then they will know a prophet has been among them."', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 1, 'Then this message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 2, '"Son of man, prophesy against the shepherds, the leaders of Israel. Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: Destruction is certain for you shepherds who feed yourselves instead of your flocks. Shouldn''t shepherds feed their sheep?', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 3, 'You drink the milk, wear the wool, and butcher the best animals, but you let your flocks starve.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 4, 'You have not taken care of the weak. You have not tended the sick or bound up the broken bones. You have not gone looking for those who have wandered away and are lost. Instead, you have ruled them with force and cruelty.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 5, 'So my sheep have been scattered without a shepherd. They are easy prey for any wild animal.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 6, 'They have wandered through the mountains and hills, across the face of the earth, yet no one has gone to search for them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 7, '"Therefore, you shepherds, hear the word of the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 8, 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, you abandoned my flock and left them to be attacked by every wild animal. Though you were my shepherds, you didn''t search for my sheep when they were lost. You took care of yourselves and left the sheep to starve.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 9, 'Therefore, you shepherds, hear the word of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 10, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: I now consider these shepherds my enemies, and I will hold them responsible for what has happened to my flock. I will take away their right to feed the flock, along with their right to feed themselves. I will rescue my flock from their mouths; the sheep will no longer be their prey.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 11, '"For this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I myself will search and find my sheep.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 12, 'I will be like a shepherd looking for his scattered flock. I will find my sheep and rescue them from all the places to which they were scattered on that dark and cloudy day.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 13, 'I will bring them back home to their own land of Israel from among the peoples and nations. I will feed them on the mountains of Israel and by the rivers in all the places where people live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 14, 'Yes, I will give them good pastureland on the high hills of Israel. There they will lie down in pleasant places and feed in lush mountain pastures.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 15, 'I myself will tend my sheep and cause them to lie down in peace, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 16, 'I will search for my lost ones who strayed away, and I will bring them safely home again. I will bind up the injured and strengthen the weak. But I will destroy those who are fat and powerful. I will feed them, yes--feed them justice!', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 17, '"And as for you, my flock, my people, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will judge between one sheep and another, separating the sheep from the goats.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 18, 'Is it not enough for you to keep the best of the pastures for yourselves? Must you also trample down the rest? Is it not enough for you to take the best water for yourselves? Must you also muddy the rest with your feet?', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 19, 'All that is left for my flock to eat is what you have trampled down. All they have to drink is water that you have fouled.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 20, '"Therefore, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will surely judge between the fat sheep and the scrawny sheep.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 21, 'For you fat sheep push and butt and crowd my sick and hungry flock until they are scattered to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 22, 'So I will rescue my flock, and they will no longer be abused and destroyed. And I will judge between one sheep and another.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 23, 'And I will set one shepherd over them, even my servant David. He will feed them and be a shepherd to them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 24, 'And I, the LORD, will be their God, and my servant David will be a prince among my people. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 25, '"I will make a covenant of peace with them and drive away the dangerous animals from the land. Then my people will be able to camp safely in the wildest places and sleep in the woods without fear.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 26, 'I will cause my people and their homes around my holy hill to be a blessing. And I will send showers, showers of blessings, which will come just when they are needed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 27, 'The orchards and fields of my people will yield bumper crops, and everyone will live in safety. When I have broken their chains of slavery and rescued them from those who enslaved them, then they will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 28, 'They will no longer be prey for other nations, and wild animals will no longer attack them. They will live in safety, and no one will make them afraid.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 29, '"And I will give them a land famous for its crops, so my people will never again go hungry or be shamed by the scorn of foreign nations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 30, 'In this way, they will know that I, the LORD their God, am with them. And they will know that they, the people of Israel, are my people, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 34, 31, 'You are my flock, the sheep of my pasture. You are my people, and I am your God, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 1, 'Again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 2, '"Son of man, turn toward Mount Seir, and prophesy against its people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 3, 'Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: I am your enemy, O Mount Seir, and I will raise my fist against you to destroy you completely.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 4, 'I will demolish your cities and make you desolate, and then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 5, 'Your continual hatred for the people of Israel led you to butcher them when they were helpless, when I had already punished them for all their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 6, 'As surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, since you show no distaste for blood, I will give you a bloodbath of your own. Your turn has come!', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 7, 'I will make Mount Seir utterly desolate, killing off all who try to escape and any who return.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 8, 'I will fill your mountains with the dead. Your hills, your valleys, and your streams will be filled with people slaughtered by the sword.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 9, 'I will make you desolate forever. Your cities will never be rebuilt. Then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 10, '"For you said, `The lands of Israel and Judah will be ours. We will take possession of them. What do we care that the LORD is there!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 11, 'Therefore, as surely as I live, says the Sovereign LORD, I will pay back your angry deeds with mine. I will punish you for all your acts of anger, envy, and hatred. And I will bring honor to my name by what I do to you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 12, 'Then you will know that I, the LORD, have heard every contemptuous word you spoke against the mountains of Israel. For you said, `They have been destroyed; they have been given to us as food to eat!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 13, 'In saying that, you boasted proudly against me, and I have heard it all!', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 14, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: The whole world will rejoice when I make you desolate.', 'NLT'),
(30, 35, 15, 'You rejoiced at the desolation of Israel''s inheritance. Now I will rejoice at yours! You will be wiped out, you people of Mount Seir and all who live in Edom! Then you will know that I am the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 1, '"Son of man, prophesy to Israel''s mountains. Give them this message: O mountains of Israel, hear the word of the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 2, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Your enemies have taunted you, saying, `Aha! Now the ancient heights belong to us!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 3, 'Therefore, son of man, give the mountains of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD: Your enemies have attacked you from all directions, and now you are possessed by many nations. You are the object of much mocking and slander.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 4, 'Therefore, O mountains of Israel, hear the word of the Sovereign LORD. He speaks to the hills and mountains, ravines and valleys, and to ruined wastes and long-deserted cities that have been destroyed and mocked by foreign nations everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 5, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: My jealous anger is on fire against these nations, especially Edom, because they have shown utter contempt for me by gleefully taking my land for themselves as plunder.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 6, '"Therefore, prophesy to the hills and mountains, the ravines and valleys of Israel. Give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: I am full of fury because you have suffered shame before the surrounding nations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 7, 'Therefore, says the Sovereign LORD, I have raised my hand and sworn an oath that those nations will soon have their turn at suffering shame.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 8, 'But the mountains of Israel will produce heavy crops of fruit to prepare for my people''s return--and they will be coming home again soon!', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 9, 'See, I am concerned for you, and I will come to help you. Your ground will be tilled and your crops planted.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 10, 'I will greatly increase the population of Israel, and the ruined cities will be rebuilt and filled with people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 11, 'Not only the people, but your flocks and herds will also greatly multiply. O mountains of Israel, I will bring people to live on you once again. I will make you even more prosperous than you were before. Then you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 12, 'I will cause my people to walk on you once again, and you will be their inheritance. You will never again devour their children.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 13, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Now the other nations taunt you, saying, `Israel is a land that devours her own people!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 14, 'But you will never again devour your people or bereave your nation, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 15, 'I will not allow those foreign nations to sneer at you, and you will no longer be shamed by them or cause your nation to fall, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 16, 'Then this further message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 17, '"Son of man, when the people of Israel were living in their own land, they defiled it by their evil deeds. To me their conduct was as filthy as a bloody rag.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 18, 'They polluted the land with murder and by worshiping idols, so I poured out my fury on them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 19, 'I scattered them to many lands to punish them for the evil way they had lived.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 20, 'But when they were scattered among the nations, they brought dishonor to my holy name. For the nations said, `These are the people of the LORD, and he couldn''t keep them safe in his own land!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 21, 'Then I was concerned for my holy name, which had been dishonored by my people throughout the world.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 22, '"Therefore, give the people of Israel this message from the Sovereign LORD: I am bringing you back again but not because you deserve it. I am doing it to protect my holy name, which you dishonored while you were scattered among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 23, 'I will show how holy my great name is--the name you dishonored among the nations. And when I reveal my holiness through you before their very eyes, says the Sovereign LORD, then the nations will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 24, 'For I will gather you up from all the nations and bring you home again to your land.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 25, '"Then I will sprinkle clean water on you, and you will be clean. Your filth will be washed away, and you will no longer worship idols.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 26, 'And I will give you a new heart with new and right desires, and I will put a new spirit in you. I will take out your stony heart of sin and give you a new, obedient heart.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 27, 'And I will put my Spirit in you so you will obey my laws and do whatever I command.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 28, '"And you will live in Israel, the land I gave your ancestors long ago. You will be my people, and I will be your God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 29, 'I will cleanse you of your filthy behavior. I will give you good crops, and I will abolish famine in the land.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 30, 'I will give you great harvests from your fruit trees and fields, and never again will the surrounding nations be able to scoff at your land for its famines.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 31, 'Then you will remember your past sins and hate yourselves for all the evil things you did.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 32, 'But remember, says the Sovereign LORD, I am not doing this because you deserve it. O my people of Israel, you should be utterly ashamed of all you have done!', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 33, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: When I cleanse you from your sins, I will bring people to live in your cities, and the ruins will be rebuilt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 34, 'The fields that used to lie empty and desolate--a shock to all who passed by--will again be farmed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 35, 'And when I bring you back, people will say, `This godforsaken land is now like Eden''s garden! The ruined cities now have strong walls, and they are filled with people!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 36, 'Then the nations all around--all those still left--will know that I, the LORD, rebuilt the ruins and planted lush crops in the wilderness. For I, the LORD, have promised this, and I will do it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 37, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: I am ready to hear Israel''s prayers for these blessings, and I am ready to grant them their requests.', 'NLT'),
(30, 36, 38, 'I will multiply them like the sacred flocks that fill Jerusalem''s streets at the time of her festivals. The ruined cities will be crowded with people once more, and everyone will know that I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 1, 'The LORD took hold of me, and I was carried away by the Spirit of the LORD to a valley filled with bones.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 2, 'He led me around among the old, dry bones that covered the valley floor. They were scattered everywhere across the ground.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 3, 'Then he asked me, "Son of man, can these bones become living people again?O Sovereign LORD," I replied, "you alone know the answer to that."', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 4, 'Then he said to me, "Speak to these bones and say, `Dry bones, listen to the word of the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 5, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Look! I am going to breathe into you and make you live again!', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 6, 'I will put flesh and muscles on you and cover you with skin. I will put breath into you, and you will come to life. Then you will know that I am the LORD.''"', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 7, 'So I spoke these words, just as he told me. Suddenly as I spoke, there was a rattling noise all across the valley. The bones of each body came together and attached themselves as they had been before.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 8, 'Then as I watched, muscles and flesh formed over the bones. Then skin formed to cover their bodies, but they still had no breath in them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 9, 'Then he said to me, "Speak to the winds and say: `This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Come, O breath, from the four winds! Breathe into these dead bodies so that they may live again.''"', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 10, 'So I spoke as he commanded me, and the wind entered the bodies, and they began to breathe. They all came to life and stood up on their feet--a great army of them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 11, 'Then he said to me, "Son of man, these bones represent the people of Israel. They are saying, `We have become old, dry bones--all hope is gone.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 12, 'Now give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: O my people, I will open your graves of exile and cause you to rise again. Then I will bring you back to the land of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 13, 'When this happens, O my people, you will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 14, 'I will put my Spirit in you, and you will live and return home to your own land. Then you will know that I am the LORD. You will see that I have done everything just as I promised. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 15, 'Again a message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 16, '"Son of man, take a stick and carve on it these words: `This stick represents Judah and its allied tribes.'' Then take another stick and carve these words on it: `This stick represents the northern tribes of Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 17, 'Now hold them together in your hand as one stick.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 18, 'When your people ask you what your actions mean,', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 19, 'say to them, `This is what the Sovereign LORD says: I will take the northern tribes and join them to Judah. I will make them one stick in my hand.''', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 20, 'Then hold out the sticks you have inscribed, so the people can see them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 21, 'And give them this message from the Sovereign LORD: I will gather the people of Israel from among the nations. I will bring them home to their own land from the places where they have been scattered.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 22, 'I will unify them into one nation in the land. One king will rule them all; no longer will they be divided into two nations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 23, 'They will stop polluting themselves with their detestable idols and other sins, for I will save them from their sinful backsliding. I will cleanse them. Then they will truly be my people, and I will be their God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 24, '"My servant David will be their king, and they will have only one shepherd. They will obey my regulations and keep my laws.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 25, 'They will live in the land of Israel where their ancestors lived, the land I gave my servant Jacob. They and their children and their grandchildren after them will live there forever, generation after generation. And my servant David will be their prince forever.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 26, 'And I will make a covenant of peace with them, an everlasting covenant. I will give them their land and multiply them, and I will put my Temple among them forever.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 27, 'I will make my home among them. I will be their God, and they will be my people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 37, 28, 'And since my Temple will remain among them forever, the nations will know that I, the LORD, have set Israel apart for myself to be holy."', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 1, 'This is another message that came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 2, '"Son of man, prophesy against Gog of the land of Magog, the prince who rules over the nations of Meshech and Tubal.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 3, 'Give him this message from the Sovereign LORD: Gog, I am your enemy!', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 4, 'I will turn you around and put hooks into your jaws to lead you out to your destruction. I will mobilize your troops and cavalry and make you a vast and mighty horde, all fully armed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 5, 'Persia, Ethiopia, and Libya will join you, too, with all their weapons.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 6, 'Gomer and all its hordes will also join you, along with the armies of Beth-togarmah from the distant north and many others.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 7, '"Get ready; be prepared! Keep all the armies around you mobilized, and take command of them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 8, 'A long time from now you will be called into action. In the distant future you will swoop down on the land of Israel, which will be lying in peace after her recovery from war and after the return of her people from many lands.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 9, 'You and all your allies--a vast and awesome horde--will roll down on them like a storm and cover the land like a cloud.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 10, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: At that time evil thoughts will come to your mind, and you will devise a wicked scheme.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 11, 'You will say, `Israel is an unprotected land filled with unwalled villages! I will march against her and destroy these people who live in such confidence!', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 12, 'I will go to those once-desolate cities that are again filled with people who have returned from exile in many nations. I will capture vast amounts of plunder and take many slaves, for the people are rich with cattle now, and they think the whole world revolves around them!''', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 13, 'But Sheba and Dedan and the merchants of Tarshish will ask, `Who are you to rob them of silver and gold? Who are you to drive away their cattle and seize their goods and make them poor?''', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 14, '"Therefore, son of man, prophesy against Gog. Give him this message from the Sovereign LORD: When my people are living in peace in their land, then you will rouse yourself.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 15, 'You will come from your homeland in the distant north with your vast cavalry and your mighty army,', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 16, 'and you will cover the land like a cloud. This will happen in the distant future. I will bring you against my land as everyone watches, and my holiness will be displayed by what happens to you. Then all the nations will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 17, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: You are the one I was talking about long ago, when I announced through Israel''s prophets that in future days I would bring you against my people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 18, 'But when Gog invades the land of Israel, says the Sovereign LORD, my fury will rise!', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 19, 'For in my jealousy and blazing anger, I promise a mighty shaking in the land of Israel on that day.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 20, 'All living things--all the fish, birds, animals, and people--will quake in terror at my presence. Mountains will be thrown down; cliffs will crumble; walls will fall to the earth.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 21, 'I will summon the sword against you throughout Israel, says the Sovereign LORD. Your men will turn against each other in mortal combat.', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 22, 'I will punish you and your hordes with disease and bloodshed; I will send torrential rain, hailstones, fire, and burning sulfur!', 'NLT'),
(30, 38, 23, 'Thus will I show my greatness and holiness, and I will make myself known to all the nations of the world. Then they will know that I am the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 1, '"Son of man, prophesy against Gog. Give him this message from the Sovereign LORD: I am your enemy, O Gog, ruler of the nations of Meshech and Tubal.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 2, 'I will turn you and drive you toward the mountains of Israel, bringing you from the distant north.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 3, 'I will knock your weapons from your hands and leave you helpless.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 4, 'You and all your vast hordes will die on the mountains. I will give you as food to the vultures and wild animals.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 5, 'You will fall in the open fields, for I have spoken, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 6, 'And I will rain down fire on Magog and on all your allies who live safely on the coasts. Then they will know that I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 7, '"Thus, I will make known my holy name among my people of Israel. I will not let it be desecrated anymore. And the nations, too, will know that I am the LORD, the Holy One of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 8, 'That day of judgment will come, says the Sovereign LORD. Everything will happen just as I have declared it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 9, '"Then the people in the towns of Israel will go out and pick up your small and large shields, bows and arrows, javelins and spears, and they will use them for fuel. There will be enough to last them seven years!', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 10, 'They will need nothing else for their fires. They won''t need to cut wood from the fields or forests, for these weapons will give them all they need. They will take plunder from those who planned to plunder them, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 11, '"And I will make a vast graveyard for Gog and his hordes in the Valley of the Travelers, east of the Dead Sea. The path of those who travel there will be blocked by this burial ground, and they will change the name of the place to the Valley of Gog''s Hordes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 12, 'It will take seven months for the people of Israel to cleanse the land by burying the bodies.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 13, 'Everyone in Israel will help, for it will be a glorious victory for Israel when I demonstrate my glory on that day, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 14, 'At the end of the seven months, special crews will be appointed to search the land for any skeletons and to bury them, so the land will be made clean again.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 15, 'Whenever some bones are found, a marker will be set up beside them so the burial crews will see them and take them to be buried in the Valley of Gog''s Hordes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 16, '(There will be a town there named Hamonah--which means `horde.'') And so the land will finally be cleansed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 17, '"And now, son of man, call all the birds and wild animals, says the Sovereign LORD. Say to them: Gather together for my great sacrificial feast. Come from far and near to the mountains of Israel, and there eat the flesh and drink the blood!', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 18, 'Eat the flesh of mighty men and drink the blood of princes as though they were rams, lambs, goats, and fat young bulls of Bashan!', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 19, 'Gorge yourselves with flesh until you are glutted; drink blood until you are drunk. This is the sacrificial feast I have prepared for you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 20, 'Feast at my banquet table--feast on horses, riders, and valiant warriors, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 21, '"Thus, I will demonstrate my glory among the nations. Everyone will see the punishment I have inflicted on them and the power I have demonstrated.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 22, 'And from that time on the people of Israel will know that I am the LORD their God.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 23, 'The nations will then know why Israel was sent away to exile--it was punishment for sin, for they acted in treachery against their God. Therefore, I turned my back on them and let their enemies destroy them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 24, 'I turned my face away and punished them in proportion to the vileness of their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 25, '"So now the Sovereign LORD says: I will end the captivity of my people; I will have mercy on Israel, for I am jealous for my holy reputation!', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 26, 'They will accept responsibility for their past shame and treachery against me after they come home to live in peace and safety in their own land. And then no one will bother them or make them afraid.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 27, 'When I bring them home from the lands of their enemies, my holiness will be displayed to the nations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 28, 'Then my people will know that I am the LORD their God--responsible for sending them away to exile and responsible for bringing them home. I will leave none of my people behind.', 'NLT'),
(30, 39, 29, 'And I will never again turn my back on them, for I will pour out my Spirit upon them, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 1, 'On April 28, during the twenty-fifth year of our captivity--fourteen years after the fall of Jerusalem--the LORD took hold of me.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 2, 'In a vision of God he took me to the land of Israel and set me down on a very high mountain. From there I could see what appeared to be a city across from me toward the south.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 3, 'As he brought me nearer, I saw a man whose face shone like bronze standing beside a gateway entrance. He was holding in his hand a measuring tape and a measuring rod.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 4, 'He said to me, "Son of man, watch and listen. Pay close attention to everything I show you. You have been brought here so I can show you many things. Then you will return to the people of Israel and tell them everything you have seen."', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 5, 'I could see a wall completely surrounding the Temple area. The man took a measuring rod that was 10 1/2 feet long and measured the wall, and the wall was 10 1/2 feet thick and 10 1/2 feet high.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 6, 'Then he went over to the gateway that goes through the eastern wall. He climbed the steps and measured the threshold of the gateway; it was 10 1/2 feet deep.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 7, 'There were guard alcoves on each side built into the gateway passage. Each of these alcoves was 10 1/2 feet square, with a distance between them of 8 3/4 feet along the passage wall. The gateway''s inner threshold, which led to the foyer at the inner end of the gateway passage, was 10 1/2 feet deep.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 8, 'He also measured the foyer of the gateway', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 9, 'and found it to be 14 feet deep, with supporting columns 3 1/2 feet thick. This foyer was at the inner end of the gateway structure, facing toward the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 10, 'There were three guard alcoves on each side of the gateway passage. Each had the same measurements, and the dividing walls separating them were also identical.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 11, 'The man measured the gateway entrance, which was 17 1/2 feet wide at the opening and 22 3/4 feet wide in the gateway passage.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 12, 'In front of each of the guard alcoves was a 21-inch curb. The alcoves themselves were 10 1/2 feet square.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 13, 'Then he measured the entire width of the gateway, measuring the distance between the back walls of facing guard alcoves; this distance was 43 3/4 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 14, 'He measured the dividing walls all along the inside of the gateway up to the gateway''s foyer; this distance was 105 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 15, 'The full length of the gateway passage was 87 1/2 feet from one end to the other.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 16, 'There were recessed windows that narrowed inward through the walls of the guard alcoves and their dividing walls. There were also windows in the foyer structure. The surfaces of the dividing walls were decorated with carved palm trees.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 17, 'Then the man brought me through the gateway into the outer courtyard of the Temple. A stone pavement ran along the walls of the courtyard, and thirty rooms were built against the walls, opening onto the pavement.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 18, 'This pavement flanked the gates and extended out from the walls into the courtyard the same distance as the gateway entrance. This was the lower pavement.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 19, 'Then the man measured across the Temple''s outer courtyard between the outer and inner gateways; the distance was 175 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 20, 'There was a gateway on the north just like the one on the east, and the man measured it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 21, 'Here, too, there were three guard alcoves on each side, with dividing walls and a foyer. All the measurements matched those of the east gateway. The gateway passage was 87 1/2 feet long and 43 3/4 feet wide between the back walls of facing guard alcoves.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 22, 'The windows, the foyer, and the palm tree decorations were identical to those in the east gateway. There were seven steps leading up to the gateway entrance, and the foyer was at the inner end of the gateway passage.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 23, 'Here on the north side, just as on the east, there was another gateway leading to the Temple''s inner courtyard directly opposite this outer gateway. The distance between the two gateways was 175 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 24, 'Then the man took me around to the south gateway and measured its various parts, and he found they were exactly the same as in the others.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 25, 'It had windows along the walls as the others did, and there was a foyer where the gateway passage opened into the outer courtyard. And like the others, the gateway passage was 87 1/2 feet long and 43 3/4 feet wide between the back walls of facing guard alcoves.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 26, 'This gateway also had a stairway of seven steps leading up to it, and there were palm tree decorations along the dividing walls.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 27, 'And here again, directly opposite the outer gateway, was another gateway that led into the inner courtyard. The distance between the two gateways was 175 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 28, 'Then the man took me to the south gateway leading into the inner courtyard. He measured it and found that it had the same measurements as the other gateways.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 29, 'Its guard alcoves, dividing walls, and foyer were the same size as those in the others. It also had windows along its walls and in the foyer structure. And like the others, the gateway passage was 87 1/2 feet long and 43 3/4 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 30, '(The foyers of the gateways leading into the inner courtyard were 8 3/4 feet deep and 43 3/4 feet wide.)', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 31, 'The foyer of the south gateway faced into the outer courtyard. It had palm tree decorations on its columns, and there were eight steps leading to its entrance.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 32, 'Then he took me to the east gateway leading to the inner courtyard. He measured it and found that it had the same measurements as the other gateways.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 33, 'Its guard alcoves, dividing walls, and foyer were the same size as those of the others, and there were windows along the walls and in the foyer structure. The gateway passage measured 87 1/2 feet long and 43 3/4 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 34, 'Its foyer faced into the outer courtyard. It had palm tree decorations on its columns, and there were eight steps leading to its entrance.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 35, 'Then he took me around to the north gateway leading to the inner courtyard. He measured it and found that it had the same measurements as the other gateways.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 36, 'The guard alcoves, dividing walls, and foyer of this gateway had the same measurements as in the others and the same window arrangements. The gateway passage measured 87 1/2 feet long and 43 3/4 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 37, 'Its foyer faced into the outer courtyard, and it had palm tree decorations on the columns. There were eight steps leading to its entrance.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 38, 'A door led from the foyer of the inner gateway on the north side into a side room where the meat for sacrifices was washed before being taken to the altar.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 39, 'On each side of this foyer were two tables, where the sacrificial animals were slaughtered for the burnt offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 40, 'Outside the foyer, on each side of the stairs going up to the north entrance, there were two more tables.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 41, 'So there were eight tables in all, four inside and four outside, where the sacrifices were cut up and prepared.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 42, 'There were also four tables of hewn stone for preparation of the burnt offerings, each 31 1/2 inches square and 21 inches high. On these tables were placed the butchering knives and other implements and the sacrificial animals.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 43, 'There were hooks, each three inches long, fastened to the foyer walls and set on the tables where the sacrificial meat was to be laid.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 44, 'Inside the inner courtyard there were two one-room buildings for the singers, one beside the north gateway, facing south, and the other beside the south gateway, facing north.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 45, 'And the man said to me, "The building beside the north inner gate is for the priests who supervise the Temple maintenance.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 46, 'The building beside the south inner gate is for the priests in charge of the altar--the descendants of Zadok--for they alone of all the Levites may approach the LORD to minister to him."', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 47, 'Then the man measured the inner courtyard and found it to be 175 feet square. The altar stood there in the courtyard in front of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 48, 'Then he brought me to the foyer of the Temple. He measured its supporting columns and found them to be 8 3/4 feet square. The entrance was 24 1/2 feet wide with walls 5 1/4 feet thick.', 'NLT'),
(30, 40, 49, 'The depth of the foyer was 35 feet and the width was 19 1/4 feet. There were ten steps leading up to it, with a column on each side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 1, 'After that, the man brought me into the Holy Place, the large main room of the Temple, and he measured the columns that framed its doorway. They were 10 1/2 feet square.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 2, 'The entrance was 17 1/2 feet wide, and the walls on each side were 8 3/4 feet wide. The Holy Place itself was 70 feet long and 35 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 3, 'Then he went into the inner room at the end of the Holy Place. He measured the columns at the entrance and found them to be 3 1/2 feet thick. The entrance was 10 1/2 feet wide, and the walls on each side of the entrance extended 12 1/4 feet to the corners of the inner room.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 4, 'The inner room was 35 feet square. "This," he told me, "is the Most Holy Place."', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 5, 'Then he measured the wall of the Temple and found that it was 10 1/2 feet thick. There was a row of rooms along the outside wall; each room was 7 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 6, 'These rooms were built in three levels, one above the other, with thirty rooms on each level. The supports for these rooms rested on ledges in the Temple wall, but the supports did not extend into the wall.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 7, 'Each level was wider than the one below it, corresponding to the narrowing of the Temple wall as it rose higher. A stairway led up from the bottom level through the middle level to the top level.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 8, 'I noticed that the Temple was built on a terrace, which provided a foundation for the side rooms. This terrace was 10 1/2 feet high.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 9, 'The outer wall of the Temple''s side rooms was 8 3/4 feet thick. This left an open area between these side rooms', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 10, 'and the row of rooms along the outer wall of the inner courtyard. This open area measured 35 feet in width, and it went all the way around the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 11, 'Two doors opened from the side rooms into the terrace yard, which was 8 3/4 feet wide. One door faced north and the other south.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 12, 'A large building stood on the west, facing the Temple courtyard. It was 122 1/2 feet wide and 157 1/2 feet long, and its walls were 8 3/4 feet thick.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 13, 'Then the man measured the Temple, and he found it to be 175 feet long. The courtyard around the building, including its walls, was an additional 175 feet in length.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 14, 'The inner courtyard to the east of the Temple was also 175 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 15, 'The building to the west, including its two walls, was also 175 feet wide. The Holy Place, the Most Holy Place, and the foyer of the Temple were all paneled with wood,', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 16, 'as were the frames of the recessed windows. The inner walls of the Temple were paneled with wood above and below the windows.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 17, 'The space above the door leading into the Most Holy Place was also paneled.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 18, 'All the walls were decorated with carvings of cherubim, each with two faces, and there was a palm tree carving between each of the cherubim.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 19, 'One face--that of a man--looked toward the palm tree on one side. The other face--that of a young lion--looked toward the palm tree on the other side. The figures were carved all along the inside of the Temple,', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 20, 'from the floor to the top of the walls, including the outer wall of the Holy Place.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 21, 'There were square columns at the entrance to the Holy Place, and the ones at the entrance of the Most Holy Place were similar.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 22, 'There was an altar made of wood, 3 1/2 feet square and 5 1/4 feet high. Its corners, base, and sides were all made of wood. "This," the man told me, "is the table that stands in the LORD''s presence."', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 23, 'Both the Holy Place and the Most Holy Place had double doorways,', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 24, 'each with two swinging doors.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 25, 'The doors leading into the Holy Place were decorated with carved cherubim and palm trees just as on the walls. And there was a wooden canopy over the front of the Temple''s foyer.', 'NLT'),
(30, 41, 26, 'On both sides of the foyer there were recessed windows decorated with carved palm trees.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 1, 'Then the man led me out of the Temple courtyard by way of the north gateway. We entered the outer courtyard and came to a group of rooms against the north wall of the inner courtyard.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 2, 'This group of structures, whose entrance opened toward the north, was 175 feet long and 87 1/2 feet wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 3, 'One block of rooms overlooked the 35-foot width of the inner courtyard. Another block of rooms looked out onto the pavement of the outer courtyard. The two blocks were built three levels high and stood across from each other.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 4, 'Between the two blocks of rooms ran a walkway 17 1/2 feet wide. It extended the entire 175 feet of the complex, and all the doors faced toward the north.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 5, 'Each of the two upper levels of rooms was narrower than the one beneath it because the upper levels had to allow space for walkways in front of them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 6, 'Since there were three levels and they did not have supporting columns as in the courtyards, each of the upper levels was set back from the level beneath it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 7, 'There was an outer wall that separated the rooms from the outer courtyard; it was 87 1/2 feet long.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 8, 'This wall added length to the outer block of rooms, which extended for only 87 1/2 feet, while the inner block--the rooms toward the Temple--extended for 175 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 9, 'There was an entrance from the outer courtyard to these rooms from the east.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 10, 'On the south side of the Temple there were two blocks of rooms just south of the inner courtyard between the Temple and the outer courtyard. These rooms were arranged just like the rooms on the north.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 11, 'There was a walkway between the two blocks of rooms just like the complex on the north side of the Temple. This complex of rooms was the same length and width as the other one, and it had the same entrances and doors. The dimensions of each were identical.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 12, 'So there was an entrance in the wall facing the doors of the inner block of rooms, and another on the east at the end of the interior walkway.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 13, 'Then the man told me, "These rooms that overlook the Temple from the north and south are holy. It is there that the priests who offer sacrifices to the LORD will eat the most holy offerings. And they will use these rooms to store the grain offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings because these rooms are holy.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 14, 'When the priests leave the Holy Place, they must not go directly to the outer courtyard. They must first take off the clothes they wore while ministering because these clothes are holy. They must put on other clothes before entering the parts of the building complex open to the public."', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 15, 'When the man had finished taking these measurements, he led me out through the east gateway to measure the entire Temple area.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 16, 'He measured the east side; it was 875 feet long.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 17, 'He also measured the north side and got the same measurement.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 18, 'The south side was the same length,', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 19, 'and so was the west side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 42, 20, 'So the area was 875 feet on each side with a wall all around it to separate the holy places from the common.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 1, 'After this, the man brought me back around to the east gateway.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 2, 'Suddenly, the glory of the God of Israel appeared from the east. The sound of his coming was like the roar of rushing waters, and the whole landscape shone with his glory.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 3, 'This vision was just like the others I had seen, first by the Kebar River and then when he came to destroy Jerusalem. And I fell down before him with my face in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 4, 'And the glory of the LORD came into the Temple through the east gateway.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 5, 'Then the Spirit took me up and brought me into the inner courtyard, and the glory of the LORD filled the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 6, 'And I heard someone speaking to me from within the Temple. (The man who had been measuring was still standing beside me.)', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 7, 'And the LORD said to me, "Son of man, this is the place of my throne and the place where I will rest my feet. I will remain here forever, living among the people of Israel. They and their kings will not defile my holy name any longer by their adulterous worship of other gods or by raising monuments in honor of their dead kings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 8, 'They put their idol altars right next to mine with only a wall between them and me. They defiled my holy name by such wickedness, so I consumed them in my anger.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 9, 'Now let them put away their idols and the sacred pillars erected to honor their kings, and I will live among them forever.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 10, '"Son of man, describe to the people of Israel the Temple I have shown you. Tell them its appearance and its plan so they will be ashamed of all their sins.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 11, 'And if they are ashamed of what they have done, describe to them all the specifications of its construction--including its entrances and doors--and everything else about it. Write down all these specifications and directions as they watch so they will be sure to remember them.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 12, 'And this is the basic law of the Temple: absolute holiness! The entire top of the hill where the Temple is built is holy. Yes, this is the primary law of the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 13, '"These are the measurements of the altar: There is a gutter all around the altar 21 inches wide and 21 inches deep, with a curb 9 inches wide around its edge. And this is the height of the altar:', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 14, 'From the gutter the altar rises 3 1/2 feet to a ledge that surrounds the altar; this lower ledge is 21 inches wide. From the lower ledge the altar rises 7 feet to the upper ledge; this upper ledge is also 21 inches wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 15, 'The top of the altar, the hearth, rises still 7 feet higher, with a horn rising up from each of the four corners.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 16, 'The top of the altar is square, measuring 21 feet by 21 feet.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 17, 'The upper ledge also forms a square, measuring 24 1/2 feet on each side, with a 21-inch gutter and a 10 1/2-inch curb all around the edge. There are steps going up the east side of the altar."', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 18, 'Then he said to me, "Son of man, this is what the Sovereign LORD says: These will be the regulations for the burning of offerings and the sprinkling of blood when the altar is built.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 19, 'At that time, the Levitical priests of the family of Zadok, who minister before me, are to be given a young bull for a sin offering, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 20, 'You will take some of its blood and smear it on the four horns of the altar, the four corners of the upper ledge, and the curb that runs around that ledge. This will cleanse and make atonement for the altar.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 21, 'Then take the young bull for the sin offering and burn it at the appointed place outside the Temple area.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 22, '"On the second day, sacrifice as a sin offering a young male goat that has no physical defects. Then cleanse and make atonement for the altar again, just as you did with the young bull.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 23, 'When you have finished the cleansing ceremony, offer another young bull that has no defects and a perfect ram from the flock.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 24, 'You are to present them to the LORD, and the priests are to sprinkle salt on them and offer them as a burnt offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 25, '"Every day for seven days a male goat, a young bull, and a ram from the flock will be sacrificed as a sin offering. None of these animals may have physical defects of any kind.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 26, 'Do this each day for seven days to cleanse and make atonement for the altar, thus setting it apart for holy use.', 'NLT'),
(30, 43, 27, 'On the eighth day, and on each day afterward, the priests will sacrifice on the altar the burnt offerings and peace offerings of the people. Then I will accept you, says the Sovereign LORD."', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 1, 'Then the man brought me back to the east gateway in the outer wall, but it was closed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 2, 'And the LORD said to me, "This gate must remain closed; it will never again be opened. No man will ever pass through it, for the LORD, the God of Israel, entered here. Thus, it must always remain shut.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 3, 'Only the prince himself may sit inside this gateway to feast in the LORD''s presence. But he may come and go only through the gateway''s foyer."', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 4, 'Then the man brought me through the north gateway to the front of the Temple. I looked and saw that the glory of the LORD filled the Temple of the LORD, and I fell to the ground with my face in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 5, 'And the LORD said to me, "Son of man, take careful notice; use your eyes and ears. Listen to everything I tell you about the regulations concerning the LORD''s Temple. Take careful note of who may be admitted to the Temple and who is to be excluded from it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 6, 'And give these rebels, the people of Israel, this message from the Sovereign LORD: O people of Israel, enough of your disgusting sins!', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 7, 'You have brought uncircumcised foreigners into my sanctuary--people who have no heart for God. In this way, you profaned my Temple even as you offered me my food, the fat and blood of sacrifices. Thus, in addition to all your other disgusting sins, you have broken my covenant.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 8, 'You have not kept the laws I gave you concerning these sacred rituals, for you have hired foreigners to take charge of my sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 9, '"So this is what the Sovereign LORD says: No foreigners, including those who live among the people of Israel, will enter my sanctuary if they have not been circumcised and do not love the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 10, 'And the men of the tribe of Levi who abandoned me when Israel strayed away from me to worship idols must bear the consequences of their unfaithfulness.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 11, 'They may still be Temple guards and gatemen, and they may still slaughter the animals brought for burnt offerings and be present to help the people.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 12, 'But they encouraged my people to worship other gods, causing Israel to fall into deep sin. So I have raised my hand and taken an oath that they must bear the consequences for their sins, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 13, 'They may not approach me to minister as priests. They may not touch any of my holy things or the holy offerings, for they must bear the shame of all the sins they have committed.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 14, 'They are to serve as the Temple caretakers and are relegated to doing maintenance work and helping the people in a general way.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 15, '"However, the Levitical priests of the family of Zadok continued to minister faithfully in the Temple when Israel abandoned me for idols. These men will serve as my ministers. They will stand in my presence and offer the fat and blood of the sacrifices, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 16, 'They are the ones who will enter my sanctuary and approach my table to serve me. They are the ones who will fulfill all my requirements.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 17, 'When they enter the gateway to the inner courtyard, they must wear only linen clothing. They must wear no wool while on duty in the inner courtyard or in the Temple itself.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 18, 'They must wear linen turbans and linen undergarments. They must not wear anything that would cause them to perspire.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 19, 'When they return to the outer courtyard where the people are, they must take off the clothes they wear while ministering to me. They must leave them in the sacred rooms and put on other clothes so they do not harm the people by transmitting holiness to them through this clothing.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 20, '"They must neither let their hair grow too long nor shave it off completely. Instead, they must trim it regularly.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 21, 'The priests must never drink wine before entering the inner courtyard.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 22, 'They may choose their wives only from among the virgins of Israel or the widows of the priests. They may not marry other widows or divorced women.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 23, 'They will teach my people the difference between what is holy and what is common, what is ceremonially clean and unclean.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 24, '"They will serve as judges to resolve any disagreements among my people. Their decisions must be based on my regulations. And the priests themselves must obey my instructions and laws at all the sacred festivals, and they will see to it that the Sabbath is set apart as a holy day.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 25, 'A priest must never defile himself by being in the presence of a dead person unless it is his father, mother, child, brother, or unmarried sister. In such cases it is permitted.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 26, 'But such a priest can only return to his Temple duties after being ritually cleansed and then waiting for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 27, 'The first day he returns to work and enters the inner courtyard and the sanctuary, he must offer a sin offering for himself, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 28, '"As to property, the priests will not have any, for I alone am their inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 29, 'Their food will come from the gifts and sacrifices brought to the Temple by the people--the grain offerings, the sin offerings, and the guilt offerings. Whatever anyone sets apart for the LORD will belong to the priests.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 30, 'The first of the ripe fruits and all the gifts brought to the LORD will go to the priests. The first samples of each grain harvest and the first of your flour must also be given to the priests so the LORD will bless your homes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 44, 31, 'The priests may never eat meat from any bird or animal that dies a natural death or that dies after being attacked by another animal.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 1, '"When you divide the land among the tribes of Israel, you must set aside a section of it for the LORD as his holy portion. This piece of land will be 8 1/3 miles long and 6 2/3 miles wide. The entire area will be holy ground.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 2, 'A section of this land, measuring 875 feet by 875 feet, will be set aside for the Temple. An additional strip of land 87 1/2 feet wide is to be left empty all around it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 3, 'Within the larger sacred area, measure out a portion of land 8 1/3 miles long and 3 1/3 miles wide. Within it the sanctuary of the Most Holy Place will be located.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 4, 'This area will be a holy land, set aside for the priests who minister to the LORD in the sanctuary. They will use it for their homes, and my Temple will be located within it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 5, 'The strip of sacred land next to it, also 8 1/3 miles long and 3 1/3 miles wide, will be a living area for the Levites who work at the Temple. It will be their possession and a place for their towns.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 6, '"Adjacent to the larger sacred area will be a section of land 8 1/3 miles long and 1 2/3 miles wide. This will be set aside to be a city where anyone in Israel can come and live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 7, '"Two special sections of land will be set apart for the prince. One section will share a border with the east side of the sacred lands and city, and the second section will share a border on the west side. Then the far eastern and western borders of the prince''s lands will line up with the eastern and western boundaries of the tribal areas.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 8, 'These sections of land will be the prince''s allotment. "My princes will no longer oppress and rob my people; they will assign the rest of the land to the people, giving an allotment to each tribe.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 9, 'For this is what the Sovereign LORD says: Enough, you princes of Israel! Stop all your violence and oppression and do what is just and right. Quit robbing and cheating my people out of their land! Stop expelling them from their homes!', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 10, 'You must use only honest weights and scales, honest dry volume measures, and honest liquid volume measures.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 11, 'The homer will be your standard unit for measuring volume. The ephah and the bath will each measure one-tenth of a homer.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 12, 'The standard unit for weight will be the silver shekel. One shekel consists of twenty gerahs, and sixty shekels are equal to one mina.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 13, '"This is the tax you must give to the prince: one bushel of wheat or barley for every sixty you harvest,', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 14, 'one percent of your olive oil,', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 15, 'and one sheep for every two hundred in your flocks in Israel. These will be the grain offerings, burnt offerings, and peace offerings that will make atonement for the people who bring them, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 16, 'All the people of Israel must join the prince in bringing their offerings.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 17, 'The prince will be required to provide offerings that are given at the religious festivals, the new moon celebrations, the Sabbath days, and all other similar occasions. He will provide the sin offerings, burnt offerings, grain offerings, drink offerings, and peace offerings to make reconciliation for the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 18, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: In early spring, on the first day of each new year, sacrifice a young bull with no physical defects to purify the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 19, 'The priest will take some of the blood of this sin offering and put it on the doorposts of the Temple, the four corners of the upper ledge on the altar, and the gateposts at the entrance to the inner courtyard.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 20, 'Do this also on the seventh day of the new year for anyone who has sinned through error or ignorance. In that way, you will make atonement for the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 21, '"On the fourteenth day of the new year, you must celebrate the Passover. This festival will last for seven days. Only bread without yeast may be eaten during that time.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 22, 'On the day of Passover the prince will provide a young bull as a sin offering for himself and the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 23, 'On each of the seven days of the feast he will prepare a burnt offering to the LORD. This daily offering will consist of seven young bulls and seven rams without any defects. A male goat will also be given each day for a sin offering.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 24, 'The prince will provide a half bushel of flour as a grain offering and a gallon of olive oil with each young bull and ram.', 'NLT'),
(30, 45, 25, '"During the seven days of the Festival of Shelters, which occurs every year in early autumn, the prince will provide these same sacrifices for the sin offering, the burnt offering, and the grain offering, along with the required olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 1, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: The east gateway of the inner wall will be closed during the six workdays each week, but it will be open on Sabbath days and the days of new moon celebrations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 2, 'The prince will enter the foyer of the gateway from the outside. Then he will stand by the gatepost while the priest offers his burnt offering and peace offering. He will worship inside the gateway passage and then go back out the way he came. The gateway will not be closed until evening.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 3, 'The common people will worship the LORD in front of this gateway on Sabbath days and the days of new moon celebrations.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 4, '"Each Sabbath day the prince will present to the LORD a burnt offering of six lambs and one ram, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 5, 'He will present a grain offering of a half bushel of flour to go with the ram and whatever amount of flour he chooses to go with each lamb. He is to offer one gallon of olive oil for each half bushel of flour.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 6, 'At the new moon celebrations, he will bring one young bull, six lambs, and one ram, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 7, 'With the young bull he must bring a half bushel of flour for a grain offering. With the ram he must bring another half bushel of flour. And with each lamb he is to bring whatever amount of flour that he decides to give. With each half bushel of flour he must offer one gallon of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 8, '"The prince must enter the gateway through the foyer, and he must leave the same way he came.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 9, 'But when the people come in through the north gateway to worship the LORD during the religious festivals, they must leave by the south gateway. And those who entered through the south gateway must leave by the north gateway. They must never leave by the same gateway they came in; they must always use the opposite gateway.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 10, 'The prince will enter and leave with the people on these occasions.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 11, '"So at the special feasts and sacred festivals, the grain offering will be a half bushel of flour with each young bull, another half bushel of flour with each ram, and as much flour as the prince chooses to give with each lamb. One gallon of oil is to be given with each half bushel of flour.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 12, 'Whenever the prince offers a voluntary burnt offering or peace offering to the LORD, the east gateway to the inner courtyard will be opened for him to enter, and he will offer his sacrifices just as he does on Sabbath days. Then he will turn and leave the way he entered, and the gateway will be shut behind him.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 13, '"Each morning a year-old lamb with no physical defects must be sacrificed as a burnt offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 14, 'With the lamb, a grain offering must also be given to the LORD--about two and a half quarts of flour with a third of a gallon of olive oil to moisten the flour. This will be a permanent law for you.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 15, 'The lamb, the grain offering, and the olive oil must be given as a daily sacrifice every morning without fail.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 16, '"This is what the Sovereign LORD says: If the prince gives a gift of land to one of his sons, it will belong to him and his descendants forever.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 17, 'But if he gives a gift of land to one of his servants, the servant may keep it only until the Year of Jubilee, which comes every fiftieth year. At that time the servant will be set free, and the land will return to the prince. Only the gifts given to the prince''s sons will be permanent.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 18, 'And the prince may never take anyone''s property by force. If he gives property to his sons, it must be from his own land, for I do not want any of my people unjustly evicted from their property."', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 19, 'Then the man brought me through the entrance beside the gateway and led me to the sacred rooms assigned to the priests, which faced toward the north. He showed me a place at the extreme west end of these rooms.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 20, 'He explained, "This is where the priests will cook the meat from the guilt offerings and sin offerings and bake the flour from the grain offerings into bread. They will do it here to avoid carrying the sacrifices through the outer courtyard and harming the people by transmitting holiness to them."', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 21, 'Then he brought me back to the outer courtyard and led me to each of its four corners. In each corner I saw an enclosure.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 22, 'Each of these enclosures was 70 feet long and 52 1/2 feet wide, surrounded by walls.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 23, 'Along the inside of these walls was a ledge of stone with fireplaces under the ledge all the way around.', 'NLT'),
(30, 46, 24, 'The man said to me, "These are the kitchens to be used by the Temple assistants to boil the sacrifices offered by the people."', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 1, 'Then the man brought me back to the entrance of the Temple. There I saw a stream flowing eastward from beneath the Temple threshold. This stream then passed to the right of the altar on its south side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 2, 'The man brought me outside the wall through the north gateway and led me around to the eastern entrance. There I could see the stream flowing out through the south side of the east gateway.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 3, 'Measuring as he went, he led me along the stream for 1,750 feet and told me to go across. At that point the water was up to my ankles.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 4, 'He measured off another 1,750 feet and told me to go across again. This time the water was up to my knees. After another 1,750 feet, it was up to my waist.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 5, 'Then he measured another 1,750 feet, and the river was too deep to cross without swimming.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 6, 'He told me to keep in mind what I had seen; then he led me back along the riverbank.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 7, 'Suddenly, to my surprise, many trees were now growing on both sides of the river!', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 8, 'Then he said to me, "This river flows east through the desert into the Jordan Valley, where it enters the Dead Sea. The waters of this stream will heal the salty waters of the Dead Sea and make them fresh and pure.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 9, 'Everything that touches the water of this river will live. Fish will abound in the Dead Sea, for its waters will be healed. Wherever this water flows, everything will live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 10, 'Fishermen will stand along the shores of the Dead Sea, fishing all the way from En-gedi to En-eglaim. The shores will be covered with nets drying in the sun. Fish of every kind will fill the Dead Sea, just as they fill the Mediterranean!', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 11, 'But the marshes and swamps will not be purified; they will be sources of salt.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 12, 'All kinds of fruit trees will grow along both sides of the river. The leaves of these trees will never turn brown and fall, and there will always be fruit on their branches. There will be a new crop every month, without fail! For they are watered by the river flowing from the Temple. The fruit will be for food and the leaves for healing."', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 13, 'This is what the Sovereign LORD says: "Follow these instructions for dividing the land for the twelve tribes of Israel: The tribe of Joseph will be given two shares of land.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 14, 'Otherwise each tribe will receive an equal share. I swore that I would give this land to your ancestors, and it will now come to you as your inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 15, '"The northern border will run from the Mediterranean toward Hethlon, then on through Lebo-hamath to Zedad;', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 16, 'then it will run to Berothah and Sibraim, which are on the border between Damascus and Hamath, and finally to Hazer-hatticon, on the border of Hauran.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 17, 'So the northern border will run from the Mediterranean to Hazar-enan, on the border between Hamath to the north and Damascus to the south.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 18, '"The eastern border starts at a point between Hauran and Damascus and runs southward along the Jordan River between Israel and Gilead, past the Dead Sea and as far south as Tamar. This will be the eastern border.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 19, '"The southern border will go west from Tamar to the waters of Meribah at Kadesh and then follow the course of the brook of Egypt to the Mediterranean. This will be the southern border.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 20, '"On the west side the Mediterranean itself will be your border from the southern border to the point where the northern border begins, opposite Lebo-hamath.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 21, '"Divide the land within these boundaries among the tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 22, 'Distribute the land as an inheritance for yourselves and for the foreigners who have joined you and are raising their families among you. They will be just like native-born Israelites to you, and they will receive an inheritance among the tribes.', 'NLT'),
(30, 47, 23, 'All these immigrants are to be given land within the territory of the tribe with whom they now live. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 1, '"Here is the list of the tribes of Israel and the territory each is to receive. The territory of Dan is in the extreme north. Its boundary line follows the Hethlon road to Lebo-hamath and then runs on to Hazar-enan on the border of Damascus, with Hamath to the north. Dan''s territory extends all the way across the land of Israel from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 2, 'Asher''s territory lies south of Dan''s and also extends from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 3, 'Naphtali''s land lies south of Asher''s, also extending from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 4, 'Then comes Manasseh south of Naphtali, and its territory also extends from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 5, 'South of Manasseh is Ephraim,', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 6, 'and then Reuben,', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 7, 'and then Judah, all of whose boundaries extend from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 8, '"South of Judah is the land set aside for a special purpose. It will be 8 1/3 miles wide and will extend as far east and west as the tribal territories, with the Temple at the center.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 9, '"The area set aside for the LORD''s Temple will be 8 1/3 miles long and 6 2/3 miles wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 10, 'For the priests there will be a strip of land measuring 8 1/3 miles long by 3 1/3 miles wide, with the LORD''s Temple at the center.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 11, 'This area is set aside for the ordained priests, the descendants of Zadok who obeyed me and did not go astray when the people of Israel and the rest of the Levites did.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 12, 'It will be their special portion when the land is distributed, the most sacred land of all. Next to the priests'' territory will lie the land where the other Levites will live.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 13, 'The land allotted to the Levites will be the same size and shape as that belonging to the priests--8 1/3 miles long and 3 1/3 miles wide. Together these portions of land will measure 8 1/3 miles long by 6 2/3 miles wide.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 14, 'None of this special land will ever be sold or traded or used by others, for it belongs to the LORD; it is set apart as holy.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 15, '"An additional strip of land 8 1/3 miles long by 1 2/3 miles wide, south of the sacred Temple area, will be allotted for public use--homes, pasturelands, and common lands, with a city at the center.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 16, 'The city will measure 1 1/2 miles on each side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 17, 'Open lands will surround the city for 150 yards in every direction.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 18, 'Outside the city there will be a farming area that stretches 3 1/3 miles to the east and 3 1/3 miles to the west along the border of the sacred area. This farmland will produce food for the people working in the city.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 19, 'Those who come from the various tribes to work in the city may farm it.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 20, 'This entire area--including the sacred lands and the city--is a square that measures 8 1/3 miles on each side.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 21, '"The areas that remain, to the east and to the west of the sacred lands and the city, will belong to the prince. Each of these areas will be 8 1/3 miles wide, extending in opposite directions to the eastern and western borders of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 22, 'So the prince''s land will include everything between the territories allotted to Judah and Benjamin, except for the areas set aside for the sacred lands and the city.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 23, '"These are the territories allotted to the rest of the tribes. Benjamin''s territory lies just south of the prince''s lands, and it extends across the entire land of Israel from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 24, 'South of Benjamin''s territory lies that of Simeon, also extending across the land from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 25, 'Next is the territory of Issachar with the same eastern and western boundaries.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 26, 'Then comes the territory of Zebulun, which also extends across the land from east to west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 27, 'The territory of Gad is just south of Zebulun with the same borders to the east and west.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 28, 'The southern border of Gad runs from Tamar to the waters of Meribah at Kadesh and then follows the brook of Egypt to the Mediterranean.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 29, 'These are the allotments that will be set aside for each tribe''s inheritance, says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 30, '"These will be the exits to the city: On the north wall, which is 1 1/2 miles long,', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 31, 'there will be three gates, each one named after a tribe of Israel. The first will be named for Reuben, the second for Judah, and the third for Levi.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 32, 'On the east wall, also 1 1/2 miles long, the gates will be named for Joseph, Benjamin, and Dan.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 33, 'The south wall, also 1 1/2 miles long, will have gates named for Simeon, Issachar, and Zebulun.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 34, 'And on the west wall, also 1 1/2 miles long, the gates will be named for Gad, Asher, and Naphtali.', 'NLT'),
(30, 48, 35, '"The distance around the entire city will be six miles. And from that day the name of the city will be `The LORD Is There.''"', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 1, 'During the third year of King Jehoiakim''s reign in Judah, King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon came to Jerusalem and besieged it with his armies.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 2, 'The Lord gave him victory over King Jehoiakim of Judah. When Nebuchadnezzar returned to Babylon, he took with him some of the sacred objects from the Temple of God and placed them in the treasure-house of his god in the land of Babylonia.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 3, 'Then the king ordered Ashpenaz, who was in charge of the palace officials, to bring to the palace some of the young men of Judah''s royal family and other noble families, who had been brought to Babylon as captives.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 4, '"Select only strong, healthy, and good-looking young men," he said. "Make sure they are well versed in every branch of learning, are gifted with knowledge and good sense, and have the poise needed to serve in the royal palace. Teach these young men the language and literature of the Babylonians. "', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 5, 'The king assigned them a daily ration of the best food and wine from his own kitchens. They were to be trained for a three-year period, and then some of them would be made his advisers in the royal court.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 6, 'Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah were four of the young men chosen, all from the tribe of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 7, 'The chief official renamed them with these Babylonian names: Daniel was called Belteshazzar. Hananiah was called Shadrach. Mishael was called Meshach. Azariah was called Abednego.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 8, 'But Daniel made up his mind not to defile himself by eating the food and wine given to them by the king. He asked the chief official for permission to eat other things instead.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 9, 'Now God had given the chief official great respect for Daniel.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 10, 'But he was alarmed by Daniel''s suggestion. "My lord the king has ordered that you eat this food and wine," he said. "If you become pale and thin compared to the other youths your age, I am afraid the king will have me beheaded for neglecting my duties."', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 11, 'Daniel talked it over with the attendant who had been appointed by the chief official to look after Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 12, '"Test us for ten days on a diet of vegetables and water," Daniel said.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 13, '"At the end of the ten days, see how we look compared to the other young men who are eating the king''s rich food. Then you can decide whether or not to let us continue eating our diet."', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 14, 'So the attendant agreed to Daniel''s suggestion and tested them for ten days.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 15, 'At the end of the ten days, Daniel and his three friends looked healthier and better nourished than the young men who had been eating the food assigned by the king.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 16, 'So after that, the attendant fed them only vegetables instead of the rich foods and wines.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 17, 'God gave these four young men an unusual aptitude for learning the literature and science of the time. And God gave Daniel special ability in understanding the meanings of visions and dreams.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 18, 'When the three-year training period ordered by the king was completed, the chief official brought all the young men to King Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 19, 'The king talked with each of them, and none of them impressed him as much as Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah. So they were appointed to his regular staff of advisers.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 20, 'In all matters requiring wisdom and balanced judgment, the king found the advice of these young men to be ten times better than that of all the magicians and enchanters in his entire kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(31, 1, 21, 'Daniel remained there until the first year of King Cyrus''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 1, 'One night during the second year of his reign, Nebuchadnezzar had a dream that disturbed him so much that he couldn''t sleep.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 2, 'He called in his magicians, enchanters, sorcerers, and astrologers, and he demanded that they tell him what he had dreamed. As they stood before the king,', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 3, 'he said, "I have had a dream that troubles me. Tell me what I dreamed, for I must know what it means."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 4, 'Then the astrologers answered the king in Aramaic, "Long live the king! Tell us the dream, and we will tell you what it means."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 5, 'But the king said to the astrologers, "I am serious about this. If you don''t tell me what my dream was and what it means, you will be torn limb from limb, and your houses will be demolished into heaps of rubble!', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 6, 'But if you tell me what I dreamed and what the dream means, I will give you many wonderful gifts and honors. Just tell me the dream and what it means!"', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 7, 'They said again, "Please, Your Majesty. Tell us the dream, and we will tell you what it means."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 8, 'The king replied, "I can see through your trick! You are trying to stall for time because you know I am serious about what I said.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 9, 'If you don''t tell me the dream, you will be condemned. You have conspired to tell me lies in hopes that something will change. But tell me the dream, and then I will know that you can tell me what it means."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 10, 'The astrologers replied to the king, "There isn''t a man alive who can tell Your Majesty his dream! And no king, however great and powerful, has ever asked such a thing of any magician, enchanter, or astrologer!', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 11, 'This is an impossible thing the king requires. No one except the gods can tell you your dream, and they do not live among people."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 12, 'The king was furious when he heard this, and he sent out orders to execute all the wise men of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 13, 'And because of the king''s decree, men were sent to find and kill Daniel and his friends.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 14, 'When Arioch, the commander of the king''s guard, came to kill them, Daniel handled the situation with wisdom and discretion.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 15, 'He asked Arioch, "Why has the king issued such a harsh decree?" So Arioch told him all that had happened.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 16, 'Daniel went at once to see the king and requested more time so he could tell the king what the dream meant.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 17, 'Then Daniel went home and told his friends Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah what had happened.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 18, 'He urged them to ask the God of heaven to show them his mercy by telling them the secret, so they would not be executed along with the other wise men of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 19, 'That night the secret was revealed to Daniel in a vision. Then Daniel praised the God of heaven,', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 20, 'saying, "Praise the name of God forever and ever, for he alone has all wisdom and power.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 21, 'He determines the course of world events; he removes kings and sets others on the throne. He gives wisdom to the wise and knowledge to the scholars.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 22, 'He reveals deep and mysterious things and knows what lies hidden in darkness, though he himself is surrounded by light.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 23, 'I thank and praise you, God of my ancestors, for you have given me wisdom and strength. You have told me what we asked of you and revealed to us what the king demanded."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 24, 'Then Daniel went in to see Arioch, who had been ordered to execute the wise men of Babylon. Daniel said to him, "Don''t kill the wise men. Take me to the king, and I will tell him the meaning of his dream."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 25, 'Then Arioch quickly took Daniel to the king and said, "I have found one of the captives from Judah who will tell Your Majesty the meaning of your dream!"', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 26, 'The king said to Daniel (also known as Belteshazzar), "Is this true? Can you tell me what my dream was and what it means?"', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 27, 'Daniel replied, "There are no wise men, enchanters, magicians, or fortune-tellers who can tell the king such things.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 28, 'But there is a God in heaven who reveals secrets, and he has shown King Nebuchadnezzar what will happen in the future. Now I will tell you your dream and the visions you saw as you lay on your bed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 29, '"While Your Majesty was sleeping, you dreamed about coming events. The revealer of mysteries has shown you what is going to happen.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 30, 'And it is not because I am wiser than any living person that I know the secret of your dream, but because God wanted you to understand what you were thinking about.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 31, '"Your Majesty, in your vision you saw in front of you a huge and powerful statue of a man, shining brilliantly, frightening and awesome.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 32, 'The head of the statue was made of fine gold, its chest and arms were of silver, its belly and thighs were of bronze,', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 33, 'its legs were of iron, and its feet were a combination of iron and clay.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 34, 'But as you watched, a rock was cut from a mountain by supernatural means. It struck the feet of iron and clay, smashing them to bits.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 35, 'The whole statue collapsed into a heap of iron, clay, bronze, silver, and gold. The pieces were crushed as small as chaff on a threshing floor, and the wind blew them all away without a trace. But the rock that knocked the statue down became a great mountain that covered the whole earth.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 36, '"That was the dream; now I will tell Your Majesty what it means.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 37, 'Your Majesty, you are a king over many kings. The God of heaven has given you sovereignty, power, strength, and honor.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 38, 'He has made you the ruler over all the inhabited world and has put even the animals and birds under your control. You are the head of gold.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 39, '"But after your kingdom comes to an end, another great kingdom, inferior to yours, will rise to take your place. After that kingdom has fallen, yet a third great kingdom, represented by the bronze belly and thighs, will rise to rule the world.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 40, 'Following that kingdom, there will be a fourth great kingdom, as strong as iron. That kingdom will smash and crush all previous empires, just as iron smashes and crushes everything it strikes.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 41, 'The feet and toes you saw that were a combination of iron and clay show that this kingdom will be divided.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 42, 'Some parts of it will be as strong as iron, and others as weak as clay.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 43, 'This mixture of iron and clay also shows that these kingdoms will try to strengthen themselves by forming alliances with each other through intermarriage. But this will not succeed, just as iron and clay do not mix.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 44, '"During the reigns of those kings, the God of heaven will set up a kingdom that will never be destroyed; no one will ever conquer it. It will shatter all these kingdoms into nothingness, but it will stand forever.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 45, 'That is the meaning of the rock cut from the mountain by supernatural means, crushing to dust the statue of iron, bronze, clay, silver, and gold. "The great God has shown Your Majesty what will happen in the future. The dream is true, and its meaning is certain."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 46, 'Then King Nebuchadnezzar bowed to the ground before Daniel and worshiped him, and he commanded his people to offer sacrifices and burn sweet incense before him.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 47, 'The king said to Daniel, "Truly, your God is the God of gods, the Lord over kings, a revealer of mysteries, for you have been able to reveal this secret."', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 48, 'Then the king appointed Daniel to a high position and gave him many valuable gifts. He made Daniel ruler over the whole province of Babylon, as well as chief over all his wise men.', 'NLT'),
(31, 2, 49, 'At Daniel''s request, the king appointed Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego to be in charge of all the affairs of the province of Babylon, while Daniel remained in the king''s court.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 1, 'King Nebuchadnezzar made a gold statue ninety feet tall and nine feet wide and set it up on the plain of Dura in the province of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 2, 'Then he sent messages to the princes, prefects, governors, advisers, counselors, judges, magistrates, and all the provincial officials to come to the dedication of the statue he had set up.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 3, 'When all these officials had arrived and were standing before the image King Nebuchadnezzar had set up,', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 4, 'a herald shouted out, "People of all races and nations and languages, listen to the king''s command!', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 5, 'When you hear the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipes, and other instruments, bow to the ground to worship King Nebuchadnezzar''s gold statue.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 6, 'Anyone who refuses to obey will immediately be thrown into a blazing furnace."', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 7, 'So at the sound of the musical instruments, all the people, whatever their race or nation or language, bowed to the ground and worshiped the statue that King Nebuchadnezzar had set up.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 8, 'But some of the astrologers went to the king and informed on the Jews.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 9, 'They said to King Nebuchadnezzar, "Long live the king!', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 10, 'You issued a decree requiring all the people to bow down and worship the gold statue when they hear the sound of the musical instruments.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 11, 'That decree also states that those who refuse to obey must be thrown into a blazing furnace.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 12, 'But there are some Jews--Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego--whom you have put in charge of the province of Babylon. They have defied Your Majesty by refusing to serve your gods or to worship the gold statue you have set up."', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 13, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar flew into a rage and ordered Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego to be brought before him. When they were brought in,', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 14, 'Nebuchadnezzar said to them, "Is it true, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, that you refuse to serve my gods or to worship the gold statue I have set up?', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 15, 'I will give you one more chance. If you bow down and worship the statue I have made when you hear the sound of the musical instruments, all will be well. But if you refuse, you will be thrown immediately into the blazing furnace. What god will be able to rescue you from my power then?"', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 16, 'Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego replied, "O Nebuchadnezzar, we do not need to defend ourselves before you.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 17, 'If we are thrown into the blazing furnace, the God whom we serve is able to save us. He will rescue us from your power, Your Majesty.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 18, 'But even if he doesn''t, Your Majesty can be sure that we will never serve your gods or worship the gold statue you have set up."', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 19, 'Nebuchadnezzar was so furious with Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego that his face became distorted with rage. He commanded that the furnace be heated seven times hotter than usual.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 20, 'Then he ordered some of the strongest men of his army to bind Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego and throw them into the blazing furnace.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 21, 'So they tied them up and threw them into the furnace, fully clothed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 22, 'And because the king, in his anger, had demanded such a hot fire in the furnace, the flames leaped out and killed the soldiers as they threw the three men in!', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 23, 'So Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, securely tied, fell down into the roaring flames.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 24, 'But suddenly, as he was watching, Nebuchadnezzar jumped up in amazement and exclaimed to his advisers, "Didn''t we tie up three men and throw them into the furnace?Yes," they said, "we did indeed, Your Majesty."', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 25, '"Look!" Nebuchadnezzar shouted. "I see four men, unbound, walking around in the fire. They aren''t even hurt by the flames! And the fourth looks like a divine being!"', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 26, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar came as close as he could to the door of the flaming furnace and shouted: "Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, servants of the Most High God, come out! Come here!" So Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego stepped out of the fire.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 27, 'Then the princes, prefects, governors, and advisers crowded around them and saw that the fire had not touched them. Not a hair on their heads was singed, and their clothing was not scorched. They didn''t even smell of smoke!', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 28, 'Then Nebuchadnezzar said, "Praise to the God of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego! He sent his angel to rescue his servants who trusted in him. They defied the king''s command and were willing to die rather than serve or worship any god except their own God.', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 29, 'Therefore, I make this decree: If any people, whatever their race or nation or language, speak a word against the God of Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, they will be torn limb from limb, and their houses will be crushed into heaps of rubble. There is no other god who can rescue like this!"', 'NLT'),
(31, 3, 30, 'Then the king promoted Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego to even higher positions in the province of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 1, 'King Nebuchadnezzar sent this message to the people of every race and nation and language throughout the world: "Peace and prosperity to you!', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 2, '"I want you all to know about the miraculous signs and wonders the Most High God has performed for me.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 3, 'How great are his signs, how powerful his wonders! His kingdom will last forever, his rule through all generations.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 4, '"I, Nebuchadnezzar, was living in my palace in comfort and prosperity.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 5, 'But one night I had a dream that greatly frightened me; I saw visions that terrified me as I lay in my bed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 6, 'So I issued an order calling in all the wise men of Babylon, so they could tell me what my dream meant.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 7, 'When all the magicians, enchanters, astrologers, and fortune-tellers came in, I told them the dream, but they could not tell me what it meant.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 8, 'At last Daniel came in before me, and I told him the dream. (He was named Belteshazzar after my god, and the spirit of the holy gods is in him.)', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 9, '"I said to him, `O Belteshazzar, master magician, I know that the spirit of the holy gods is in you and that no mystery is too great for you to solve. Now tell me what my dream means.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 10, '" `While I was lying in my bed, this is what I dreamed. I saw a large tree in the middle of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 11, 'The tree grew very tall and strong, reaching high into the heavens for all the world to see.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 12, 'It had fresh green leaves, and it was loaded with fruit for all to eat. Wild animals lived in its shade, and birds nested in its branches. All the world was fed from this tree.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 13, '" `Then as I lay there dreaming, I saw a messenger, a holy one, coming down from heaven.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 14, 'The messenger shouted, "Cut down the tree; lop off its branches! Shake off its leaves, and scatter its fruit! Chase the animals from its shade and the birds from its branches.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 15, 'But leave the stump and the roots in the ground, bound with a band of iron and bronze and surrounded by tender grass. Now let him be drenched with the dew of heaven, and let him live like an animal among the plants of the fields.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 16, 'For seven periods of time, let him have the mind of an animal instead of a human.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 17, 'For this has been decreed by the messengers; it is commanded by the holy ones. The purpose of this decree is that the whole world may understand that the Most High rules over the kingdoms of the world and gives them to anyone he chooses--even to the lowliest of humans."', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 18, '" `O Belteshazzar, that was the dream that I, King Nebuchadnezzar, had. Now tell me what it means, for no one else can help me. All the wisest men of my kingdom have failed me. But you can tell me because the spirit of the holy gods is in you.''', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 19, '"Upon hearing this, Daniel (also known as Belteshazzar) was overcome for a time, aghast at the meaning of the dream. Finally, the king said to him, `Belteshazzar, don''t be alarmed by the dream and what it means.''"Belteshazzar replied, `Oh, how I wish the events foreshadowed in this dream would happen to your enemies, my lord, and not to you!', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 20, 'You saw a tree growing very tall and strong, reaching high into the heavens for all the world to see.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 21, 'It had fresh green leaves, and it was loaded with fruit for all to eat. Wild animals lived in its shade, and birds nested in its branches.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 22, 'That tree, Your Majesty, is you. For you have grown strong and great; your greatness reaches up to heaven, and your rule to the ends of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 23, '" `Then you saw a messenger, a holy one, coming down from heaven and saying, "Cut down the tree and destroy it. But leave the stump and the roots in the ground, bound with a band of iron and bronze and surrounded by tender grass. Let him be drenched with the dew of heaven. Let him eat grass with the animals of the field for seven periods of time."', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 24, '" `This is what the dream means, Your Majesty, and what the Most High has declared will happen to you.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 25, 'You will be driven from human society, and you will live in the fields with the wild animals. You will eat grass like a cow, and you will be drenched with the dew of heaven. Seven periods of time will pass while you live this way, until you learn that the Most High rules over the kingdoms of the world and gives them to anyone he chooses.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 26, 'But the stump and the roots were left in the ground. This means that you will receive your kingdom back again when you have learned that heaven rules.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 27, '" `O King Nebuchadnezzar, please listen to me. Stop sinning and do what is right. Break from your wicked past by being merciful to the poor. Perhaps then you will continue to prosper.''', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 28, '"But all these things did happen to King Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 29, 'Twelve months later, he was taking a walk on the flat roof of the royal palace in Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 30, 'As he looked out across the city, he said, `Just look at this great city of Babylon! I, by my own mighty power, have built this beautiful city as my royal residence and as an expression of my royal splendor.''', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 31, '"While he was still speaking these words, a voice called down from heaven, `O King Nebuchadnezzar, this message is for you! You are no longer ruler of this kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 32, 'You will be driven from human society. You will live in the fields with the wild animals, and you will eat grass like a cow. Seven periods of time will pass while you live this way, until you learn that the Most High rules over the kingdoms of the world and gives them to anyone he chooses.''', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 33, '"That very same hour the prophecy was fulfilled, and Nebuchadnezzar was driven from human society. He ate grass like a cow, and he was drenched with the dew of heaven. He lived this way until his hair was as long as eagles'' feathers and his nails were like birds'' claws.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 34, '"After this time had passed, I, Nebuchadnezzar, looked up to heaven. My sanity returned, and I praised and worshiped the Most High and honored the one who lives forever. His rule is everlasting, and his kingdom is eternal.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 35, 'All the people of the earth are nothing compared to him. He has the power to do as he pleases among the angels of heaven and with those who live on earth. No one can stop him or challenge him, saying, `What do you mean by doing these things?''', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 36, '"When my sanity returned to me, so did my honor and glory and kingdom. My advisers and officers sought me out, and I was reestablished as head of my kingdom, with even greater honor than before.', 'NLT'),
(31, 4, 37, '"Now I, Nebuchadnezzar, praise and glorify and honor the King of heaven. All his acts are just and true, and he is able to humble those who are proud."', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 1, 'A number of years later, King Belshazzar gave a great feast for a thousand of his nobles and drank wine with them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 2, 'While Belshazzar was drinking, he gave orders to bring in the gold and silver cups that his predecessor, Nebuchadnezzar, had taken from the Temple in Jerusalem, so that he and his nobles, his wives, and his concubines might drink from them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 3, 'So they brought these gold cups taken from the Temple of God in Jerusalem, and the king and his nobles, his wives, and his concubines drank from them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 4, 'They drank toasts from them to honor their idols made of gold, silver, bronze, iron, wood, and stone.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 5, 'At that very moment they saw the fingers of a human hand writing on the plaster wall of the king''s palace, near the lampstand. The king himself saw the hand as it wrote,', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 6, 'and his face turned pale with fear. Such terror gripped him that his knees knocked together and his legs gave way beneath him.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 7, 'The king shouted for the enchanters, astrologers, and fortune-tellers to be brought before him. He said to these wise men of Babylon, "Whoever can read this writing and tell me what it means will be dressed in purple robes of royal honor and will wear a gold chain around his neck. He will become the third highest ruler in the kingdom!"', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 8, 'But when all the king''s wise men came in, none of them could read the writing or tell him what it meant.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 9, 'So the king grew even more alarmed, and his face turned ashen white. His nobles, too, were shaken.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 10, 'But when the queen mother heard what was happening, she hurried to the banquet hall. She said to Belshazzar, "Long live the king! Don''t be so pale and afraid about this.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 11, 'There is a man in your kingdom who has within him the spirit of the holy gods. During Nebuchadnezzar''s reign, this man was found to have insight, understanding, and wisdom as though he himself were a god. Your predecessor, King Nebuchadnezzar, made him chief over all the magicians, enchanters, astrologers, and fortune-tellers of Babylon.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 12, 'This man Daniel, whom the king named Belteshazzar, has a sharp mind and is filled with divine knowledge and understanding. He can interpret dreams, explain riddles, and solve difficult problems. Call for Daniel, and he will tell you what the writing means."', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 13, 'So Daniel was brought in before the king. The king asked him, "Are you Daniel, who was exiled from Judah by my predecessor, King Nebuchadnezzar?', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 14, 'I have heard that you have the spirit of the gods within you and that you are filled with insight, understanding, and wisdom.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 15, 'My wise men and enchanters have tried to read this writing on the wall, but they cannot.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 16, 'I am told that you can give interpretations and solve difficult problems. If you can read these words and tell me their meaning, you will be clothed in purple robes of royal honor, and you will wear a gold chain around your neck. You will become the third highest ruler in the kingdom."', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 17, 'Daniel answered the king, "Keep your gifts or give them to someone else, but I will tell you what the writing means.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 18, 'Your Majesty, the Most High God gave sovereignty, majesty, glory, and honor to your predecessor, Nebuchadnezzar.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 19, 'He made him so great that people of all races and nations and languages trembled before him in fear. He killed those he wanted to kill and spared those he wanted to spare. He honored those he wanted to honor and disgraced those he wanted to disgrace.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 20, 'But when his heart and mind were hardened with pride, he was brought down from his royal throne and stripped of his glory.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 21, 'He was driven from human society. He was given the mind of an animal, and he lived among the wild donkeys. He ate grass like a cow, and he was drenched with the dew of heaven, until he learned that the Most High God rules the kingdoms of the world and appoints anyone he desires to rule over them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 22, '"You are his successor, O Belshazzar, and you knew all this, yet you have not humbled yourself.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 23, 'For you have defied the Lord of heaven and have had these cups from his Temple brought before you. You and your nobles and your wives and concubines have been drinking wine from them while praising gods of silver, gold, bronze, iron, wood, and stone--gods that neither see nor hear nor know anything at all. But you have not honored the God who gives you the breath of life and controls your destiny!', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 24, 'So God has sent this hand to write a message.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 25, '"This is the message that was written: MENE, MENE, TEKEL, PARSIN.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 26, 'This is what these words mean: Mene means `numbered''--God has numbered the days of your reign and has brought it to an end.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 27, 'Tekel means `weighed''--you have been weighed on the balances and have failed the test.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 28, 'Parsin means `divided''--your kingdom has been divided and given to the Medes and Persians."', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 29, 'Then at Belshazzar''s command, Daniel was dressed in purple robes, a gold chain was hung around his neck, and he was proclaimed the third highest ruler in the kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 30, 'That very night Belshazzar, the Babylonian king, was killed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 5, 31, 'And Darius the Mede took over the kingdom at the age of sixty-two.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 1, 'Darius the Mede decided to divide the kingdom into 120 provinces, and he appointed a prince to rule over each province.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 2, 'The king also chose Daniel and two others as administrators to supervise the princes and to watch out for the king''s interests.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 3, 'Daniel soon proved himself more capable than all the other administrators and princes. Because of his great ability, the king made plans to place him over the entire empire.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 4, 'Then the other administrators and princes began searching for some fault in the way Daniel was handling his affairs, but they couldn''t find anything to criticize. He was faithful and honest and always responsible.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 5, 'So they concluded, "Our only chance of finding grounds for accusing Daniel will be in connection with the requirements of his religion."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 6, 'So the administrators and princes went to the king and said, "Long live King Darius!', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 7, 'We administrators, prefects, princes, advisers, and other officials have unanimously agreed that Your Majesty should make a law that will be strictly enforced. Give orders that for the next thirty days anyone who prays to anyone, divine or human--except to Your Majesty--will be thrown to the lions.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 8, 'And let Your Majesty issue and sign this law so it cannot be changed, a law of the Medes and Persians, which cannot be revoked."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 9, 'So King Darius signed the law.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 10, 'But when Daniel learned that the law had been signed, he went home and knelt down as usual in his upstairs room, with its windows open toward Jerusalem. He prayed three times a day, just as he had always done, giving thanks to his God.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 11, 'The officials went together to Daniel''s house and found him praying and asking for God''s help.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 12, 'So they went back to the king and reminded him about his law. "Did you not sign a law that for the next thirty days anyone who prays to anyone, divine or human--except to Your Majesty--will be thrown to the lions?Yes," the king replied, "that decision stands; it is a law of the Medes and Persians, which cannot be revoked."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 13, 'Then they told the king, "That man Daniel, one of the captives from Judah, is paying no attention to you or your law. He still prays to his God three times a day."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 14, 'Hearing this, the king was very angry with himself for signing the law, and he tried to find a way to save Daniel. He spent the rest of the day looking for a way to get Daniel out of this predicament.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 15, 'In the evening the men went together to the king and said, "Your Majesty knows that according to the law of the Medes and the Persians, no law that the king signs can be changed."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 16, 'So at last the king gave orders for Daniel to be arrested and thrown into the den of lions. The king said to him, "May your God, whom you worship continually, rescue you."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 17, 'A stone was brought and placed over the mouth of the den. The king sealed the stone with his own royal seal and the seals of his nobles, so that no one could rescue Daniel from the lions.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 18, 'Then the king returned to his palace and spent the night fasting. He refused his usual entertainment and couldn''t sleep at all that night.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 19, 'Very early the next morning, the king hurried out to the lions'' den.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 20, 'When he got there, he called out in anguish, "Daniel, servant of the living God! Was your God, whom you worship continually, able to rescue you from the lions?"', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 21, 'Daniel answered, "Long live the king!', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 22, 'My God sent his angel to shut the lions'' mouths so that they would not hurt me, for I have been found innocent in his sight. And I have not wronged you, Your Majesty."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 23, 'The king was overjoyed and ordered that Daniel be lifted from the den. Not a scratch was found on him because he had trusted in his God.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 24, 'Then the king gave orders to arrest the men who had maliciously accused Daniel. He had them thrown into the lions'' den, along with their wives and children. The lions leaped on them and tore them apart before they even hit the floor of the den.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 25, 'Then King Darius sent this message to the people of every race and nation and language throughout the world: "Peace and prosperity to you!', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 26, '"I decree that everyone throughout my kingdom should tremble with fear before the God of Daniel. For he is the living God, and he will endure forever. His kingdom will never be destroyed, and his rule will never end.', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 27, 'He rescues and saves his people; he performs miraculous signs and wonders in the heavens and on earth. He has rescued Daniel from the power of the lions."', 'NLT'),
(31, 6, 28, 'So Daniel prospered during the reign of Darius and the reign of Cyrus the Persian.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 1, 'Earlier, during the first year of King Belshazzar''s reign in Babylon, Daniel had a dream and saw visions as he lay in his bed. He wrote the dream down, and this is what he saw.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 2, 'In my vision that night, I, Daniel, saw a great storm churning the surface of a great sea, with strong winds blowing from every direction.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 3, 'Then four huge beasts came up out of the water, each different from the others.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 4, 'The first beast was like a lion with eagles'' wings. As I watched, its wings were pulled off, and it was left standing with its two hind feet on the ground, like a human being. And a human mind was given to it.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 5, 'Then I saw a second beast, and it looked like a bear. It was rearing up on one side, and it had three ribs in its mouth between its teeth. And I heard a voice saying to it, "Get up! Devour many people!"', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 6, 'Then the third of these strange beasts appeared, and it looked like a leopard. It had four wings like birds'' wings on its back, and it had four heads. Great authority was given to this beast.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 7, 'Then in my vision that night, I saw a fourth beast, terrifying, dreadful, and very strong. It devoured and crushed its victims with huge iron teeth and trampled what was left beneath its feet. It was different from any of the other beasts, and it had ten horns.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 8, 'As I was looking at the horns, suddenly another small horn appeared among them. Three of the first horns were wrenched out, roots and all, to make room for it. This little horn had eyes like human eyes and a mouth that was boasting arrogantly.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 9, 'I watched as thrones were put in place and the Ancient One sat down to judge. His clothing was as white as snow, his hair like whitest wool. He sat on a fiery throne with wheels of blazing fire,', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 10, 'and a river of fire flowed from his presence. Millions of angels ministered to him, and a hundred million stood to attend him. Then the court began its session, and the books were opened.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 11, 'I continued to watch because I could hear the little horn''s boastful speech. I kept watching until the fourth beast was killed and its body was destroyed by fire.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 12, 'As for the other three beasts, their authority was taken from them, but they were allowed to live for a while longer.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 13, 'As my vision continued that night, I saw someone who looked like a man coming with the clouds of heaven. He approached the Ancient One and was led into his presence.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 14, 'He was given authority, honor, and royal power over all the nations of the world, so that people of every race and nation and language would obey him. His rule is eternal--it will never end. His kingdom will never be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 15, 'I, Daniel, was troubled by all I had seen, and my visions terrified me.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 16, 'So I approached one of those standing beside the throne and asked him what it all meant. He explained it to me like this:', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 17, '"These four huge beasts represent four kingdoms that will arise from the earth.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 18, 'But in the end, the holy people of the Most High will be given the kingdom, and they will rule forever and ever."', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 19, 'Then I wanted to know the true meaning of the fourth beast, the one so different from the others and so terrifying. It devoured and crushed its victims with iron teeth and bronze claws, and it trampled what was left beneath its feet.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 20, 'I also asked about the ten horns on the fourth beast''s head and the little horn that came up afterward and destroyed three of the other horns. This was the horn that seemed greater than the others and had human eyes and a mouth that was boasting arrogantly.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 21, 'As I watched, this horn was waging war against the holy people and was defeating them,', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 22, 'until the Ancient One came and judged in favor of the holy people of the Most High. Then the time arrived for the holy people to take over the kingdom.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 23, 'Then he said to me, "This fourth beast is the fourth world power that will rule the earth. It will be different from all the others. It will devour the whole world, trampling everything in its path.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 24, 'Its ten horns are ten kings that will rule that empire. Then another king will arise, different from the other ten, who will subdue three of them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 25, 'He will defy the Most High and wear down the holy people of the Most High. He will try to change their sacred festivals and laws, and they will be placed under his control for a time, times, and half a time.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 26, '"But then the court will pass judgment, and all his power will be taken away and completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 27, 'Then the sovereignty, power, and greatness of all the kingdoms under heaven will be given to the holy people of the Most High. They will rule forever, and all rulers will serve and obey them."', 'NLT'),
(31, 7, 28, 'That was the end of the vision. I, Daniel, was terrified by my thoughts and my face was pale with fear, but I kept these things to myself.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 1, 'During the third year of King Belshazzar''s reign, I, Daniel, saw another vision, following the one that had already appeared to me.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 2, 'This time I was at the fortress of Susa, in the province of Elam, standing beside the Ulai River.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 3, 'As I looked up, I saw in front of me a ram with two long horns standing beside the river. One of the horns was longer than the other, even though it had begun to grow later than the shorter one.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 4, 'The ram butted everything out of its way to the west, to the north, and to the south, and no one could stand against it or help its victims. It did as it pleased and became very great.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 5, 'While I was watching, suddenly a male goat appeared from the west, crossing the land so swiftly that it didn''t even touch the ground. This goat, which had one very large horn between its eyes,', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 6, 'headed toward the two-horned ram that I had seen standing beside the river.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 7, 'The goat charged furiously at the ram and struck it, breaking off both its horns. Now the ram was helpless, and the goat knocked it down and trampled it. There was no one who could rescue the ram from the goat''s power.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 8, 'The goat became very powerful. But at the height of its power, its large horn was broken off. In the large horn''s place grew four prominent horns pointing in the four directions of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 9, 'From one of the prominent horns came a small horn whose power grew very great. It extended toward the south and the east and toward the glorious land of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 10, 'His power reached to the heavens where it attacked the heavenly armies, throwing some of the heavenly beings and stars to the ground and trampling them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 11, 'He even challenged the Commander of heaven''s armies by canceling the daily sacrifices offered to him and by destroying his Temple.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 12, 'But the army of heaven was restrained from destroying him for this sin. As a result, sacrilege was committed against the Temple ceremonies, and truth was overthrown. The horn succeeded in everything it did.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 13, 'Then I heard two of the holy ones talking to each other. One of them said, "How long will the events of this vision last? How long will the rebellion that causes desecration stop the daily sacrifices? How long will the Temple and heaven''s armies be trampled on?"', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 14, 'The other replied, "It will take twenty-three hundred evenings and mornings; then the Temple will be restored."', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 15, 'As I, Daniel, was trying to understand the meaning of this vision, someone who looked like a man suddenly stood in front of me.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 16, 'And I heard a human voice calling out from the Ulai River, "Gabriel, tell this man the meaning of his vision."', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 17, 'As Gabriel approached the place where I was standing, I became so terrified that I fell to the ground. "Son of man," he said, "you must understand that the events you have seen in your vision relate to the time of the end."', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 18, 'While he was speaking, I fainted and lay there with my face to the ground. But Gabriel roused me with a touch and helped me to my feet.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 19, 'Then he said, "I am here to tell you what will happen later in the time of wrath. What you have seen pertains to the very end of time.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 20, 'The two-horned ram represents the kings of Media and Persia.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 21, 'The shaggy male goat represents the king of Greece, and the large horn between its eyes represents the first king of the Greek Empire.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 22, 'The four prominent horns that replaced the one large horn show that the Greek Empire will break into four sections with four kings, none of them as great as the first.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 23, '"At the end of their rule, when their sin is at its height, a fierce king, a master of intrigue, will rise to power.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 24, 'He will become very strong, but not by his own power. He will cause a shocking amount of destruction and succeed in everything he does. He will destroy powerful leaders and devastate the holy people.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 25, 'He will be a master of deception, defeating many by catching them off guard. Without warning he will destroy them. He will even take on the Prince of princes in battle, but he will be broken, though not by human power.', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 26, '"This vision about the twenty-three hundred evenings and mornings is true. But none of these things will happen for a long time, so do not tell anyone about them yet."', 'NLT'),
(31, 8, 27, 'Then I, Daniel, was overcome and lay sick for several days. Afterward I got up and performed my duties for the king, but I was greatly troubled by the vision and could not understand it.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 1, 'It was the first year of the reign of Darius the Mede, the son of Ahasuerus, who became king of the Babylonians.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 2, 'During the first year of his reign, I, Daniel, was studying the writings of the prophets. I learned from the word of the LORD, as recorded by Jeremiah the prophet, that Jerusalem must lie desolate for seventy years.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 3, 'So I turned to the Lord God and pleaded with him in prayer and fasting. I wore rough sackcloth and sprinkled myself with ashes.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 4, 'I prayed to the LORD my God and confessed: "O Lord, you are a great and awesome God! You always fulfill your promises of unfailing love to those who love you and keep your commands.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 5, 'But we have sinned and done wrong. We have rebelled against you and scorned your commands and regulations.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 6, 'We have refused to listen to your servants the prophets, who spoke your messages to our kings and princes and ancestors and to all the people of the land.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 7, '"Lord, you are in the right; but our faces are covered with shame, just as you see us now. This is true of us all, including the people of Judah and Jerusalem and all Israel, scattered near and far, wherever you have driven us because of our disloyalty to you.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 8, 'O LORD, we and our kings, princes, and ancestors are covered with shame because we have sinned against you.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 9, 'But the Lord our God is merciful and forgiving, even though we have rebelled against him.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 10, 'We have not obeyed the LORD our God, for we have not followed the laws he gave us through his servants the prophets.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 11, 'All Israel has disobeyed your law and turned away, refusing to listen to your voice. "So now the solemn curses and judgments written in the law of Moses, the servant of God, have been poured out against us because of our sin.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 12, 'You have done exactly what you warned you would do against us and our rulers. Never in all history has there been a disaster like the one that happened in Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 13, 'Every curse written against us in the law of Moses has come true. All the troubles he predicted have taken place. But we have refused to seek mercy from the LORD our God by turning from our sins and recognizing his truth.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 14, 'The LORD has brought against us the disaster he prepared, for we did not obey him, and the LORD our God is just in everything he does.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 15, '"O Lord our God, you brought lasting honor to your name by rescuing your people from Egypt in a great display of power. But we have sinned and are full of wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 16, 'In view of all your faithful mercies, Lord, please turn your furious anger away from your city of Jerusalem, your holy mountain. All the neighboring nations mock Jerusalem and your people because of our sins and the sins of our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 17, '"O our God, hear your servant''s prayer! Listen as I plead. For your own sake, Lord, smile again on your desolate sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 18, '"O my God, listen to me and hear my request. Open your eyes and see our wretchedness. See how your city lies in ruins--for everyone knows that it is yours. We do not ask because we deserve help, but because you are so merciful.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 19, '"O Lord, hear. O Lord, forgive. O Lord, listen and act! For your own sake, O my God, do not delay, for your people and your city bear your name."', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 20, 'I went on praying and confessing my sin and the sins of my people, pleading with the LORD my God for Jerusalem, his holy mountain.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 21, 'As I was praying, Gabriel, whom I had seen in the earlier vision, came swiftly to me at the time of the evening sacrifice.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 22, 'He explained to me, "Daniel, I have come here to give you insight and understanding.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 23, 'The moment you began praying, a command was given. I am here to tell you what it was, for God loves you very much. Now listen, so you can understand the meaning of your vision.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 24, '"A period of seventy sets of seven has been decreed for your people and your holy city to put down rebellion, to bring an end to sin, to atone for guilt, to bring in everlasting righteousness, to confirm the prophetic vision, and to anoint the Most Holy Place.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 25, 'Now listen and understand! Seven sets of seven plus sixty-two sets of seven will pass from the time the command is given to rebuild Jerusalem until the Anointed One comes. Jerusalem will be rebuilt with streets and strong defenses, despite the perilous times.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 26, '"After this period of sixty-two sets of seven, the Anointed One will be killed, appearing to have accomplished nothing, and a ruler will arise whose armies will destroy the city and the Temple. The end will come with a flood, and war and its miseries are decreed from that time to the very end.', 'NLT'),
(31, 9, 27, 'He will make a treaty with the people for a period of one set of seven, but after half this time, he will put an end to the sacrifices and offerings. Then as a climax to all his terrible deeds, he will set up a sacrilegious object that causes desecration, until the end that has been decreed is poured out on this defiler."', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 1, 'In the third year of the reign of King Cyrus of Persia, Daniel (also known as Belteshazzar) had another vision. It concerned events certain to happen in the future--times of war and great hardship--and Daniel understood what the vision meant.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 2, 'When this vision came to me, I, Daniel, had been in mourning for three weeks.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 3, 'All that time I had eaten no rich food or meat, had drunk no wine, and had used no fragrant oils.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 4, 'On April 23, as I was standing beside the great Tigris River,', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 5, 'I looked up and saw a man dressed in linen clothing, with a belt of pure gold around his waist.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 6, 'His body looked like a dazzling gem. From his face came flashes like lightning, and his eyes were like flaming torches. His arms and feet shone like polished bronze, and his voice was like the roaring of a vast multitude of people.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 7, 'I, Daniel, am the only one who saw this vision. The men with me saw nothing, but they were suddenly terrified and ran away to hide.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 8, 'So I was left there all alone to watch this amazing vision. My strength left me, my face grew deathly pale, and I felt very weak.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 9, 'When I heard him speak, I fainted and lay there with my face to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 10, 'Just then a hand touched me and lifted me, still trembling, to my hands and knees.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 11, 'And the man said to me, "O Daniel, greatly loved of God, listen carefully to what I have to say to you. Stand up, for I have been sent to you." When he said this to me, I stood up, still trembling with fear.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 12, 'Then he said, "Don''t be afraid, Daniel. Since the first day you began to pray for understanding and to humble yourself before your God, your request has been heard in heaven. I have come in answer to your prayer.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 13, 'But for twenty-one days the spirit prince of the kingdom of Persia blocked my way. Then Michael, one of the archangels, came to help me, and I left him there with the spirit prince of the kingdom of Persia.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 14, 'Now I am here to explain what will happen to your people in the future, for this vision concerns a time yet to come."', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 15, 'While he was speaking to me, I looked down at the ground, unable to say a word.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 16, 'Then the one who looked like a man touched my lips, and I opened my mouth and began to speak. I said to the one standing in front of me, "I am terrified by the vision I have seen, my lord, and I am very weak.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 17, 'How can someone like me, your servant, talk to you, my lord? My strength is gone, and I can hardly breathe."', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 18, 'Then the one who looked like a man touched me again, and I felt my strength returning.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 19, '"Don''t be afraid," he said, "for you are deeply loved by God. Be at peace; take heart and be strong!" As he spoke these words, I suddenly felt stronger and said to him, "Now you may speak, my lord, for you have strengthened me."', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 20, 'He replied, "Do you know why I have come? Soon I must return to fight against the spirit prince of the kingdom of Persia, and then against the spirit prince of the kingdom of Greece.', 'NLT'),
(31, 10, 21, 'But before I do that, I will tell you what is written in the Book of Truth. (There is no one to help me against these spirit princes except Michael, your spirit prince. 1I have been standing beside Michael as his support and defense since the first year of the reign of Darius the Mede.)', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 1, '***', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 2, '"Now then, I will reveal the truth to you. Three more Persian kings will reign, to be succeeded by a fourth, far richer than the others. Using his wealth for political advantage, he will stir up everyone to war against the kingdom of Greece.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 3, '"Then a mighty king will rise to power who will rule a vast kingdom and accomplish everything he sets out to do.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 4, 'But at the height of his power, his kingdom will be broken apart and divided into four parts. It will not be ruled by the king''s descendants, nor will the kingdom hold the authority it once had. For his empire will be uprooted and given to others.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 5, '"The king of the south will increase in power, but one of this king''s own officials will become more powerful than he and will rule his kingdom with great strength.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 6, '"Some years later, an alliance will be formed between the king of the north and the king of the south. The daughter of the king of the south will be given in marriage to the king of the north to secure the alliance, but she will lose her influence over him, and so will her father. She will be given up along with her supporters.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 7, 'But when one of her relatives becomes king of the south, he will raise an army and enter the fortress of the king of the north and defeat him.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 8, 'When he returns again to Egypt, he will carry back their idols with him, along with priceless gold and silver dishes. For some years afterward he will leave the king of the north alone.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 9, '"Later the king of the north will invade the realm of the king of the south but will soon return to his own land.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 10, 'However, the sons of the king of the north will assemble a mighty army that will advance like a flood and carry the battle as far as the enemy''s fortress.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 11, 'Then the king of the south, in great anger, will rally against the vast forces assembled by the king of the north and will defeat them.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 12, 'After the enemy army is swept away, the king of the south will be filled with pride and will have many thousands of his enemies killed. But his success will be short lived.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 13, '"A few years later, the king of the north will return with a fully equipped army far greater than the one he lost.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 14, 'At that time there will be a general uprising against the king of the south. Lawless ones among your own people will join them in order to fulfill the vision, but they will not succeed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 15, 'Then the king of the north will come and lay siege to a fortified city and capture it. The best troops of the south will not be able to stand in the face of the onslaught.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 16, '"The king of the north will march onward unopposed; none will be able to stop him. He will pause in the glorious land of Israel, intent on destroying it.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 17, 'He will make plans to come with the might of his entire kingdom and will form an alliance with the king of the south. He will give him a daughter in marriage in order to overthrow the kingdom from within, but his plan will fail.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 18, '"After this, he will turn his attention to the coastal cities and conquer many. But a commander from another land will put an end to his insolence and will cause him to retreat in shame.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 19, 'He will take refuge in his own fortresses but will stumble and fall, and he will be seen no more.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 20, '"His successor will be remembered as the king who sent a tax collector to maintain the royal splendor, but after a very brief reign, he will die, though neither in battle nor open conflict.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 21, '"The next to come to power will be a despicable man who is not directly in line for royal succession. But he will slip in when least expected and take over the kingdom by flattery and intrigue.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 22, 'Before him great armies will be swept away, including a covenant prince.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 23, 'By making deceitful promises, he will make various alliances. With a mere handful of followers, he will become strong.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 24, 'Without warning he will enter the richest areas of the land and do something that none of his predecessors ever did--distribute among his followers the plunder and wealth of the rich. He will plot the overthrow of strongholds, but this will last for only a short while.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 25, '"Then he will stir up his courage and raise a great army against the king of the south. The king of the south will go to battle with a mighty army, but to no avail, for plots against him will succeed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 26, 'Those of his own household will bring his downfall. His army will be swept away, and many will be killed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 27, 'Seeking nothing but each other''s harm, these kings will plot against each other at the conference table, attempting to deceive each other. But it will make no difference, for an end will still come at the appointed time.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 28, '"The king of the north will then return home with great riches. On the way he will set himself against the people of the holy covenant, doing much damage before continuing his journey.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 29, '"Then at the appointed time he will once again invade the south, but this time the result will be different.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 30, 'For warships from western coastlands will scare him off, and he will withdraw and return home. But he will vent his anger against the people of the holy covenant and reward those who forsake the covenant.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 31, 'His army will take over the Temple fortress, polluting the sanctuary, putting a stop to the daily sacrifices, and setting up the sacrilegious object that causes desecration.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 32, 'He will flatter those who have violated the covenant and win them over to his side. But the people who know their God will be strong and will resist him.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 33, '"Those who are wise will give instruction to many. But for a time many of these teachers will die by fire and sword, or they will be jailed and robbed.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 34, 'While all these persecutions are going on, a little help will arrive, though many who join them will not be sincere.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 35, 'And some who are wise will fall victim to persecution. In this way, they will be refined and cleansed and made pure until the time of the end, for the appointed time is still to come.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 36, '"The king will do as he pleases, exalting himself and claiming to be greater than every god there is, even blaspheming the God of gods. He will succeed--until the time of wrath is completed. For what has been determined will surely take place.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 37, 'He will have no regard for the gods of his ancestors, or for the god beloved of women, or for any other god, for he will boast that he is greater than them all.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 38, 'Instead of these, he will worship the god of fortresses--a god his ancestors never knew--and lavish on him gold, silver, precious stones, and costly gifts.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 39, 'Claiming this foreign god''s help, he will attack the strongest fortresses. He will honor those who submit to him, appointing them to positions of authority and dividing the land among them as their reward.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 40, '"Then at the time of the end, the king of the south will attack him, and the king of the north will storm out against him with chariots, cavalry, and a vast navy. He will invade various lands and sweep through them like a flood.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 41, 'He will enter the glorious land of Israel, and many nations will fall, but Moab, Edom, and the best part of Ammon will escape.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 42, 'He will conquer many countries, and Egypt will not escape.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 43, 'He will gain control over the gold, silver, and treasures of Egypt, and the Libyans and Ethiopians will be his servants.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 44, '"But then news from the east and the north will alarm him, and he will set out in great anger to destroy many as he goes.', 'NLT'),
(31, 11, 45, 'He will halt between the glorious holy mountain and the sea and will pitch his royal tents there, but while he is there, his time will suddenly run out, and there will be no one to help him.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 1, '"At that time Michael, the archangel who stands guard over your nation, will arise. Then there will be a time of anguish greater than any since nations first came into existence. But at that time every one of your people whose name is written in the book will be rescued.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 2, 'Many of those whose bodies lie dead and buried will rise up, some to everlasting life and some to shame and everlasting contempt.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 3, 'Those who are wise will shine as bright as the sky, and those who turn many to righteousness will shine like stars forever.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 4, 'But you, Daniel, keep this prophecy a secret; seal up the book until the time of the end. Many will rush here and there, and knowledge will increase."', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 5, 'Then I, Daniel, looked and saw two others standing on opposite banks of the river.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 6, 'One of them asked the man dressed in linen, who was now standing above the river, "How long will it be until these shocking events happen?"', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 7, 'The man dressed in linen, who was standing above the river, raised both his hands toward heaven and took this solemn oath by the one who lives forever: "It will go on for a time, times, and half a time. When the shattering of the holy people has finally come to an end, all these things will have happened."', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 8, 'I heard what he said, but I did not understand what he meant. So I asked, "How will all this finally end, my lord?"', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 9, 'But he said, "Go now, Daniel, for what I have said is for the time of the end.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 10, 'Many will be purified, cleansed, and refined by these trials. But the wicked will continue in their wickedness, and none of them will understand. Only those who are wise will know what it means.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 11, '"From the time the daily sacrifice is taken away and the sacrilegious object that causes desecration is set up to be worshiped, there will be 1,290 days.', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 12, 'And blessed are those who wait and remain until the end of the 1,335 days!', 'NLT'),
(31, 12, 13, '"As for you, go your way until the end. You will rest, and then at the end of the days, you will rise again to receive the inheritance set aside for you."', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 1, 'The LORD gave these messages to Hosea son of Beeri during the years when Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah were kings of Judah, and Jeroboam son of Jehoash was king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 2, 'When the LORD first began speaking to Israel through Hosea, he said to him, "Go and marry a prostitute, so some of her children will be born to you from other men. This will illustrate the way my people have been untrue to me, openly committing adultery against the LORD by worshiping other gods."', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 3, 'So Hosea married Gomer, the daughter of Diblaim, and she became pregnant and gave Hosea a son.', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 4, 'And the LORD said, "Name the child Jezreel, for I am about to punish King Jehu''s dynasty to avenge the murders he committed at Jezreel.', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 5, 'In fact, I will put an end to Israel''s independence by breaking its military power in the Jezreel Valley."', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 6, 'Soon Gomer became pregnant again and gave birth to a daughter. And the LORD said to Hosea, "Name your daughter Lo-ruhamah--`Not loved''--for I will no longer show love to the people of Israel or forgive them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 7, 'But I, the LORD their God, will show love to the people of Judah. I will personally free them from their enemies without any help from weapons or armies."', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 8, 'After Gomer had weaned Lo-ruhamah, she again became pregnant and gave birth to a second son.', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 9, 'And the LORD said, "Name him Lo-ammi--`Not my people''--for Israel is not my people, and I am not their God.', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 10, 'Yet the time will come when Israel will prosper and become a great nation. In that day its people will be like the sands of the seashore--too many to count! Then, at the place where they were told, `You are not my people,'' it will be said, `You are children of the living God.''', 'NLT'),
(32, 1, 11, 'Then the people of Judah and Israel will unite under one leader, and they will return from exile together. What a day that will be--the day of Jezreel--when God will again plant his people in his land. 1In that day you will call your brothers Ammi--`My people.'' And you will call your sisters Ruhamah--`The ones I love.''', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 1, '***', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 2, '"But now, call Israel to account, for she is no longer my wife, and I am no longer her husband. Tell her to take off her garish makeup and suggestive clothing and to stop playing the prostitute.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 3, 'If she doesn''t, I will strip her as naked as she was on the day she was born. I will leave her to die of thirst, as in a desert or a dry and barren wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 4, 'And I will not love her children as I would my own because they are not my children! They were conceived in adultery.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 5, 'For their mother is a shameless prostitute and became pregnant in a shameful way. She said, `I''ll run after other lovers and sell myself to them for food and drink, for clothing of wool and linen, and for olive oil.''', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 6, '"But I will fence her in with thornbushes. I will block the road to make her lose her way.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 7, 'When she runs after her lovers, she won''t be able to catch up with them. She will search for them but not find them. Then she will think, `I might as well return to my husband because I was better off with him than I am now.''', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 8, 'She doesn''t realize that it was I who gave her everything she has--the grain, the wine, the olive oil. Even the gold and silver she used in worshiping the god Baal were gifts from me!', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 9, '"But now I will take back the wine and ripened grain I generously provided each harvest season. I will take away the linen and wool clothing I gave her to cover her nakedness.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 10, 'I will strip her naked in public, while all her lovers look on. No one will be able to rescue her from my hands.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 11, 'I will put an end to her annual festivals, her new moon celebrations, and her Sabbath days--all her appointed festivals.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 12, 'I will destroy her vineyards and orchards, things she claims her lovers gave her. I will let them grow into tangled thickets, where only wild animals will eat the fruit.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 13, 'I will punish her for all the times she deserted me, when she burned incense to her images of Baal, put on her earrings and jewels, and went out looking for her lovers," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 14, '"But then I will win her back once again. I will lead her out into the desert and speak tenderly to her there.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 15, 'I will return her vineyards to her and transform the Valley of Trouble into a gateway of hope. She will give herself to me there, as she did long ago when she was young, when I freed her from her captivity in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 16, '"In that coming day," says the LORD, "you will call me `my husband'' instead of `my master.''', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 17, 'O Israel, I will cause you to forget your images of Baal; even their names will no longer be spoken.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 18, 'At that time I will make a covenant with all the wild animals and the birds and the animals that scurry along the ground so that they will not harm you. I will remove all weapons of war from the land, all swords and bows, so you can live unafraid in peace and safety.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 19, 'I will make you my wife forever, showing you righteousness and justice, unfailing love and compassion.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 20, 'I will be faithful to you and make you mine, and you will finally know me as LORD.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 21, '"In that day," says the LORD, "I will answer the pleading of the sky for clouds, which will pour down water on the earth in answer to its cries for rain.', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 22, 'Then the earth will answer the thirsty cries of the grain, the grapes, and the olive trees for moisture. And the whole grand chorus will sing together, `Jezreel''--`God plants!''', 'NLT'),
(32, 2, 23, '"At that time I will plant a crop of Israelites and raise them for myself! I will show love to those I called `Not loved.'' And to those I called `Not my people,'' I will say, `Now you are my people.'' Then they will reply, `You are our God!''"', 'NLT'),
(32, 3, 1, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Go and get your wife again. Bring her back to you and love her, even though she loves adultery. For the LORD still loves Israel even though the people have turned to other gods, offering them choice gifts. "', 'NLT'),
(32, 3, 2, 'So I bought her back for fifteen pieces of silver and about five bushels of barley and a measure of wine.', 'NLT'),
(32, 3, 3, 'Then I said to her, "You must live in my house for many days and stop your prostitution. During this time, you will not have sexual intercourse with anyone, not even with me. "', 'NLT'),
(32, 3, 4, 'This illustrates that Israel will be a long time without a king or prince, and without sacrifices, temple, priests, or even idols!', 'NLT'),
(32, 3, 5, 'But afterward the people will return to the LORD their God and to David''s descendant, their king. They will come trembling in awe to the LORD, and they will receive his good gifts in the last days.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 1, 'Hear the word of the LORD, O people of Israel! The LORD has filed a lawsuit against you, saying: "There is no faithfulness, no kindness, no knowledge of God in your land.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 2, 'You curse and lie and kill and steal and commit adultery. There is violence everywhere, with one murder after another.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 3, 'That is why your land is not producing. It is filled with sadness, and all living things are becoming sick and dying. Even the animals, birds, and fish have begun to disappear.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 4, '"Don''t point your finger at someone else and try to pass the blame! Look, you priests, my complaint is with you!', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 5, 'As a sentence for your crimes, you will stumble in broad daylight, just as you might at night, and so will your false prophets. And I will destroy your mother, Israel.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 6, 'My people are being destroyed because they don''t know me. It is all your fault, you priests, for you yourselves refuse to know me. Now I refuse to recognize you as my priests. Since you have forgotten the laws of your God, I will forget to bless your children.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 7, 'The more priests there are, the more they sin against me. They have exchanged the glory of God for the disgrace of idols.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 8, '"The priests get fed when the people sin and bring their sin offerings to them. So the priests are glad when the people sin!', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 9, '`Like priests, like people''--since the priests are wicked, the people are wicked, too. So now I will punish both priests and people for all their wicked deeds.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 10, 'They will eat and still be hungry. Though they do a big business as prostitutes, they will have no children, for they have deserted the LORD to worship other gods.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 11, '"Alcohol and prostitution have robbed my people of their brains.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 12, 'They are asking a piece of wood to tell them what to do! They think a stick can tell them the future! Longing after idols has made them foolish. They have played the prostitute, serving other gods and deserting their God.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 13, 'They offer sacrifices to idols on the tops of mountains. They go up into the hills to burn incense in the pleasant shade of oaks, poplars, and other trees. "That is why your daughters turn to prostitution, and your daughters-in-law commit adultery.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 14, 'Why should I punish them? For you men are doing the same thing, sinning with whores and shrine prostitutes. O foolish people! You will be destroyed, for you refuse to understand.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 15, '"Though Israel is a prostitute, may Judah avoid such guilt. O Judah, do not join with those who worship me insincerely at Gilgal and at Beth-aven. Their worship is mere pretense as they take oaths in the LORD''s name.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 16, 'Israel is as stubborn as a heifer, so the LORD will put her out to pasture. She will stand alone and unprotected, like a helpless lamb in an open field.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 17, 'Leave her alone because she is married to idolatry.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 18, 'The men of Israel finish up their drinking bouts and off they go to find some prostitutes. Their love for shame is greater than their love for honor.', 'NLT'),
(32, 4, 19, 'So a mighty wind will sweep them away. They will die in shame because they offer sacrifices to idols.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 1, '"Hear this, you priests and all of Israel''s leaders! Listen, all you men of the royal family! These words of judgment are for you: You are doomed! For you have led the people into a snare by worshiping the idols at Mizpah and Tabor.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 2, 'You have dug a deep pit to trap them at Acacia. But never forget--I will settle with all of you for what you have done.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 3, 'I know what you are like, O Israel! You have left me as a prostitute leaves her husband; you are utterly defiled.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 4, 'Your deeds won''t let you return to your God. You are a prostitute through and through, and you cannot know the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 5, '"The arrogance of Israel testifies against her; she will stumble under her load of guilt. Judah, too, will fall with her.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 6, 'Then at last, they will come with their flocks and herds to offer sacrifices to the LORD. But it will be too late! They will not find him, because he has withdrawn from them, and they are now alone.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 7, 'For they have betrayed the honor of the LORD, bearing children that aren''t his. Now their false religion will devour them, along with their wealth.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 8, '"Blow the ram''s horn in Gibeah! Sound the alarm in Ramah! Raise the battle cry in Beth-aven! Lead on into battle, O warriors of Benjamin!', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 9, 'One thing is certain, Israel: When your day of punishment comes, you will become a heap of rubble.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 10, '"The leaders of Judah have become as bad as thieves. So I will pour my anger down on them like a waterfall.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 11, 'The people of Israel will be crushed and broken by my judgment because they are determined to worship idols.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 12, 'I will destroy Israel as a moth consumes wool. I will sap Judah''s strength as dry rot weakens wood.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 13, '"When Israel and Judah saw how sick they were, Israel turned to Assyria, to the great king there, but he could neither help nor cure them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 14, 'I will tear at Israel and Judah as a lion rips apart its prey. I will carry them off, and there will be no one left to rescue them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 5, 15, 'Then I will return to my place until they admit their guilt and look to me for help. For as soon as trouble comes, they will search for me."', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 1, '"Come, let us return to the LORD! He has torn us in pieces; now he will heal us. He has injured us; now he will bandage our wounds.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 2, 'In just a short time, he will restore us so we can live in his presence.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 3, 'Oh, that we might know the LORD! Let us press on to know him! Then he will respond to us as surely as the arrival of dawn or the coming of rains in early spring."', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 4, '"O Israel and Judah, what should I do with you?" asks the LORD. "For your love vanishes like the morning mist and disappears like dew in the sunlight.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 5, 'I sent my prophets to cut you to pieces. I have slaughtered you with my words, threatening you with death. My judgment will strike you as surely as day follows night.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 6, 'I want you to be merciful; I don''t want your sacrifices. I want you to know God; that''s more important than burnt offerings.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 7, '"But like Adam, you broke my covenant and rebelled against me.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 8, 'Gilead is a city of sinners, tracked with footprints of blood.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 9, 'Its citizens are bands of robbers, lying in ambush for their victims. Gangs of priests murder travelers along the road to Shechem and practice every kind of sin.', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 10, 'Yes, I have seen a horrible thing in Israel: My people have defiled themselves by chasing after other gods!', 'NLT'),
(32, 6, 11, '"O Judah, a harvest of punishment is also waiting for you, though I wanted so much to restore the fortunes of my people!', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 1, '"I wanted to heal Israel, but its sins were far too great. Samaria is filled with liars, thieves, and bandits!', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 2, 'Its people don''t realize I am watching them. Their sinful deeds are all around them; I see them all!', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 3, 'The people make the king glad with their wickedness. The princes laugh about the people''s many lies.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 4, 'They are all adulterers, always aflame with lust. They are like an oven that is kept hot even while the baker is still kneading the dough.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 5, '"On royal holidays, the princes get drunk. The king makes a fool of himself and drinks with those who are making fun of him.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 6, 'Their hearts blaze like a furnace with intrigue. Their plot smolders through the night, and in the morning it flames forth like a raging fire.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 7, 'They kill their kings one after another, and no one cries out to me for help.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 8, '"My people of Israel mingle with godless foreigners, picking up their evil ways. Now they have become as worthless as a half-baked cake!', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 9, 'Worshiping foreign gods has sapped their strength, but they don''t even know it. Israel is like an old man with graying hair, unaware of how weak and old he has become.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 10, 'His arrogance testifies against him, yet he doesn''t return to the LORD his God or even try to find him.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 11, '"The people of Israel have become like silly, witless doves, first calling to Egypt, then flying to Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 12, 'But as they fly about, I will throw my net over them and bring them down like a bird from the sky. I will punish them for all their evil ways.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 13, '"How terrible it will be for my people who have deserted me! Let them die, for they have rebelled against me. I wanted to redeem them, but they have only spoken lies about me.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 14, 'They do not cry out to me with sincere hearts. Instead, they sit on their couches and wail. They cut themselves, begging foreign gods for crops and prosperity.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 15, '"I trained them and made them strong, yet now they plot evil against me.', 'NLT'),
(32, 7, 16, 'They look everywhere except to heaven, to the Most High. They are like a crooked bow that always misses its target. Their leaders will be killed by their enemies because of their insolence toward me. Then the people of Egypt will laugh at them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 1, '"Sound the alarm! The enemy descends like an eagle on the people of the LORD, for they have broken my covenant and revolted against my law.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 2, 'Now Israel pleads with me, `Help us, for you are our God!''', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 3, 'But it is too late! The people of Israel have rejected what is good, and now their enemies will chase after them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 4, 'The people have appointed kings and princes, but not with my consent. By making idols for themselves from their silver and gold, they have brought about their own destruction.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 5, '"O Samaria, I reject this calf--this idol you have made. My fury burns against you. How long will you be incapable of innocence?', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 6, 'This calf you worship was crafted by your own hands! It is not God! Therefore, it must be smashed to bits.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 7, '"They have planted the wind and will harvest the whirlwind. The stalks of wheat wither, producing no grain. And if there is any grain, foreigners will eat it.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 8, 'The people of Israel have been swallowed up; they lie among the nations like an old pot that no one wants.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 9, 'Like a wild donkey looking for a mate, they have gone up to Assyria. The people of Israel have sold themselves to many lovers.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 10, 'But though they have sold themselves to many lands, I will now gather them together. Then they will writhe under the burden of the great king!', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 11, '"Israel has built many altars to take away sin, but these very altars became places for sinning!', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 12, 'Even though I gave them all my laws, they act as if those laws don''t apply to them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 13, 'The people of Israel love their rituals of sacrifice, but to me their sacrifices are all meaningless! I will call my people to account for their sins, and I will punish them. They will go back down to Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(32, 8, 14, '"Israel has built great palaces, and Judah has fortified its cities. But they have both forgotten their Maker. Therefore, I will send down fire on their palaces and burn their fortresses."', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 1, 'O people of Israel, do not rejoice as others do. For you have been unfaithful to your God, hiring yourselves out like prostitutes, offering sacrifices to other gods on every threshing floor.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 2, 'So now your harvests will be too small to feed you. The grapes you gather will not quench your thirst.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 3, 'You may no longer stay here in this land of the LORD. You will be carried off to Egypt and Assyria, where you will live on food that is ceremonially unclean.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 4, 'There, far from home, you will not be allowed to pour out wine as a sacrifice to the LORD. None of the sacrifices you offer there will please him. Such sacrifices will be unclean, just as food touched by a person in mourning is unclean. All who present such sacrifices will be defiled. They may eat this food to feed themselves, but they may not offer it to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 5, 'What then will you do on festival days? What will you do on days of feasting in the LORD''s presence?', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 6, 'Even if you escape destruction from Assyria, you will be conquered by Egypt. Memphis will bury you. Briers will take over your treasures of silver; brambles will fill your homes.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 7, 'The time of Israel''s punishment has come; the day of payment is almost here. Soon Israel will know this all too well. "The prophets are crazy!" the people shout. "The inspired men are mad!" So they taunt, for the nation is burdened with sin and shows only hatred for those who love God.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 8, 'The prophet is a watchman for my God over Israel, yet traps are laid in front of him wherever he goes. He faces hostility even in the house of God.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 9, 'The things my people do are as depraved as what they did in Gibeah long ago. God will not forget. He will surely punish them for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 10, 'The LORD says, "O Israel, when I first found you, it was like finding fresh grapes in the desert! When I saw your ancestors, it was like seeing the first ripe figs of the season! But then they deserted me for Baal-peor, giving themselves to that shameful idol. Soon they became as vile as the god they worshiped.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 11, 'The glory of Israel will fly away like a bird, for your children will die at birth or perish in the womb or never even be conceived.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 12, 'Even if your children do survive to grow up, I will take them from you. It will be a terrible day when I turn away and leave you alone.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 13, 'I have watched Israel become as beautiful and pleasant as Tyre. But now Israel will bring out her children to be slaughtered."', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 14, 'O LORD, what should I request for your people? I will ask for wombs that don''t give birth and breasts that give no milk.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 15, 'The LORD says, "All their wickedness began at Gilgal; there I began to hate them. I will drive them from my land because of their evil actions. I will love them no more because all their leaders are rebels.', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 16, 'The people of Israel are stricken. Their roots are dried up; they will bear no more fruit. And if they give birth, I will slaughter their beloved children."', 'NLT'),
(32, 9, 17, 'My God will reject the people of Israel because they will not listen or obey. They will be wanderers, homeless among the nations.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 1, 'How prosperous Israel is--a luxuriant vine loaded with fruit! But the more wealth the people got, the more they poured it on the altars of their foreign gods. The richer the harvests they brought in, the more beautiful the statues and idols they built.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 2, 'The hearts of the people are fickle; they are guilty and must be punished. The LORD will break down their foreign altars and smash their many idols.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 3, 'Then they will say, "We have no king because we didn''t fear the LORD. But what''s the difference? What could a king do for us anyway?"', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 4, 'They spout empty words and make promises they don''t intend to keep. So perverted justice springs up among them like poisonous weeds in a farmer''s field.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 5, 'The people of Samaria tremble for their calf idol at Beth-aven. The people mourn over it, and the priests wail for it, because its glory will be stripped away.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 6, 'This idol they love so much will be carted away with them when they go as captives to Assyria, a gift to the great king there. Israel will be laughed at and shamed because its people have trusted in this idol.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 7, 'Samaria will be cut off, and its king will disappear like a chip of wood on an ocean wave.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 8, 'And the pagan shrines of Aven, the place of Israel''s sin, will crumble. Thorns and thistles will grow up around them. They will beg the mountains to bury them and the hills to fall on them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 9, 'The LORD says, "O Israel, ever since that awful night in Gibeah, there has been only sin and more sin! You have made no progress whatsoever. Was it not right that the wicked men of Gibeah were attacked?', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 10, 'Now I will attack you, too, for your rebellion and disobedience. I will call out the armies of the nations to punish you for your multiplied sins.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 11, '"Israel is like a trained heifer accustomed to treading out the grain--an easy job that she loves. Now I will put a heavy yoke on her tender neck. I will drive her in front of the plow. Israel and Judah must now break up the hard ground; their days of ease are gone.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 12, 'I said, `Plant the good seeds of righteousness, and you will harvest a crop of my love. Plow up the hard ground of your hearts, for now is the time to seek the LORD, that he may come and shower righteousness upon you.''', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 13, '"But you have cultivated wickedness and raised a thriving crop of sins. You have eaten the fruit of lies--trusting in your military might, believing that great armies could make your nation safe!', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 14, 'Now the terrors of war will rise among your people. All your fortifications will fall, just as they did when Shalman destroyed Beth-arbel. Even mothers and children were dashed to death there.', 'NLT'),
(32, 10, 15, 'You will share that fate, Bethel, because of your great wickedness. When the day of judgment dawns, the king of Israel will be completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 1, '"When Israel was a child, I loved him as a son, and I called my son out of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 2, 'But the more I called to him, the more he rebelled, offering sacrifices to the images of Baal and burning incense to idols.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 3, 'It was I who taught Israel how to walk, leading him along by the hand. But he doesn''t know or even care that it was I who took care of him.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 4, 'I led Israel along with my ropes of kindness and love. I lifted the yoke from his neck, and I myself stooped to feed him.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 5, '"But since my people refuse to return to me, they will go back to Egypt and will be forced to serve Assyria.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 6, 'War will swirl through their cities; their enemies will crash through their gates and destroy them, trapping them in their own evil plans.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 7, 'For my people are determined to desert me. They call me the Most High, but they don''t truly honor me.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 8, '"Oh, how can I give you up, Israel? How can I let you go? How can I destroy you like Admah and Zeboiim? My heart is torn within me, and my compassion overflows.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 9, 'No, I will not punish you as much as my burning anger tells me to. I will not completely destroy Israel, for I am God and not a mere mortal. I am the Holy One living among you, and I will not come to destroy.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 10, '"For someday the people will follow the LORD. I will roar like a lion, and my people will return trembling from the west.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 11, 'Like a flock of birds, they will come from Egypt. Flying like doves, they will return from Assyria. And I will bring them home again," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(32, 11, 12, 'Israel surrounds me with lies and deceit, but Judah still walks with God and is faithful to the Holy One.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 1, 'The people of Israel feed on the wind; they chase after the east wind all day long. They multiply lies and violence; they make alliances with Assyria and cut deals with the Egyptians.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 2, 'Now the LORD is bringing a lawsuit against Judah. He is about to punish Jacob for all his deceitful ways.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 3, 'Before Jacob was born, he struggled with his brother; when he became a man, he even fought with God.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 4, 'Yes, he wrestled with the angel and won. He wept and pleaded for a blessing from him. There at Bethel he met God face to face, and God spoke to him--', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 5, 'the LORD God Almighty, the LORD is his name!', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 6, 'So now, come back to your God! Act on the principles of love and justice, and always live in confident dependence on your God.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 7, 'But no, the people are like crafty merchants selling from dishonest scales--they love to cheat.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 8, 'Israel boasts, "I am rich, and I''ve gotten it all by myself! No one can say I got it by cheating! My record is spotless!"', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 9, '"I am the LORD your God, who rescued you from your slavery in Egypt. And I will make you live in tents again, as you do each year when you celebrate the Festival of Shelters.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 10, 'I sent my prophets to warn you with many visions and parables."', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 11, 'But Gilead is filled with sinners who worship idols. And in Gilgal, too, they sacrifice bulls; their altars are lined up like the heaps of stone along the edges of a plowed field.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 12, 'Jacob fled to the land of Aram and earned a wife by tending sheep.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 13, 'Then the LORD led Jacob''s descendants, the Israelites, out of Egypt by a prophet, who guided and protected them.', 'NLT'),
(32, 12, 14, 'But the people of Israel have bitterly provoked the LORD, so their Lord will now sentence them to death in payment for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 1, 'In the past when the tribe of Ephraim spoke, the people shook with fear because the other Israelite tribes looked up to them. But the people of Ephraim sinned by worshiping Baal and thus sealed their destruction.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 2, 'Now they keep on sinning by making silver idols to worship--images shaped skillfully with human hands. "Sacrifice to these," they cry, "and kiss the calf idols!"', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 3, 'Therefore, they will disappear like the morning mist, like dew in the morning sun, like chaff blown by the wind, like smoke from a chimney.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 4, '"I am the LORD your God, who rescued you from your slavery in Egypt. You have no God but me, for there is no other savior.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 5, 'I took care of you in the wilderness, in that dry and thirsty land.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 6, 'But when you had eaten and were satisfied, then you became proud and forgot me.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 7, 'So now I will attack you like a lion, or like a leopard that lurks along the road.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 8, 'I will rip you to pieces like a bear whose cubs have been taken away. I will tear you apart and devour you like a hungry lion.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 9, '"You are about to be destroyed, O Israel, though I am your helper.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 10, 'Where now is your king? Why don''t you call on him for help? Where are all the leaders of the land? You asked for them, now let them save you!', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 11, 'In my anger I gave you kings, and in my fury I took them away.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 12, '"The sins of Ephraim have been collected and stored away for punishment.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 13, 'The people have been offered new birth, but they are like a child who resists being born. How stubborn they are! How foolish!', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 14, 'Should I ransom them from the grave? Should I redeem them from death? O death, bring forth your terrors! O grave, bring forth your plagues! For I will not relent!', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 15, 'Ephraim was the most fruitful of all his brothers, but the east wind--a blast from the LORD--will arise in the desert. It will blow hard against the people of Ephraim, drying up their land. All their flowing springs and wells will disappear. Every precious thing they have will be plundered and carried away.', 'NLT'),
(32, 13, 16, 'The people of Samaria must bear the consequences of their guilt because they rebelled against their God. They will be killed by an invading army, their little ones dashed to death against the ground, their pregnant women ripped open by swords."', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 1, 'Return, O Israel, to the LORD your God, for your sins have brought you down.', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 2, 'Bring your petitions, and return to the LORD. Say to him, "Forgive all our sins and graciously receive us, so that we may offer you the sacrifice of praise.', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 3, 'Assyria cannot save us, nor can our strength in battle. Never again will we call the idols we have made `our gods.'' No, in you alone do the orphans find mercy."', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 4, 'The LORD says, "Then I will heal you of your idolatry and faithlessness, and my love will know no bounds, for my anger will be gone forever!', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 5, 'I will be to Israel like a refreshing dew from heaven. It will blossom like the lily; it will send roots deep into the soil like the cedars in Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 6, 'Its branches will spread out like those of beautiful olive trees, as fragrant as the cedar forests of Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 7, 'My people will return again to the safety of their land. They will flourish like grain and blossom like grapevines. They will be as fragrant as the wines of Lebanon.', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 8, '"O Israel, stay away from idols! I am the one who looks after you and cares for you. I am like a tree that is always green, giving my fruit to you all through the year."', 'NLT'),
(32, 14, 9, 'Let those who are wise understand these things. Let those who are discerning listen carefully. The paths of the LORD are true and right, and righteous people live by walking in them. But sinners stumble and fall along the way.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 1, 'The LORD gave this message to Joel son of Pethuel.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 2, 'Hear this, you leaders of the people! Everyone listen! In all your history, has anything like this ever happened before?', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 3, 'Tell your children about it in the years to come. Pass the awful story down from generation to generation.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 4, 'After the cutting locusts finished eating the crops, the swarming locusts took what was left! After them came the hopping locusts, and then the stripping locusts, too!', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 5, 'Wake up, you drunkards, and weep! All the grapes are ruined, and all your new wine is gone!', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 6, 'A vast army of locusts has invaded my land. It is a terrible army, too numerous to count! Its teeth are as sharp as the teeth of lions!', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 7, 'They have destroyed my grapevines and fig trees, stripping their bark and leaving the branches white and bare.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 8, 'Weep with sorrow, as a virgin weeps when her fiance has died.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 9, 'There is no grain or wine to offer at the Temple of the LORD. The priests are mourning because there are no offerings. Listen to the weeping of these ministers of the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 10, 'The fields are ruined and empty of crops. The grain, the wine, and the olive oil are gone.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 11, 'Despair, all you farmers! Wail, all you vine growers! Weep, because the wheat and barley--yes, all the field crops--are ruined.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 12, 'The grapevines and the fig trees have all withered. The pomegranate trees, palm trees, and apple trees--yes, all the fruit trees--have dried up. All joy has dried up with them.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 13, 'Dress yourselves in sackcloth, you priests! Wail, you who serve before the altar! Come, spend the night in sackcloth, you ministers of my God! There is no grain or wine to offer at the Temple of your God.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 14, 'Announce a time of fasting; call the people together for a solemn meeting. Bring the leaders and all the people into the Temple of the LORD your God, and cry out to him there.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 15, 'The day of the LORD is on the way, the day when destruction comes from the Almighty. How terrible that day will be!', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 16, 'We watch as our food disappears before our very eyes. There are no joyful celebrations in the house of our God.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 17, 'The seeds die in the parched ground, and the grain crops fail. The barns and granaries stand empty and abandoned.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 18, 'How the animals moan with hunger! The cattle wander about confused because there is no pasture for them. The sheep bleat in misery.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 19, 'LORD, help us! The fire has consumed the pastures and burned up all the trees.', 'NLT'),
(33, 1, 20, 'Even the wild animals cry out to you because they have no water to drink. The streams have dried up, and fire has consumed the pastures.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 1, 'Blow the trumpet in Jerusalem! Sound the alarm on my holy mountain! Let everyone tremble in fear because the day of the LORD is upon us.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 2, 'It is a day of darkness and gloom, a day of thick clouds and deep blackness. Suddenly, like dawn spreading across the mountains, a mighty army appears! How great and powerful they are! The likes of them have not been seen before and never will be seen again.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 3, 'Fire burns in front of them and follows them in every direction! Ahead of them the land lies as fair as the Garden of Eden in all its beauty. Behind them is nothing but desolation; not one thing escapes.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 4, 'They look like tiny horses, and they run as fast.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 5, 'Look at them as they leap along the mountaintops! Listen to the noise they make--like the rumbling of chariots, like the roar of a fire sweeping across a field, or like a mighty army moving into battle.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 6, 'Fear grips all the people; every face grows pale with fright.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 7, 'The attackers march like warriors and scale city walls like trained soldiers. Straight forward they march, never breaking rank.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 8, 'They never jostle each other; each moves in exactly the right place. They lunge through the gaps, and no weapon can stop them.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 9, 'They swarm over the city and run along its walls. They enter all the houses, climbing like thieves through the windows.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 10, 'The earth quakes as they advance, and the heavens tremble. The sun and moon grow dark, and the stars no longer shine.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 11, 'The LORD leads them with a shout! This is his mighty army, and they follow his orders. The day of the LORD is an awesome, terrible thing. Who can endure it?', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 12, 'That is why the LORD says, "Turn to me now, while there is time! Give me your hearts. Come with fasting, weeping, and mourning.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 13, 'Don''t tear your clothing in your grief; instead, tear your hearts." Return to the LORD your God, for he is gracious and merciful. He is not easily angered. He is filled with kindness and is eager not to punish you.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 14, 'Who knows? Perhaps even yet he will give you a reprieve, sending you a blessing instead of this terrible curse. Perhaps he will give you so much that you will be able to offer grain and wine to the LORD your God as before!', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 15, 'Blow the trumpet in Jerusalem! Announce a time of fasting; call the people together for a solemn meeting.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 16, 'Bring everyone--the elders, the children, and even the babies. Call the bridegroom from his quarters and the bride from her private room.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 17, 'The priests, who minister in the LORD''s presence, will stand between the people and the altar, weeping. Let them pray, "Spare your people, LORD! They belong to you, so don''t let them become an object of mockery. Don''t let their name become a proverb of unbelieving foreigners who say, `Where is the God of Israel? He must be helpless!''"', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 18, 'Then the LORD will pity his people and be indignant for the honor of his land!', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 19, 'He will reply, "Look! I am sending you grain and wine and olive oil, enough to satisfy your needs. You will no longer be an object of mockery among the surrounding nations.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 20, 'I will remove these armies from the north and send them far away. I will drive them back into the parched wastelands, where they will die. Those in the rear will go into the Dead Sea; those at the front will go into the Mediterranean. The stench of their rotting bodies will rise over the land." Surely the LORD has done great things!', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 21, 'Don''t be afraid, my people! Be glad now and rejoice because the LORD has done great things.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 22, 'Don''t be afraid, you animals of the field! The pastures will soon be green. The trees will again be filled with luscious fruit; fig trees and grapevines will flourish once more.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 23, 'Rejoice, you people of Jerusalem! Rejoice in the LORD your God! For the rains he sends are an expression of his grace. Once more the autumn rains will come, as well as the rains of spring.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 24, 'The threshing floors will again be piled high with grain, and the presses will overflow with wine and olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 25, 'The LORD says, "I will give you back what you lost to the stripping locusts, the cutting locusts, the swarming locusts, and the hopping locusts. It was I who sent this great destroying army against you.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 26, 'Once again you will have all the food you want, and you will praise the LORD your God, who does these miracles for you. Never again will my people be disgraced like this.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 27, 'Then you will know that I am here among my people of Israel and that I alone am the LORD your God. My people will never again be disgraced like this.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 28, '"Then after I have poured out my rains again, I will pour out my Spirit upon all people. Your sons and daughters will prophesy. Your old men will dream dreams. Your young men will see visions.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 29, 'In those days, I will pour out my Spirit even on servants, men and women alike.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 30, '"I will cause wonders in the heavens and on the earth--blood and fire and pillars of smoke.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 31, 'The sun will be turned into darkness, and the moon will turn bloodred before that great and terrible day of the LORD arrives.', 'NLT'),
(33, 2, 32, 'And anyone who calls on the name of the LORD will be saved. There will be people on Mount Zion in Jerusalem who escape, just as the LORD has said. These will be among the survivors whom the LORD has called.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 1, '"At that time, when I restore the prosperity of Judah and Jerusalem," says the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 2, '"I will gather the armies of the world into the valley of Jehoshaphat. There I will judge them for harming my people, for scattering my inheritance among the nations, and for dividing up my land.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 3, 'They cast lots to decide which of my people would be their slaves. They traded young boys for prostitutes and little girls for enough wine to get drunk.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 4, '"What do you have against me, Tyre and Sidon and you cities of Philistia? Are you trying to take revenge on me? If you are, then watch out! I will strike swiftly and pay you back for everything you have done.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 5, 'You have taken my silver and gold and all my precious treasures, and you have carried them off to your pagan temples.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 6, 'You have sold the people of Judah and Jerusalem to the Greeks, who took them far from their homeland.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 7, 'But I will bring them back again from all these places to which you sold them, and I will pay you back for all you have done.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 8, 'I will sell your sons and daughters to the people of Judah, and they will sell them to the peoples of Arabia, a nation far away. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 9, 'Say to the nations far and wide: "Get ready for war! Call out your best warriors! Let all your fighting men advance for the attack!', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 10, 'Beat your plowshares into swords and your pruning hooks into spears. Train even your weaklings to be warriors.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 11, 'Come quickly, all you nations everywhere! Gather together in the valley." And now, O LORD, call out your warriors!', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 12, '"Let the nations be called to arms. Let them march to the valley of Jehoshaphat. There I, the LORD, will sit to pronounce judgment on them all.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 13, 'Now let the sickle do its work, for the harvest is ripe. Come, tread the winepress because it is full. The storage vats are overflowing with the wickedness of these people."', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 14, 'Thousands upon thousands are waiting in the valley of decision. It is there that the day of the LORD will soon arrive.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 15, 'The sun and moon will grow dark, and the stars will no longer shine.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 16, 'The LORD''s voice will roar from Zion and thunder from Jerusalem, and the earth and heavens will begin to shake. But to his people of Israel, the LORD will be a welcoming refuge and a strong fortress.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 17, '"Then you will know that I, the LORD your God, live in Zion, my holy mountain. Jerusalem will be holy forever, and foreign armies will never conquer her again.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 18, 'In that day the mountains will drip with sweet wine, and the hills will flow with milk. Water will fill the dry streambeds of Judah, and a fountain will burst forth from the LORD''s Temple, watering the arid valley of acacias.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 19, 'Egypt will become a wasteland and Edom a wilderness, because they attacked Judah and killed her innocent people.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 20, '"But Judah will remain forever, and Jerusalem will endure through all future generations.', 'NLT'),
(33, 3, 21, 'I will pardon my people''s crimes, which I have not yet pardoned; and I, the LORD, will make my home in Jerusalem with my people."', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 1, 'This message was given to Amos, a shepherd from the town of Tekoa in Judah. He received this message in visions two years before the earthquake, when Uzziah was king of Judah and Jeroboam II, the son of Jehoash, was king of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 2, 'This is his report of what he saw and heard: "The LORD''s voice roars from his Temple on Mount Zion; he thunders from Jerusalem! Suddenly, the lush pastures of the shepherds dry up. All the grass on Mount Carmel withers and dies."', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 3, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Damascus have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They beat down my people in Gilead as grain is threshed with threshing sledges of iron.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 4, 'So I will send down fire on King Hazael''s palace, and the fortresses of King Ben-hadad will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 5, 'I will break down the gates of Damascus and slaughter its people all the way to the valley of Aven. I will destroy the ruler in Beth-eden, and the people of Aram will return to Kir as slaves. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 6, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Gaza have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They sent my people into exile, selling them as slaves in Edom.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 7, 'So I will send down fire on the walls of Gaza, and all its fortresses will be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 8, 'I will slaughter the people of Ashdod and destroy the king of Ashkelon. Then I will turn to attack Ekron, and the few Philistines still left will be killed. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 9, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Tyre have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They broke their treaty of brotherhood with Israel, selling whole villages as slaves to Edom.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 10, 'So I will send down fire on the walls of Tyre, and all its fortresses will be destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 11, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Edom have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They chased down their relatives, the Israelites, with swords. They showed them no mercy and were unrelenting in their anger.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 12, 'So I will send down fire on Teman, and the fortresses of Bozrah will be destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 13, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Ammon have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! When they attacked Gilead to extend their borders, they committed cruel crimes, ripping open pregnant women with their swords.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 14, 'So I will send down fire on the walls of Rabbah, and all its fortresses will be destroyed. There will be wild shouts during the battle, swirling like a whirlwind in a mighty storm.', 'NLT'),
(34, 1, 15, 'And their king and his princes will go into exile together. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 1, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Moab have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They desecrated the tomb of Edom''s king and burned his bones to ashes.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 2, 'So I will send down fire on the land of Moab, and all the fortresses in Kerioth will be destroyed. The people will fall in the noise of battle, as the warriors shout and the trumpets blare.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 3, 'And I will destroy their king and slaughter all their princes. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 4, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Judah have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They have rejected the laws of the LORD, refusing to obey him. They have been led astray by the same lies that deceived their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 5, 'So I will send down fire on Judah, and all the fortresses of Jerusalem will be destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 6, 'This is what the LORD says: "The people of Israel have sinned again and again, and I will not forget it. I will not let them go unpunished any longer! They have perverted justice by selling honest people for silver and poor people for a pair of sandals.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 7, 'They trample helpless people in the dust and deny justice to those who are oppressed. Both father and son sleep with the same woman, corrupting my holy name.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 8, 'At their religious festivals, they lounge around in clothing stolen from their debtors. In the house of their god, they present offerings of wine purchased with stolen money.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 9, '"Yet think of all I did for my people! I destroyed the Amorites before my people arrived in the land. The Amorites were as tall as cedar trees and strong as oaks, but I destroyed their fruit and dug out their roots.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 10, 'It was I who rescued you from Egypt and led you through the desert for forty years so you could possess the land of the Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 11, 'I chose some of your sons to be prophets and others to be Nazirites. Can you deny this, my people of Israel?" asks the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 12, '"But you caused the Nazirites to sin by making them drink your wine, and you said to my prophets, `Shut up!''', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 13, '"So I will make you groan as a wagon groans when it is loaded down with grain.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 14, 'Your fastest runners will not get away. The strongest among you will become weak. Even the mightiest warriors will be unable to save themselves.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 15, 'The archers will fail to stand their ground. The swiftest soldiers won''t be fast enough to escape. Even warriors on horses won''t be able to outrun the danger.', 'NLT'),
(34, 2, 16, 'On that day, the most courageous of your fighting men will drop their weapons and run for their lives. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 1, 'Listen to this message that the LORD has spoken against you, O people of Israel and Judah--the entire family I rescued from Egypt:', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 2, '"From among all the families on the earth, I chose you alone. That is why I must punish you for all your sins."', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 3, 'Can two people walk together without agreeing on the direction?', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 4, 'Does a lion ever roar in a thicket without first finding a victim? Does a young lion growl in its den without first catching its prey?', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 5, 'Does a bird ever get caught in a trap that has no bait? Does a trap ever spring shut when there''s nothing there to catch?', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 6, 'When the war trumpet blares, shouldn''t the people be alarmed? When disaster comes to a city, isn''t it because the LORD planned it?', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 7, '"But always, first of all, I warn you through my servants the prophets. I, the Sovereign LORD, have now done this."', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 8, 'The lion has roared--tremble in fear! The Sovereign LORD has spoken--I dare not refuse to proclaim his message!', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 9, 'Announce this to the leaders of Philistia and Egypt: "Take your seats now on the hills around Samaria, and witness the scandalous spectacle of all Israel''s crimes."', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 10, '"My people have forgotten what it means to do right," says the LORD. "Their fortresses are filled with wealth taken by theft and violence.', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 11, 'Therefore," says the Sovereign LORD, "an enemy is coming! He will surround them and shatter their defenses. Then he will plunder all their fortresses."', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 12, 'This is what the LORD says: "A shepherd who tries to rescue a sheep from a lion''s mouth will recover only two legs and a piece of ear. So it will be when the Israelites in Samaria are rescued with only a broken chair and a tattered pillow.', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 13, 'Now listen to this, and announce it throughout all Israel, "says the Lord, the LORD God Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 14, '"On the very day I punish Israel for its sins, I will destroy the pagan altars at Bethel. The horns of the altar will be cut off and fall to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(34, 3, 15, 'And I will destroy the beautiful homes of the wealthy--their winter mansions and their summer houses, too--all their palaces filled with ivory. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 1, 'Listen to me, you "fat cows" of Samaria, you women who oppress the poor and crush the needy and who are always asking your husbands for another drink!', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 2, 'The Sovereign LORD has sworn this by his holiness: "The time will come when you will be led away with hooks in your noses. Every last one of you will be dragged away like a fish on a hook!', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 3, 'You will leave by going straight through the breaks in the wall; you will be thrown from your fortresses. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 4, '"Go ahead and offer your sacrifices to the idols at Bethel and Gilgal. Keep on disobeying--your sins are mounting up! Offer sacrifices each morning and bring your tithes every three days!', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 5, 'Present your bread made with yeast as an offering of thanksgiving. Then give your extra voluntary offerings so you can brag about it everywhere! This is the kind of thing you Israelites love to do," says the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 6, '"I brought hunger to every city and famine to every town. But still you wouldn''t return to me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 7, '"I kept the rain from falling when you needed it the most, ruining all your crops. I sent rain on one town but withheld it from another. Rain fell on one field, while another field withered away.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 8, 'People staggered from one town to another for a drink of water, but there was never enough. But still you wouldn''t return to me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 9, '"I struck your farms and vineyards with blight and mildew. Locusts devoured all your fig and olive trees. But still you wouldn''t return to me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 10, '"I sent plagues against you like the plagues I sent against Egypt long ago. I killed your young men in war and slaughtered all your horses. The stench of death filled the air! But still you wouldn''t return to me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 11, '"I destroyed some of your cities, as I destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah. Those of you who survived were like half-burned sticks snatched from a fire. But still you wouldn''t return to me," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 12, '"Therefore, I will bring upon you all these further disasters I have announced. Prepare to meet your God as he comes in judgment, you people of Israel!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 4, 13, 'For the LORD is the one who shaped the mountains, stirs up the winds, and reveals his every thought. He turns the light of dawn into darkness and treads the mountains under his feet. The LORD God Almighty is his name!', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 1, 'Listen, you people of Israel! Listen to this funeral song I am singing:', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 2, '"The virgin Israel has fallen, never to rise again! She lies forsaken on the ground, with none to raise her up."', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 3, 'The Sovereign LORD says: "When one of your cities sends a thousand men to battle, only a hundred will return. When a town sends a hundred, only ten will come back alive."', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 4, 'Now this is what the LORD says to the family of Israel: "Come back to me and live!', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 5, 'Don''t go to worship the idols of Bethel, Gilgal, or Beersheba. For the people of Gilgal will be dragged off into exile, and the people of Bethel will come to nothing."', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 6, 'Come back to the LORD and live! If you don''t, he will roar through Israel like a fire, devouring you completely. Your gods in Bethel certainly won''t be able to quench the flames!', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 7, 'You wicked people! You twist justice, making it a bitter pill for the poor and oppressed. Righteousness and fair play are meaningless fictions to you.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 8, 'It is the LORD who created the stars, the Pleiades and Orion. It is he who turns darkness into morning and day into night. It is he who draws up water from the oceans and pours it down as rain on the land. The LORD is his name!', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 9, 'With blinding speed and power he destroys the strong, crushing all their defenses.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 10, 'How you hate honest judges! How you despise people who tell the truth!', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 11, 'You trample the poor and steal what little they have through taxes and unfair rent. Therefore, you will never live in the beautiful stone houses you are building. You will never drink wine from the lush vineyards you are planting.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 12, 'For I know the vast number of your sins and rebellions. You oppress good people by taking bribes and deprive the poor of justice in the courts.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 13, 'So those who are wise will keep quiet, for it is an evil time.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 14, 'Do what is good and run from evil--that you may live! Then the LORD God Almighty will truly be your helper, just as you have claimed he is.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 15, 'Hate evil and love what is good; remodel your courts into true halls of justice. Perhaps even yet the LORD God Almighty will have mercy on his people who remain.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 16, 'Therefore, this is what the Lord, the LORD God Almighty, says: "There will be crying in all the public squares and in every street. Call for the farmers to weep with you, and summon professional mourners to wail and lament.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 17, 'There will be wailing in every vineyard, for I will pass through and destroy them all. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 18, 'How terrible it will be for you who say, "If only the day of the LORD were here! For then the LORD would rescue us from all our enemies." But you have no idea what you are wishing for. That day will not bring light and prosperity, but darkness and disaster.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 19, 'In that day you will be like a man who runs from a lion--only to meet a bear. After escaping the bear, he leans his hand against a wall in his house--and is bitten by a snake.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 20, 'Yes, the day of the LORD will be a dark and hopeless day, without a ray of joy or hope.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 21, '"I hate all your show and pretense--the hypocrisy of your religious festivals and solemn assemblies.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 22, 'I will not accept your burnt offerings and grain offerings. I won''t even notice all your choice peace offerings.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 23, 'Away with your hymns of praise! They are only noise to my ears. I will not listen to your music, no matter how lovely it is.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 24, 'Instead, I want to see a mighty flood of justice, a river of righteous living that will never run dry.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 25, '"Was it to me you were bringing sacrifices and offerings during the forty years in the wilderness, Israel?', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 26, 'No, your real interest was in your pagan gods--Sakkuth your king god and Kaiwan your star god--the images you yourselves made.', 'NLT'),
(34, 5, 27, 'So I will send you into exile, to a land east of Damascus," says the LORD, whose name is God Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 1, 'How terrible it will be for you who lounge in luxury and think you are secure in Jerusalem and Samaria! You are famous and popular in Israel, you to whom the people go for help.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 2, 'Go over to Calneh and see what happened there. Then go to the great city of Hamath and on down to the Philistine city of Gath. You are no better than they were, and look at how they were destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 3, 'You push away every thought of coming disaster, but your actions only bring the day of judgment closer.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 4, 'How terrible it will be for you who sprawl on ivory beds surrounded with luxury, eating the meat of tender lambs and choice calves.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 5, 'You sing idle songs to the sound of the harp, and you fancy yourselves to be great musicians, as King David was.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 6, 'You drink wine by the bowlful, and you perfume yourselves with exotic fragrances, caring nothing at all that your nation is going to ruin.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 7, 'Therefore, you will be the first to be led away as captives. Suddenly, all your revelry will end.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 8, 'The Sovereign LORD has sworn by his own name, and this is what he, the LORD God Almighty, says: "I despise the pride and false glory of Israel, and I hate their beautiful homes. I will give this city and everything in it to their enemies."', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 9, 'If there are ten men left in one house, they will all die.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 10, 'And when a close relative--one who is responsible for burning the dead--goes into the house to carry away a dead body, he will ask the last survivor, "Is there anyone else with you?" And the person will answer, "No!" Then he will say, "Hush! Don''t even whisper the name of the LORD. He might hear you!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 11, 'When the LORD gives the command, homes both great and small will be smashed to pieces.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 12, 'Can horses gallop over rocks? Can oxen be used to plow rocks? Stupid even to ask--but that''s how stupid you are when you turn justice into poison and make bitter the sweet fruit of righteousness.', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 13, 'And just as stupid is this bragging about your conquest of Lo-debar. You boast, "Didn''t we take Karnaim by our own strength and power?"', 'NLT'),
(34, 6, 14, '"O people of Israel, I am about to bring an enemy nation against you," says the LORD God Almighty. "It will oppress you bitterly throughout your land--from Lebo-hamath in the north to the Arabah Valley in the south."', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 1, 'The Sovereign LORD showed me a vision. I saw him preparing to send a vast swarm of locusts over the land. This was after the king''s share had been harvested from the fields and as the main crop was coming up.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 2, 'In my vision the locusts ate everything in sight that was green. Then I said, "O Sovereign LORD, please forgive your people! Unless you relent, Israel will not survive, for we are only a small nation."', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 3, 'So the LORD relented and did not fulfill the vision. "I won''t do it," he said.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 4, 'Then the Sovereign LORD showed me another vision. I saw him preparing to punish his people with a great fire. The fire had burned up the depths of the sea and was devouring the entire land.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 5, 'Then I said, "O Sovereign LORD, please don''t do it. Unless you relent, Israel will not survive, for we are only a small nation."', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 6, 'Then the LORD turned from this plan, too. "I won''t do that either," said the Sovereign LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 7, 'Then he showed me another vision. I saw the Lord standing beside a wall that had been built using a plumb line. He was checking it with a plumb line to see if it was straight.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 8, 'And the LORD said to me, "Amos, what do you see?" I answered, "A plumb line." And the Lord replied, "I will test my people with this plumb line. I will no longer ignore all their sins.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 9, 'The pagan shrines of your ancestors and the temples of Israel will be destroyed, and I will bring the dynasty of King Jeroboam to a sudden end."', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 10, 'But when Amaziah, the priest of Bethel, heard what Amos was saying, he rushed a message to King Jeroboam: "Amos is hatching a plot against you right here on your very doorstep! What he is saying is intolerable. It will lead to rebellion all across the land.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 11, 'He is saying, `Jeroboam will soon be killed and the people of Israel will be sent away into exile.''"', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 12, 'Then Amaziah sent orders to Amos: "Get out of here, you seer! Go on back to the land of Judah and do your preaching there!', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 13, 'Don''t bother us here in Bethel with your prophecies, especially not here where the royal sanctuary is!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 14, 'But Amos replied, "I''m not one of your professional prophets. I certainly never trained to be one. I''m just a shepherd, and I take care of fig trees.', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 15, 'But the LORD called me away from my flock and told me, `Go and prophesy to my people in Israel.''', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 16, '"Now then, listen to this message from the LORD! You say, `Don''t prophesy against Israel. Stop preaching against my people. ''', 'NLT'),
(34, 7, 17, 'But this is what the LORD says: Because you have refused to listen, your wife will become a prostitute in this city, and your sons and daughters will be killed. Your land will be divided up, and you yourself will die in a foreign land. And the people of Israel will certainly become captives in exile, far from their homeland."', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 1, 'Then the Sovereign LORD showed me another vision. In it I saw a basket filled with ripe fruit.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 2, '"What do you see, Amos?" he asked. I replied, "A basket full of ripe fruit." Then the LORD said, "This fruit represents my people of Israel--ripe for punishment! I will not delay their punishment again.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 3, 'In that day the riotous sounds of singing in the Temple will turn to wailing. Dead bodies will be scattered everywhere. They will be carried out of the city in silence. I, the Sovereign LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 4, 'Listen to this, you who rob the poor and trample the needy!', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 5, 'You can''t wait for the Sabbath day to be over and the religious festivals to end so you can get back to cheating the helpless. You measure out your grain in false measures and weigh it out on dishonest scales.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 6, 'And you mix the wheat you sell with chaff swept from the floor! Then you enslave poor people for a debt of one piece of silver or a pair of sandals.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 7, 'Now the LORD has sworn this oath by his own name, the Pride of Israel: "I will never forget the wicked things you have done!', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 8, 'The earth will tremble for your deeds, and everyone will mourn. The land will rise up like the Nile River at floodtime, toss about, and sink again.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 9, 'At that time," says the Sovereign LORD, "I will make the sun go down at noon and darken the earth while it is still day.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 10, 'I will turn your celebrations into times of mourning, and your songs of joy will be turned to weeping. You will wear funeral clothes and shave your heads as signs of sorrow, as if your only son had died. How very bitter that day will be!', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 11, '"The time is surely coming," says the Sovereign LORD, "when I will send a famine on the land--not a famine of bread or water but of hearing the words of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 12, 'People will stagger everywhere from sea to sea, searching for the word of the LORD, running here and going there, but they will not find it.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 13, 'Beautiful girls and fine young men will grow faint and weary, thirsting for the LORD''s word.', 'NLT'),
(34, 8, 14, 'And those who worship and swear by the idols of Samaria, Dan, and Beersheba will fall down, never to rise again."', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 1, 'Then I saw a vision of the Lord standing beside the altar. He said, "Strike the tops of the Temple columns so hard that the foundation will shake. Smash the columns so the roof will crash down on the people below. Then those who survive will be slaughtered in battle. No one will escape!', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 2, '"Even if they dig down to the place of the dead, I will reach down and pull them up. Even if they climb up into the heavens, I will bring them down.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 3, 'Even if they hide at the very top of Mount Carmel, I will search them out and capture them. Even if they hide at the bottom of the ocean, I will send the great sea serpent after them to bite and destroy them.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 4, 'Even if they are driven into exile, I will command the sword to kill them there. I am determined to bring disaster upon them and not to help them."', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 5, 'The Lord, the LORD Almighty, touches the land and it melts, and all its people mourn. The ground rises like the Nile River at floodtime, and then it sinks again.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 6, 'The upper stories of the LORD''s home are in the heavens, while its foundation is on the earth. He draws up water from the oceans and pours it down as rain on the land. The LORD is his name!', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 7, '"Do you Israelites think you are more important to me than the Ethiopians?" asks the LORD. "I brought you out of Egypt, but have I not done as much for other nations, too? I brought the Philistines from Crete and led the Arameans out of Kir.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 8, '"I, the Sovereign LORD, am watching this sinful nation of Israel, and I will uproot it and scatter its people across the earth. Yet I have promised that I will never completely destroy the family of Israel, "says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 9, '"For I have commanded that Israel be persecuted by the other nations as grain is sifted in a sieve, yet not one true kernel will be lost.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 10, 'But all the sinners will die by the sword--all those who say, `Nothing bad will happen to us.''', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 11, '"In that day I will restore the fallen kingdom of David. It is now like a house in ruins, but I will rebuild its walls and restore its former glory.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 12, 'And Israel will possess what is left of Edom and all the nations I have called to be mine. I, the LORD, have spoken, and I will do these things.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 13, '"The time will come," says the LORD, "when the grain and grapes will grow faster than they can be harvested. Then the terraced vineyards on the hills of Israel will drip with sweet wine!', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 14, 'I will bring my exiled people of Israel back from distant lands, and they will rebuild their ruined cities and live in them again. They will plant vineyards and gardens; they will eat their crops and drink their wine.', 'NLT'),
(34, 9, 15, 'I will firmly plant them there in the land I have given them," says the LORD your God. "Then they will never be uprooted again."', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 1, 'This is the vision that the Sovereign LORD revealed to Obadiah concerning the land of Edom. We have heard a message from the LORD that an ambassador was sent to the nations to say, "Get ready, everyone! Let''s assemble our armies and attack Edom!"', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 2, 'The LORD says, "I will cut you down to size among the nations, Edom; you will be small and despised.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 3, 'You are proud because you live in a rock fortress and make your home high in the mountains. `Who can ever reach us way up here?'' you ask boastfully. Don''t fool yourselves!', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 4, 'Though you soar as high as eagles and build your nest among the stars, I will bring you crashing down. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 5, '"If thieves came at night and robbed you, they would not take everything. Those who harvest grapes always leave a few for the poor. But your enemies will wipe you out completely!', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 6, 'Every nook and cranny of Edom will be searched and looted. Every treasure will be found and taken.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 7, '"All your allies will turn against you. They will help to chase you from your land. They will promise you peace, while plotting your destruction. Your trusted friends will set traps for you, and you won''t even know about it.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 8, 'At that time not a single wise person will be left in the whole land of Edom!" says the LORD. "For on the mountains of Edom I will destroy everyone who has wisdom and understanding.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 9, 'The mightiest warriors of Teman will be terrified, and everyone on the mountains of Edom will be cut down in the slaughter.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 10, '"And why? Because of the violence you did to your close relatives in Israel. Now you will be destroyed completely and filled with shame forever.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 11, 'For you deserted your relatives in Israel during their time of greatest need. You stood aloof, refusing to lift a finger to help when foreign invaders carried off their wealth and cast lots to divide up Jerusalem. You acted as though you were one of Israel''s enemies.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 12, '"You shouldn''t have done this! You shouldn''t have gloated when they exiled your relatives to distant lands. You shouldn''t have rejoiced because they were suffering such misfortune. You shouldn''t have crowed over them as they suffered these disasters.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 13, 'You shouldn''t have plundered the land of Israel when they were suffering such calamity. You shouldn''t have gloated over the destruction of your relatives, looting their homes and making yourselves rich at their expense.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 14, 'You shouldn''t have stood at the crossroads, killing those who tried to escape. You shouldn''t have captured the survivors, handing them over to their enemies in that terrible time of trouble.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 15, '"The day is near when I, the LORD, will judge the godless nations! As you have done to Israel, so it will be done to you. All your evil deeds will fall back on your own heads.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 16, 'Just as you swallowed up my people on my holy mountain, so you and the surrounding nations will swallow the punishment I pour out on you. Yes, you nations will drink and stagger and disappear from history, as though you had never even existed.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 17, '"But Jerusalem will become a refuge for those who escape; it will be a holy place. And the people of Israel will come back to reclaim their inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 18, 'At that time Israel will be a raging fire, and Edom, a field of dry stubble. The fire will roar across the field, devouring everything and leaving no survivors in Edom. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 19, '"Then my people living in the Negev will occupy the mountains of Edom. Those living in the foothills of Judah will possess the Philistine plains and take over the fields of Ephraim and Samaria. And the people of Benjamin will occupy the land of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 20, 'The exiles of Israel will return to their land and occupy the Phoenician coast as far north as Zarephath. The captives from Jerusalem exiled in the north will return to their homeland and resettle the villages of the Negev.', 'NLT'),
(35, 1, 21, 'Deliverers will go up to Mount Zion in Jerusalem to rule over the mountains of Edom. And the LORD himself will be king!"', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 1, 'The LORD gave this message to Jonah son of Amittai:', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 2, '"Get up and go to the great city of Nineveh! Announce my judgment against it because I have seen how wicked its people are."', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 3, 'But Jonah got up and went in the opposite direction in order to get away from the LORD. He went down to the seacoast, to the port of Joppa, where he found a ship leaving for Tarshish. He bought a ticket and went on board, hoping that by going away to the west he could escape from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 4, 'But as the ship was sailing along, suddenly the LORD flung a powerful wind over the sea, causing a violent storm that threatened to send them to the bottom.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 5, 'Fearing for their lives, the desperate sailors shouted to their gods for help and threw the cargo overboard to lighten the ship. And all this time Jonah was sound asleep down in the hold.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 6, 'So the captain went down after him. "How can you sleep at a time like this?" he shouted. "Get up and pray to your god! Maybe he will have mercy on us and spare our lives."', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 7, 'Then the crew cast lots to see which of them had offended the gods and caused the terrible storm. When they did this, Jonah lost the toss.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 8, '"What have you done to bring this awful storm down on us?" they demanded. "Who are you? What is your line of work? What country are you from? What is your nationality?"', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 9, 'And Jonah answered, "I am a Hebrew, and I worship the LORD, the God of heaven, who made the sea and the land."', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 10, 'Then he told them that he was running away from the LORD. The sailors were terrified when they heard this. "Oh, why did you do it?" they groaned.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 11, 'And since the storm was getting worse all the time, they asked him, "What should we do to you to stop this storm?"', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 12, '"Throw me into the sea," Jonah said, "and it will become calm again. For I know that this terrible storm is all my fault."', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 13, 'Instead, the sailors tried even harder to row the boat ashore. But the stormy sea was too violent for them, and they couldn''t make it.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 14, 'Then they cried out to the LORD, Jonah''s God. "O LORD," they pleaded, "don''t make us die for this man''s sin. And don''t hold us responsible for his death, because it isn''t our fault. O LORD, you have sent this storm upon him for your own good reasons."', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 15, 'Then the sailors picked Jonah up and threw him into the raging sea, and the storm stopped at once!', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 16, 'The sailors were awestruck by the LORD''s great power, and they offered him a sacrifice and vowed to serve him.', 'NLT'),
(36, 1, 17, 'Now the LORD had arranged for a great fish to swallow Jonah. And Jonah was inside the fish for three days and three nights.', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 1, 'Then Jonah prayed to the LORD his God from inside the fish.', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 2, 'He said, "I cried out to the LORD in my great trouble, and he answered me. I called to you from the world of the dead, and LORD, you heard me!', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 3, 'You threw me into the ocean depths, and I sank down to the heart of the sea. I was buried beneath your wild and stormy waves.', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 4, 'Then I said, `O LORD, you have driven me from your presence. How will I ever again see your holy Temple?''', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 5, '"I sank beneath the waves, and death was very near. The waters closed in around me, and seaweed wrapped itself around my head.', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 6, 'I sank down to the very roots of the mountains. I was locked out of life and imprisoned in the land of the dead. But you, O LORD my God, have snatched me from the yawning jaws of death!', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 7, '"When I had lost all hope, I turned my thoughts once more to the LORD. And my earnest prayer went out to you in your holy Temple.', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 8, 'Those who worship false gods turn their backs on all God''s mercies.', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 9, 'But I will offer sacrifices to you with songs of praise, and I will fulfill all my vows. For my salvation comes from the LORD alone."', 'NLT'),
(36, 2, 10, 'Then the LORD ordered the fish to spit up Jonah on the beach, and it did.', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 1, 'Then the LORD spoke to Jonah a second time:', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 2, '"Get up and go to the great city of Nineveh, and deliver the message of judgment I have given you."', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 3, 'This time Jonah obeyed the LORD''s command and went to Nineveh, a city so large that it took three days to see it all.', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 4, 'On the day Jonah entered the city, he shouted to the crowds: "Forty days from now Nineveh will be destroyed!"', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 5, 'The people of Nineveh believed God''s message, and from the greatest to the least, they decided to go without food and wear sackcloth to show their sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 6, 'When the king of Nineveh heard what Jonah was saying, he stepped down from his throne and took off his royal robes. He dressed himself in sackcloth and sat on a heap of ashes.', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 7, 'Then the king and his nobles sent this decree throughout the city: "No one, not even the animals, may eat or drink anything at all.', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 8, 'Everyone is required to wear sackcloth and pray earnestly to God. Everyone must turn from their evil ways and stop all their violence.', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 9, 'Who can tell? Perhaps even yet God will have pity on us and hold back his fierce anger from destroying us."', 'NLT'),
(36, 3, 10, 'When God saw that they had put a stop to their evil ways, he had mercy on them and didn''t carry out the destruction he had threatened.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 1, 'This change of plans upset Jonah, and he became very angry.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 2, 'So he complained to the LORD about it: "Didn''t I say before I left home that you would do this, LORD? That is why I ran away to Tarshish! I knew that you were a gracious and compassionate God, slow to get angry and filled with unfailing love. I knew how easily you could cancel your plans for destroying these people.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 3, 'Just kill me now, LORD! I''d rather be dead than alive because nothing I predicted is going to happen."', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 4, 'The LORD replied, "Is it right for you to be angry about this?"', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 5, 'Then Jonah went out to the east side of the city and made a shelter to sit under as he waited to see if anything would happen to the city.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 6, 'And the LORD God arranged for a leafy plant to grow there, and soon it spread its broad leaves over Jonah''s head, shading him from the sun. This eased some of his discomfort, and Jonah was very grateful for the plant.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 7, 'But God also prepared a worm! The next morning at dawn the worm ate through the stem of the plant, so that it soon died and withered away.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 8, 'And as the sun grew hot, God sent a scorching east wind to blow on Jonah. The sun beat down on his head until he grew faint and wished to die. "Death is certainly better than this!" he exclaimed.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 9, 'Then God said to Jonah, "Is it right for you to be angry because the plant died?Yes," Jonah retorted, "even angry enough to die!"', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 10, 'Then the LORD said, "You feel sorry about the plant, though you did nothing to put it there. And a plant is only, at best, short lived.', 'NLT'),
(36, 4, 11, 'But Nineveh has more than 120,000 people living in spiritual darkness, not to mention all the animals. Shouldn''t I feel sorry for such a great city?"', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 1, 'The LORD gave these messages to Micah of Moresheth during the years when Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah were kings of Judah. The messages concerned both Samaria and Jerusalem, and they came to Micah in the form of visions.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 2, 'Attention! Let all the people of the world listen! The Sovereign LORD has made accusations against you; the Lord speaks from his holy Temple.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 3, 'Look! The LORD is coming! He leaves his throne in heaven and comes to earth, walking on the high places.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 4, 'They melt beneath his feet and flow into the valleys like wax in a fire, like water pouring down a hill.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 5, 'And why is this happening? Because of the sins and rebellion of Israel and Judah. Who is to blame for Israel''s rebellion? Samaria, its capital city! Where is the center of idolatry in Judah? In Jerusalem, its capital!', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 6, '"So I, the LORD, will make the city of Samaria a heap of rubble. Her streets will be plowed up for planting vineyards. I will roll the stones of her walls down into the valley below, exposing all her foundations.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 7, 'All her carved images will be smashed to pieces. All her sacred treasures will be burned up. These things were bought with the money earned by her prostitution, and they will now be carried away to pay prostitutes elsewhere."', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 8, 'Because of all this, I will mourn and lament. I will walk around naked and barefoot in sorrow and shame. I will howl like a jackal and wail like an ostrich.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 9, 'For my people''s wound is far too deep to heal. It has reached into Judah, even to the gates of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 10, 'Don''t tell our enemies in the city of Gath; don''t weep at all. You people in Beth-leaphrah, roll in the dust to show your anguish and despair.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 11, 'You people of Shaphir, go as captives into exile--naked and ashamed. The people of Zaanan dare not come outside their walls. The people of Beth-ezel mourn because the very foundations of their city have been swept away.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 12, 'The people of Maroth anxiously wait for relief, but only bitterness awaits them as the LORD''s judgment reaches even to the gates of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 13, 'Quick! Use your swiftest chariots and flee, you people of Lachish. You were the first city in Judah to follow Israel in the sin of idol worship, and so you led Jerusalem into sin.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 14, 'Send a farewell gift to Moresheth-gath; there is no hope of saving it. The town of Aczib has deceived the kings of Israel, for it promised help it could not give.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 15, 'You people of Mareshah, I will bring a conqueror to capture your town. And the leaders of Israel will go to Adullam.', 'NLT'),
(37, 1, 16, 'Weep, you people of Judah! Shave your heads in sorrow, for the children you love will be snatched away, and you will never see them again. Make yourselves as bald as an eagle, for your little ones will be exiled to distant lands.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 1, 'How terrible it will be for you who lie awake at night, thinking up evil plans. You rise at dawn and hurry to carry out any of the wicked schemes you have power to accomplish.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 2, 'When you want a certain piece of land, you find a way to seize it. When you want someone''s house, you take it by fraud and violence. No one''s family or inheritance is safe with you around!', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 3, 'But this is what the LORD says: "I will reward your evil with evil; you won''t be able to escape! After I am through with you, none of you will ever again walk proudly in the streets."', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 4, 'In that day your enemies will make fun of you by singing this song of despair about your experience: "We are finished, completely ruined! God has confiscated our land, taking it from us. He has given our fields to those who betrayed us. "', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 5, 'Others will set your boundaries then, and the LORD''s people will have no say in how the land is divided.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 6, '"Don''t say such things," the people say. "Don''t prophesy like that. Such disasters will never come our way!"', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 7, 'Should you talk that way, O family of Israel? Will the LORD have patience with such behavior? If you would do what is right, you would find my words to be good.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 8, 'Yet to this very hour my people rise against me! You steal the shirts right off the backs of those who trusted you, making them as ragged as men who have just come home from battle.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 9, 'You have evicted women from their homes and stripped their children of all their God-given rights.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 10, 'Up! Begone! This is no longer your land and home, for you have filled it with sin and ruined it completely.', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 11, 'Suppose a prophet full of lies were to say to you, "I''ll preach to you the joys of wine and drink!" That''s just the kind of prophet you would like!', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 12, '"Someday, O Israel, I will gather the few of you who are left. I will bring you together again like sheep in a fold, like a flock in its pasture. Yes, your land will again be filled with noisy crowds!', 'NLT'),
(37, 2, 13, 'Your leader will break out and lead you out of exile. He will bring you through the gates of your cities of captivity, back to your own land. Your king will lead you; the LORD himself will guide you."', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 1, 'Listen, you leaders of Israel! You are supposed to know right from wrong,', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 2, 'but you are the very ones who hate good and love evil. You skin my people alive and tear the flesh off their bones.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 3, 'You eat my people''s flesh, cut away their skin, and break their bones. You chop them up like meat for the cooking pot.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 4, 'Then you beg the LORD for help in times of trouble! Do you really expect him to listen? After all the evil you have done, he won''t even look at you!', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 5, 'This is what the LORD says to you false prophets: "You are leading my people astray! You promise peace for those who give you food, but you declare war on anyone who refuses to pay you.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 6, 'Now the night will close around you, cutting off all your visions. Darkness will cover you, making it impossible for you to predict the future. The sun will set for you prophets, and your day will come to an end.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 7, 'Then you seers will cover your faces in shame, and you diviners will be disgraced. And you will admit that your messages were not from God."', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 8, 'But as for me, I am filled with power and the Spirit of the LORD. I am filled with justice and might, fearlessly pointing out Israel''s sin and rebellion.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 9, 'Listen to me, you leaders of Israel! You hate justice and twist all that is right.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 10, 'You are building Jerusalem on a foundation of murder and corruption.', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 11, 'You rulers govern for the bribes you can get; you priests teach God''s laws only for a price; you prophets won''t prophesy unless you are paid. Yet all of you claim you are depending on the LORD. "No harm can come to us," you say, "for the LORD is here among us."', 'NLT'),
(37, 3, 12, 'So because of you, Mount Zion will be plowed like an open field; Jerusalem will be reduced to rubble! A great forest will grow on the hilltop, where the Temple now stands.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 1, 'In the last days, the Temple of the LORD in Jerusalem will become the most important place on earth. People from all over the world will go there to worship.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 2, 'Many nations will come and say, "Come, let us go up to the mountain of the LORD, to the Temple of the God of Israel. There he will teach us his ways, so that we may obey him." For in those days the LORD''s teaching and his word will go out from Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 3, 'The LORD will settle international disputes. All the nations will beat their swords into plowshares and their spears into pruning hooks. All wars will stop, and military training will come to an end.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 4, 'Everyone will live quietly in their own homes in peace and prosperity, for there will be nothing to fear. The LORD Almighty has promised this!', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 5, 'Even though the nations around us worship idols, we will follow the LORD our God forever and ever.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 6, '"In that coming day," says the LORD, "I will gather together my people who are lame, who have been exiles, filled with grief.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 7, 'They are weak and far from home, but I will make them strong again, a mighty nation. Then I, the LORD, will rule from Jerusalem as their king forever."', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 8, 'As for you, O Jerusalem, the citadel of God''s people, your royal might and power will come back to you again. The kingship will be restored to my precious Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 9, 'But why are you now screaming in terror? Have you no king to lead you? He is dead! Have you no wise people to counsel you? All are gone! Pain has gripped you like it does a woman in labor.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 10, 'Writhe and groan in terrible pain, you people of Jerusalem, for you must leave this city to live in the open fields. You will soon be sent into exile in distant Babylon. But the LORD will rescue you there; he will redeem you from the grip of your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 11, 'True, many nations have gathered together against you, calling for your blood, eager to gloat over your destruction.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 12, 'But they do not know the LORD''s thoughts or understand his plan. These nations don''t know that he is gathering them together to be beaten and trampled like bundles of grain on a threshing floor.', 'NLT'),
(37, 4, 13, '"Rise up and destroy the nations, O Jerusalem!" says the LORD. "For I will give you iron horns and bronze hooves, so you can trample many nations to pieces. Then you will give all the wealth they acquired as offerings to me, the Lord of all the earth."', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 1, 'Mobilize! Marshal your troops! The enemy is laying siege to Jerusalem. With a rod they will strike the leader of Israel in the face.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 2, 'But you, O Bethlehem Ephrathah, are only a small village in Judah. Yet a ruler of Israel will come from you, one whose origins are from the distant past.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 3, 'The people of Israel will be abandoned to their enemies until the time when the woman in labor gives birth to her son. Then at last his fellow countrymen will return from exile to their own land.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 4, 'And he will stand to lead his flock with the LORD''s strength, in the majesty of the name of the LORD his God. Then his people will live there undisturbed, for he will be highly honored all around the world.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 5, 'And he will be the source of our peace. When the Assyrians invade our land and break through our defenses, we will appoint seven rulers to watch over us, eight princes to lead us.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 6, 'They will rule Assyria with drawn swords and enter the gates of the land of Nimrod. They will rescue us from the Assyrians when they pour over the borders to invade our land.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 7, 'Then the few left in Israel will go out among the nations. They will be like dew sent by the LORD or like rain falling on the grass, which no one can hold back.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 8, 'The remnant of Israel will go out among the nations and be as strong as a lion. And the other nations will be like helpless sheep, with no one to rescue them.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 9, 'The people of Israel will stand up to their foes, and all their enemies will be wiped out.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 10, '"At that same time," says the LORD, "I will destroy all your weapons--your horses and chariots.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 11, 'I will tear down your walls and demolish the defenses of your cities.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 12, 'I will put an end to all witchcraft; there will be no more fortune-tellers to consult.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 13, 'I will destroy all your idols and sacred pillars, so you will never again worship the work of your own hands.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 14, 'I will abolish your pagan shrines with their Asherah poles and destroy the cities where your idol temples stand.', 'NLT'),
(37, 5, 15, 'I will pour out my vengeance on all the nations that refuse to obey me."', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 1, 'Listen to what the LORD is saying: "Stand up and state your case against me. Let the mountains and hills be called to witness your complaints.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 2, '"And now, O mountains, listen to the LORD''s complaint! He has a case against his people Israel! He will prosecute them to the full extent of the law.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 3, 'O my people, what have I done to make you turn from me? Tell me why your patience is exhausted! Answer me!', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 4, 'For I brought you out of Egypt and redeemed you from your slavery. I sent Moses, Aaron, and Miriam to help you.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 5, '"Don''t you remember, my people, how King Balak of Moab tried to have you cursed and how Balaam son of Beor blessed you instead? And remember your journey from Acacia to Gilgal, when I, the LORD, did everything I could to teach you about my faithfulness."', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 6, 'What can we bring to the LORD to make up for what we''ve done? Should we bow before God with offerings of yearling calves?', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 7, 'Should we offer him thousands of rams and tens of thousands of rivers of olive oil? Would that please the LORD? Should we sacrifice our firstborn children to pay for the sins of our souls? Would that make him glad?', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 8, 'No, O people, the LORD has already told you what is good, and this is what he requires: to do what is right, to love mercy, and to walk humbly with your God.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 9, 'Listen! Fear the LORD if you are wise! His voice is calling out to everyone in Jerusalem: "The armies of destruction are coming; the LORD is sending them.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 10, 'Will there be no end of your getting rich by cheating? The homes of the wicked are filled with treasures gained by dishonestly measuring out grain in short measures.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 11, 'And how can I tolerate all your merchants who use dishonest scales and weights?', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 12, 'The rich among you have become wealthy through extortion and violence. Your citizens are so used to lying that their tongues can no longer tell the truth.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 13, '"Therefore, I will wound you! I will bring you to ruin for all your sins.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 14, 'You will eat but never have enough. Your hunger pangs and emptiness will still remain. And though you try to save your money, it will come to nothing in the end. You will save a little, but I will give it to those who conquer you.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 15, 'You will plant crops but not harvest them. You will press your olives but not get enough oil to anoint yourselves. You will trample the grapes but get no juice to make your wine.', 'NLT'),
(37, 6, 16, '"The only laws you keep are those of evil King Omri; the only example you follow is that of wicked King Ahab! Therefore, I will make an example of you, bringing you to complete ruin. You will be treated with contempt, mocked by all who see you."', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 1, 'What misery is mine! I feel like the fruit picker after the harvest who can find nothing to eat. Not a cluster of grapes or a single fig can be found to satisfy my hunger.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 2, 'The godly people have all disappeared; not one fair-minded person is left on the earth. They are all murderers, even setting traps for their own brothers.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 3, 'They go about their evil deeds with both hands. How skilled they are at using them! Officials and judges alike demand bribes. The people with money and influence pay them off, and together they scheme to twist justice.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 4, 'Even the best of them is like a brier; the straightest is more crooked than a hedge of thorns. But your judgment day is coming swiftly now. Your time of punishment is here.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 5, 'Don''t trust anyone--not your best friend or even your wife!', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 6, 'For the son despises his father. The daughter defies her mother. The daughter-in-law defies her mother-in-law. Your enemies will be right in your own household.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 7, 'As for me, I look to the LORD for his help. I wait confidently for God to save me, and my God will certainly hear me.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 8, 'Do not gloat over me, my enemies! For though I fall, I will rise again. Though I sit in darkness, the LORD himself will be my light.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 9, 'I will be patient as the LORD punishes me, for I have sinned against him. But after that, he will take up my case and punish my enemies for all the evil they have done to me. The LORD will bring me out of my darkness into the light, and I will see his righteousness.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 10, 'Then my enemies will see that the LORD is on my side. They will be ashamed that they taunted me, saying, "Where is the LORD--that God of yours?" With my own eyes I will see them trampled down like mud in the streets.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 11, 'In that day, Israel, your cities will be rebuilt, and your borders will be extended.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 12, 'People from many lands will come and honor you--from Assyria all the way to the towns of Egypt, and from Egypt all the way to the Euphrates River, and from many distant seas and mountains.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 13, 'But the land will become empty and desolate because of the wickedness of those who live there.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 14, 'O LORD, come and rule your people; lead your flock in green pastures. Help them to live in peace and prosperity. Let them enjoy the fertile pastures of Bashan and Gilead as they did long ago.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 15, '"Yes," says the LORD, "I will do mighty miracles for you, like those I did when I rescued you from slavery in Egypt."', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 16, 'All the nations of the world will stand amazed at what the LORD will do for you. They will be embarrassed that their power is so insignificant. They will stand in silent awe, deaf to everything around them.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 17, 'They will come to realize what lowly creatures they really are. Like snakes crawling from their holes, they will come out to meet the LORD our God. They will fear him greatly, trembling in terror at his presence.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 18, 'Where is another God like you, who pardons the sins of the survivors among his people? You cannot stay angry with your people forever, because you delight in showing mercy.', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 19, 'Once again you will have compassion on us. You will trample our sins under your feet and throw them into the depths of the ocean!', 'NLT'),
(37, 7, 20, 'You will show us your faithfulness and unfailing love as you promised with an oath to our ancestors Abraham and Jacob long ago.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 1, 'This message concerning Nineveh came as a vision to Nahum, who lived in Elkosh.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 2, 'The LORD is a jealous God, filled with vengeance and wrath. He takes revenge on all who oppose him and furiously destroys his enemies!', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 3, 'The LORD is slow to get angry, but his power is great, and he never lets the guilty go unpunished. He displays his power in the whirlwind and the storm. The billowing clouds are the dust beneath his feet.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 4, 'At his command the oceans and rivers dry up, the lush pastures of Bashan and Carmel fade, and the green forests of Lebanon wilt.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 5, 'In his presence the mountains quake, and the hills melt away; the earth trembles, and its people are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 6, 'Who can stand before his fierce anger? Who can survive his burning fury? His rage blazes forth like fire, and the mountains crumble to dust in his presence.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 7, 'The LORD is good. When trouble comes, he is a strong refuge. And he knows everyone who trusts in him.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 8, 'But he sweeps away his enemies in an overwhelming flood. He pursues his foes into the darkness of night.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 9, 'Why are you scheming against the LORD? He will destroy you with one blow; he won''t need to strike twice!', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 10, 'His enemies, tangled up like thorns, staggering like drunks, will be burned like dry straw in a field.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 11, 'Who is this king of yours who dares to plot evil against the LORD?', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 12, 'This is what the LORD says: "Even though the Assyrians have many allies, they will be destroyed and disappear. O my people, I have already punished you once, and I will not do it again.', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 13, 'Now I will break your chains and release you from Assyrian oppression."', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 14, 'And this is what the LORD says concerning the Assyrians in Nineveh: "You will have no more children to carry on your name. I will destroy all the idols in the temples of your gods. I am preparing a grave for you because you are despicable and don''t deserve to live!"', 'NLT'),
(38, 1, 15, 'Look! A messenger is coming over the mountains with good news! He is bringing a message of peace. Celebrate your festivals, O people of Judah, and fulfill all your vows, for your enemies from Nineveh will never invade your land again. They have been completely destroyed!', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 1, 'Nineveh, you are already surrounded by enemy armies! Sound the alarm! Man the ramparts! Muster your defenses, and keep a sharp watch for the enemy attack to begin!', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 2, 'For the land of Israel lies empty and broken after your attacks, but the LORD will restore its honor and power again.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 3, 'Shields flash red in the sunlight! The attack begins! See their scarlet uniforms! Watch as their glittering chariots move into position, with a forest of spears waving above them.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 4, 'The chariots race recklessly along the streets and through the squares, swift as lightning, flickering like torches.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 5, 'The king shouts to his officers; they stumble in their haste, rushing to the walls to set up their defenses.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 6, 'But too late! The river gates are open! The enemy has entered! The palace is about to collapse!', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 7, 'Nineveh''s exile has been decreed, and all the servant girls mourn its capture. Listen to them moan like doves; watch them beat their breasts in sorrow.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 8, 'Nineveh is like a leaking water reservoir! The people are slipping away. "Stop, stop!" someone shouts, but the people just keep on running.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 9, 'Loot the silver! Plunder the gold! There seems no end to Nineveh''s many treasures--its vast, uncounted wealth.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 10, 'Soon the city is an empty shambles, stripped of its wealth. Hearts melt in horror, and knees shake. The people stand aghast, their faces pale and trembling.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 11, 'Where now is that great Nineveh, lion of the nations, full of fight and boldness, where the old and feeble and the young and tender lived with nothing to fear?', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 12, 'O Nineveh, you were once a mighty lion! You crushed your enemies to feed your cubs and your mate. You filled your city and your homes with captives and plunder.', 'NLT'),
(38, 2, 13, '"I am your enemy!" says the LORD Almighty. "Your chariots will soon go up in smoke. The finest of your youth will be killed in battle. Never again will you bring back plunder from conquered nations. Never again will the voices of your proud messengers be heard."', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 1, 'How terrible it will be for Nineveh, the city of murder and lies! She is crammed with wealth to be plundered.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 2, 'Listen! Hear the crack of the whips as the chariots rush forward against her. Wheels rumble, horses'' hooves pound, and chariots clatter as they bump wildly through the streets.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 3, 'See the flashing swords and glittering spears in the upraised arms of the cavalry! The dead are lying in the streets--dead bodies, heaps of bodies, everywhere. People stumble over them, scramble to their feet, and fall again.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 4, 'All this because Nineveh, the beautiful and faithless city, mistress of deadly charms, enticed the nations with her beauty. She taught them all to worship her false gods, enchanting people everywhere.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 5, '"No wonder I am your enemy!" declares the LORD Almighty. "And now I will lift your skirts so all the earth will see your nakedness and shame.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 6, 'I will cover you with filth and show the world how vile you really are.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 7, 'All who see you will shrink back in horror and say, `Nineveh lies in utter ruin.'' Yet no one anywhere will regret your destruction."', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 8, 'Are you any better than Thebes, surrounded by rivers, protected by water on all sides?', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 9, 'Ethiopia and the land of Egypt were the source of her strength, which seemed without limit. The nations of Put and Libya also helped and supported her.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 10, 'Yet Thebes fell, and her people were led away as captives. Her babies were dashed to death against the stones of the streets. Soldiers cast lots to see who would get the Egyptian officers as servants. All their leaders were bound in chains.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 11, 'And you, Nineveh, will also stagger like a drunkard. You will hide for fear of the attacking enemy.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 12, 'All your fortresses will fall. They will be devoured like the ripe figs that fall into the mouths of those who shake the trees.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 13, 'Your troops will be as weak and helpless as women. The gates of your land will be opened wide to the enemy and set on fire and burned.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 14, 'Get ready for the siege! Store up water! Strengthen the defenses! Make bricks to repair the walls! Go into the pits to trample clay, and pack it into molds!', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 15, 'But in the middle of your preparations, the fire will devour you; the sword will cut you down. The enemy will consume you like locusts, devouring everything they see. There will be no escape, even if you multiply like grasshoppers.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 16, 'Merchants, as numerous as the stars, have filled your city with vast wealth. But like a swarm of locusts, they strip the land and then fly away.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 17, 'Your princes and officials are also like locusts, crowding together in the hedges to survive the cold. But like locusts that fly away when the sun comes up to warm the earth, all of them will fly away and disappear.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 18, 'O Assyrian king, your princes lie dead in the dust. Your people are scattered across the mountains. There is no longer a shepherd to gather them together.', 'NLT'),
(38, 3, 19, 'There is no healing for your wound; your injury is fatal. All who hear of your destruction will clap their hands for joy. Where can anyone be found who has not suffered from your cruelty?', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 1, 'This is the message that the prophet Habakkuk received from the LORD in a vision.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 2, 'How long, O LORD, must I call for help? But you do not listen! "Violence!" I cry, but you do not come to save.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 3, 'Must I forever see this sin and misery all around me? Wherever I look, I see destruction and violence. I am surrounded by people who love to argue and fight.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 4, 'The law has become paralyzed and useless, and there is no justice given in the courts. The wicked far outnumber the righteous, and justice is perverted with bribes and trickery.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 5, 'The LORD replied, "Look at the nations and be amazed! Watch and be astounded at what I will do! For I am doing something in your own day, something you wouldn''t believe even if someone told you about it.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 6, 'I am raising up the Babylonians to be a new power on the world scene. They are a cruel and violent nation who will march across the world and conquer it.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 7, 'They are notorious for their cruelty. They do as they like, and no one can stop them.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 8, 'Their horses are swifter than leopards. They are a fierce people, more fierce than wolves at dusk. Their horsemen race forward from distant places. Like eagles they swoop down to pounce on their prey.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 9, '"On they come, all of them bent on violence. Their hordes advance like a wind from the desert, sweeping captives ahead of them like sand.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 10, 'They scoff at kings and princes and scorn all their defenses. They simply pile ramps of earth against their walls and capture them!', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 11, 'They sweep past like the wind and are gone. But they are deeply guilty, for their own strength is their god."', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 12, 'O LORD my God, my Holy One, you who are eternal--is your plan in all of this to wipe us out? Surely not! O LORD our Rock, you have decreed the rise of these Babylonians to punish and correct us for our terrible sins.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 13, 'You are perfectly just in this. But will you, who cannot allow sin in any form, stand idly by while they swallow us up? Should you be silent while the wicked destroy people who are more righteous than they?', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 14, 'Are we but fish to be caught and killed? Are we but creeping things that have no leader to defend them from their enemies?', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 15, 'Must we be strung up on their hooks and dragged out in their nets while they rejoice?', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 16, 'Then they will worship their nets and burn incense in front of them. "These nets are the gods who have made us rich!" they will claim.', 'NLT'),
(39, 1, 17, 'Will you let them get away with this forever? Will they succeed forever in their heartless conquests?', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 1, 'I will climb up into my watchtower now and wait to see what the LORD will say to me and how he will answer my complaint.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 2, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Write my answer in large, clear letters on a tablet, so that a runner can read it and tell everyone else.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 3, 'But these things I plan won''t happen right away. Slowly, steadily, surely, the time approaches when the vision will be fulfilled. If it seems slow, wait patiently, for it will surely take place. It will not be delayed.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 4, '"Look at the proud! They trust in themselves, and their lives are crooked; but the righteous will live by their faith.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 5, 'Wealth is treacherous, and the arrogant are never at rest. They range far and wide, with their mouths opened as wide as death, but they are never satisfied. In their greed they have gathered up many nations and peoples.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 6, 'But the time is coming when all their captives will taunt them, saying, `You thieves! At last justice has caught up with you! Now you will get what you deserve for your oppression and extortion!''', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 7, 'Suddenly, your debtors will rise up in anger. They will turn on you and take all you have, while you stand trembling and helpless.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 8, 'You have plundered many nations; now they will plunder you. You murderers! You have filled the countryside with violence and all the cities, too.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 9, '"How terrible it will be for you who get rich by unjust means! You believe your wealth will buy security, putting your families beyond the reach of danger.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 10, 'But by the murders you committed, you have shamed your name and forfeited your lives.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 11, 'The very stones in the walls of your houses cry out against you, and the beams in the ceilings echo the complaint.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 12, '"How terrible it will be for you who build cities with money gained by murder and corruption!', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 13, 'Has not the LORD Almighty promised that the wealth of nations will turn to ashes? They work so hard, but all in vain!', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 14, 'For the time will come when all the earth will be filled, as the waters fill the sea, with an awareness of the glory of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 15, '"How terrible it will be for you who make your neighbors drunk! You force your cup on them so that you can gloat over their nakedness and shame.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 16, 'But soon it will be your turn! Come, drink and be exposed! Drink from the cup of the LORD''s judgment, and all your glory will be turned to shame.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 17, 'You cut down the forests of Lebanon. Now you will be cut down! You terrified the wild animals you caught in your traps. Now terror will strike you because of your murder and violence in cities everywhere!', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 18, '"What have you gained by worshiping all your man-made idols? How foolish to trust in something made by your own hands! What fools you are to believe such lies!', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 19, 'How terrible it will be for you who beg lifeless wooden idols to save you. You ask speechless stone images to tell you what to do. Can an idol speak for God? They may be overlaid with gold and silver, but they are lifeless inside.', 'NLT'),
(39, 2, 20, 'But the LORD is in his holy Temple. Let all the earth be silent before him."', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 1, 'This prayer was sung by the prophet Habakkuk:', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 2, 'I have heard all about you, LORD, and I am filled with awe by the amazing things you have done. In this time of our deep need, begin again to help us, as you did in years gone by. Show us your power to save us. And in your anger, remember your mercy.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 3, 'I see God, the Holy One, moving across the deserts from Edom and Mount Paran. His brilliant splendor fills the heavens, and the earth is filled with his praise! What a wonderful God he is!', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 4, 'Rays of brilliant light flash from his hands. He rejoices in his awesome power.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 5, 'Pestilence marches before him; plague follows close behind.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 6, 'When he stops, the earth shakes. When he looks, the nations tremble. He shatters the everlasting mountains and levels the eternal hills. But his power is not diminished in the least!', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 7, 'I see the peoples of Cushan and Midian trembling in terror.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 8, 'Was it in anger, LORD, that you struck the rivers and parted the sea? Were you displeased with them? No, you were sending your chariots of salvation!', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 9, 'You were commanding your weapons of power! You split open the earth with flowing rivers!', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 10, 'The mountains watched and trembled. Onward swept the raging waters. The mighty deep cried out, lifting its hands to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 11, 'The lofty sun and moon began to fade, obscured by brilliance from your arrows and the flashing of your glittering spear.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 12, 'You marched across the land in awesome anger and trampled the nations in your fury.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 13, 'You went out to rescue your chosen people, to save your anointed ones. You crushed the heads of the wicked and laid bare their bones from head to toe.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 14, 'With their own weapons, you destroyed those who rushed out like a whirlwind, thinking Israel would be easy prey.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 15, 'You trampled the sea with your horses, and the mighty waters piled high.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 16, 'I trembled inside when I heard all this; my lips quivered with fear. My legs gave way beneath me, and I shook in terror. I will wait quietly for the coming day when disaster will strike the people who invade us.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 17, 'Even though the fig trees have no blossoms, and there are no grapes on the vine; even though the olive crop fails, and the fields lie empty and barren; even though the flocks die in the fields, and the cattle barns are empty,', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 18, 'yet I will rejoice in the LORD! I will be joyful in the God of my salvation.', 'NLT'),
(39, 3, 19, 'The Sovereign LORD is my strength! He will make me as surefooted as a deer and bring me safely over the mountains. (For the choir director: This prayer is to be accompanied by stringed instruments.)', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 1, 'The LORD gave these messages to Zephaniah when Josiah son of Amon was king of Judah. Zephaniah was the son of Cushi, son of Gedaliah, son of Amariah, son of Hezekiah.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 2, '"I will sweep away everything in all your land," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 3, '"I will sweep away both people and animals alike. Even the birds of the air and the fish in the sea will die. I will reduce the wicked to heaps of rubble, along with the rest of humanity," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 4, '"I will crush Judah and Jerusalem with my fist and destroy every last trace of their Baal worship. I will put an end to all the idolatrous priests, so that even the memory of them will disappear.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 5, 'For they go up to their roofs and bow to the sun, moon, and stars. They claim to follow the LORD, but then they worship Molech, too. So now I will destroy them!', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 6, 'And I will destroy those who used to worship me but now no longer do. They no longer ask for the LORD''s guidance or seek my blessings."', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 7, 'Stand in silence in the presence of the Sovereign LORD, for the awesome day of the LORD''s judgment has come. The LORD has prepared his people for a great slaughter and has chosen their executioners.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 8, '"On that day of judgment," says the LORD, "I will punish the leaders and princes of Judah and all those following pagan customs.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 9, 'Yes, I will punish those who participate in pagan worship ceremonies, and those who steal and kill to fill their masters'' homes with loot.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 10, '"On that day," says the LORD, "a cry of alarm will come from the Fish Gate and echo throughout the newer Mishneh section of the city. And a great crashing sound will come from the surrounding hills.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 11, 'Wail in sorrow, all you who live in the market area, for all who buy and sell there will die.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 12, '"I will search with lanterns in Jerusalem''s darkest corners to find and punish those who sit contented in their sins, indifferent to the LORD, thinking he will do nothing at all to them.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 13, 'They are the very ones whose property will be plundered by the enemy, whose homes will be ransacked. They will never have a chance to live in the new homes they have built. They will never drink wine from the vineyards they have planted.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 14, '"That terrible day of the LORD is near. Swiftly it comes--a day when strong men will cry bitterly.', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 15, 'It is a day when the LORD''s anger will be poured out. It is a day of terrible distress and anguish, a day of ruin and desolation, a day of darkness and gloom, of clouds, blackness,', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 16, 'trumpet calls, and battle cries. Down go the walled cities and strongest battlements!', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 17, '"Because you have sinned against the LORD, I will make you as helpless as a blind man searching for a path. Your blood will be poured out into the dust, and your bodies will lie there rotting on the ground."', 'NLT'),
(40, 1, 18, 'Your silver and gold will be of no use to you on that day of the LORD''s anger. For the whole land will be devoured by the fire of his jealousy. He will make a terrifying end of all the people on earth.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 1, 'Gather together and pray, you shameless nation.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 2, 'Gather while there is still time, before judgment begins and your opportunity is blown away like chaff. Act now, before the fierce fury of the LORD falls and the terrible day of the LORD''s anger begins.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 3, 'Beg the LORD to save you--all you who are humble, all you who uphold justice. Walk humbly and do what is right. Perhaps even yet the LORD will protect you from his anger on that day of destruction.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 4, 'Gaza, Ashkelon, Ashdod, Ekron--these Philistine cities, too, will be rooted out and left in desolation.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 5, 'And how terrible it will be for you Philistines who live along the coast and in the land of Canaan, for this judgment is against you, too! The LORD will destroy you until not one of you is left.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 6, 'The coastal area will become a pasture, a place of shepherd camps and enclosures for sheep.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 7, 'The few survivors of the tribe of Judah will pasture there. They will lie down to rest in the abandoned houses in Ashkelon. For the LORD their God will visit his people in kindness and restore their prosperity again.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 8, '"I have heard the taunts of the people of Moab and Ammon, mocking my people and invading their borders.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 9, 'Now, as surely as I live," says the LORD Almighty, the God of Israel, "Moab and Ammon will be destroyed as completely as Sodom and Gomorrah. Their land will become a place of stinging nettles, salt pits, and eternal desolation. Those of my people who are left will plunder them and take their land."', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 10, 'They will receive the wages of their pride, for they have scoffed at the people of the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 11, 'The LORD will terrify them as he destroys all the gods in the land. Then people from nations around the world will worship the LORD, each in their own land.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 12, '"You Ethiopians will also be slaughtered by my sword," says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 13, 'And the LORD will strike the lands of the north with his fist. He will destroy Assyria and make its great capital, Nineveh, a desolate wasteland, parched like a desert.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 14, 'The city that once was so proud will become a pasture for sheep and cattle. All sorts of wild animals will settle there. Owls of many kinds will live among the ruins of its palaces, hooting from the gaping windows. Rubble will block all the doorways, and the cedar paneling will lie open to the wind and weather.', 'NLT'),
(40, 2, 15, 'This is the fate of that boisterous city, once so secure. "In all the world there is no city as great as I," it boasted. But now, look how it has become an utter ruin, a place where animals live! Everyone passing that way will laugh in derision or shake a defiant fist.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 1, 'How terrible it will be for rebellious, polluted Jerusalem, the city of violence and crime.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 2, 'It proudly refuses to listen even to the voice of the LORD. No one can tell it anything; it refuses all correction. It does not trust in the LORD or draw near to its God.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 3, 'Its leaders are like roaring lions hunting for their victims--out for everything they can get. Its judges are like ravenous wolves at evening time, who by dawn have left no trace of their prey.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 4, 'Its prophets are arrogant liars seeking their own gain. Its priests defile the Temple by disobeying God''s laws.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 5, 'But the LORD is still there in the city, and he does no wrong. Day by day his justice is more evident, but no one takes notice--the wicked know no shame.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 6, '"I have wiped out many nations, devastating their fortress walls and towers. Their cities are now deserted; their streets are in silent ruin. There are no survivors to even tell what happened.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 7, 'I thought, `Surely they will have reverence for me now! Surely they will listen to my warnings, so I won''t need to strike again.'' But no; however much I punish them, they continue their evil practices from dawn till dusk and dusk till dawn."', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 8, 'So now the LORD says: "Be patient; the time is coming soon when I will stand up and accuse these evil nations. For it is my decision to gather together the kingdoms of the earth and pour out my fiercest anger and fury on them. All the earth will be devoured by the fire of my jealousy.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 9, '"On that day I will purify the lips of all people, so that everyone will be able to worship the LORD together.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 10, 'My scattered people who live beyond the rivers of Ethiopia will come to present their offerings.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 11, 'And then you will no longer need to be ashamed of yourselves, for you will no longer be rebels against me. I will remove all the proud and arrogant people from among you. There will be no pride on my holy mountain.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 12, 'Those who are left will be the lowly and the humble, for it is they who trust in the name of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 13, 'The people of Israel who survive will do no wrong to each other, never telling lies or deceiving one another. They will live peaceful lives, lying down to sleep in safety; there will be no one to make them afraid."', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 14, 'Sing, O daughter of Zion; shout aloud, O Israel! Be glad and rejoice with all your heart, O daughter of Jerusalem!', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 15, 'For the LORD will remove his hand of judgment and will disperse the armies of your enemy. And the LORD himself, the King of Israel, will live among you! At last your troubles will be over, and you will fear disaster no more.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 16, 'On that day the announcement to Jerusalem will be, "Cheer up, Zion! Don''t be afraid!', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 17, 'For the LORD your God has arrived to live among you. He is a mighty savior. He will rejoice over you with great gladness. With his love, he will calm all your fears. He will exult over you by singing a happy song."', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 18, '"I will gather you who mourn for the appointed festivals; you will be disgraced no more.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 19, 'And I will deal severely with all who have oppressed you. I will save the weak and helpless ones; I will bring together those who were chased away. I will give glory and renown to my former exiles, who have been mocked and shamed.', 'NLT'),
(40, 3, 20, 'On that day I will gather you together and bring you home again. I will give you a good name, a name of distinction among all the nations of the earth. They will praise you as I restore your fortunes before their very eyes. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 1, 'On August 29 of the second year of King Darius''s reign, the LORD gave a message through the prophet Haggai to Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and to Jeshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest.', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 2, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: The people are saying, `The time has not yet come to rebuild the LORD''s house--the Temple.''"', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 3, 'So the LORD sent this message through the prophet Haggai:', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 4, '"Why are you living in luxurious houses while my house lies in ruins?', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 5, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: Consider how things are going for you!', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 6, 'You have planted much but harvested little. You have food to eat, but not enough to fill you up. You have wine to drink, but not enough to satisfy your thirst. You have clothing to wear, but not enough to keep you warm. Your wages disappear as though you were putting them in pockets filled with holes!', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 7, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: Consider how things are going for you!', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 8, 'Now go up into the hills, bring down timber, and rebuild my house. Then I will take pleasure in it and be honored, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 9, 'You hoped for rich harvests, but they were poor. And when you brought your harvest home, I blew it away. Why? Because my house lies in ruins, says the LORD Almighty, while you are all busy building your own fine houses.', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 10, 'That is why the heavens have withheld the dew and the earth has withheld its crops.', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 11, 'I have called for a drought on your fields and hills--a drought to wither the grain and grapes and olives and all your other crops, a drought to starve both you and your cattle and to ruin everything you have worked so hard to get."', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 12, 'Then Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, Jeshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and the whole remnant of God''s people obeyed the message from the LORD their God. It had been delivered by the prophet Haggai, whom the LORD their God had sent, and the people worshiped the LORD in earnest.', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 13, 'Then Haggai, the LORD''s messenger, gave the people this message from the LORD: "I am with you, says the LORD!"', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 14, 'So the LORD sparked the enthusiasm of Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, Jeshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and the whole remnant of God''s people. They came and began their work on the house of the LORD Almighty, their God.', 'NLT'),
(41, 1, 15, 'This was on September 21 of the second year of King Darius''s reign.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 1, 'Then on October 17 of that same year, the LORD sent another message through the prophet Haggai.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 2, '"Say this to Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, governor of Judah, and to Jeshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest, and to the remnant of God''s people there in the land:', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 3, 'Is there anyone who can remember this house--the Temple--as it was before? In comparison, how does it look to you now? It must seem like nothing at all!', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 4, 'But now take courage, Zerubbabel, says the LORD. Take courage, Jeshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest. Take courage, all you people still left in the land, says the LORD. Take courage and work, for I am with you, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 5, 'My Spirit remains among you, just as I promised when you came out of Egypt. So do not be afraid.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 6, '"For this is what the LORD Almighty says: In just a little while I will again shake the heavens and the earth. I will shake the oceans and the dry land, too.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 7, 'I will shake all the nations, and the treasures of all the nations will come to this Temple. I will fill this place with glory, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 8, 'The silver is mine, and the gold is mine, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 9, 'The future glory of this Temple will be greater than its past glory, says the LORD Almighty. And in this place I will bring peace. I, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 10, 'On December 18 of the second year of King Darius''s reign, the LORD sent this message to the prophet Haggai:', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 11, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says! Ask the priests this question about the law:', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 12, 'If one of you is carrying a holy sacrifice in his robes and happens to brush against some bread or stew, wine or oil, or any other kind of food, will it also become holy?" The priests replied, "No."', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 13, 'Then Haggai asked, "But if someone becomes ceremonially unclean by touching a dead person and then brushes against any of the things mentioned, will it be defiled?" And the priests answered, "Yes."', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 14, 'Then Haggai said, "That is how it is with this people and this nation, says the LORD. Everything they do and everything they offer is defiled.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 15, 'So think about this from now on--consider how things were going for you before you began to lay the foundation of the LORD''s Temple.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 16, 'When you hoped for a twenty-bushel crop, you harvested only ten. When you expected to draw fifty gallons from the winepress, you found only twenty.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 17, 'I sent blight and mildew and hail to destroy all the produce of your labor. Yet, even so, you refused to return to me, says the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 18, '"On this eighteenth day of December--the day when the foundation of the LORD''s Temple was laid--carefully consider this:', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 19, 'I am giving you a promise now while the seed is still in the barn, before you have harvested your grain and before the grapevine, the fig tree, the pomegranate, and the olive tree have produced their crops. From this day onward I will bless you."', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 20, 'The LORD sent this second message to Haggai on December 18:', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 21, '"Tell Zerubbabel, the governor of Judah, that I am about to shake the heavens and the earth.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 22, 'I will overthrow royal thrones, destroying the power of foreign kingdoms. I will overturn their chariots and charioteers. The horses will fall, and their riders will kill each other.', 'NLT'),
(41, 2, 23, 'But when this happens, says the LORD Almighty, I will honor you, Zerubbabel son of Shealtiel, my servant. I will treat you like a signet ring on my finger, says the LORD, for I have specially chosen you. I, the LORD Almighty, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 1, 'In midautumn of the second year of King Darius''s reign, the LORD gave this message to the prophet Zechariah son of Berekiah and grandson of Iddo.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 2, '"I, the LORD, was very angry with your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 3, 'Therefore, say to the people, `This is what the LORD Almighty says: Return to me, and I will return to you, says the LORD Almighty.''', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 4, 'Do not be like your ancestors who would not listen when the earlier prophets said to them, `This is what the LORD Almighty says: Turn from your evil ways and stop all your evil practices.''', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 5, '"Your ancestors and their prophets are now long dead.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 6, 'But all the things I said through my servants the prophets happened to your ancestors, just as I said they would. As a result, they repented and said, `We have received what we deserved from the LORD Almighty. He has done what he said he would do.''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 7, 'Then on February 15 of the second year of King Darius''s reign, the LORD sent another message to the prophet Zechariah son of Berekiah and grandson of Iddo. Zechariah said:', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 8, 'In a vision during the night, I saw a man sitting on a red horse that was standing among some myrtle trees in a small valley. Behind him were red, brown, and white horses, each with its own rider.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 9, 'I asked the angel who was talking with me, "My lord, what are all those horses for?I will show you," the angel replied.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 10, 'So the man standing among the myrtle trees explained, "They are the ones the LORD has sent out to patrol the earth."', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 11, 'Then the other riders reported to the angel of the LORD, who was standing among the myrtle trees, "We have patrolled the earth, and the whole earth is at peace."', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 12, 'Upon hearing this, the angel of the LORD prayed this prayer: "O LORD Almighty, for seventy years now you have been angry with Jerusalem and the towns of Judah. How long will it be until you again show mercy to them?"', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 13, 'And the LORD spoke kind and comforting words to the angel who talked with me.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 14, 'Then the angel said to me, "Shout this message for all to hear: `This is what the LORD Almighty says: My love for Jerusalem and Mount Zion is passionate and strong.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 15, 'But I am very angry with the other nations that enjoy peace and security. I was only a little angry with my people, but the nations punished them far beyond my intentions.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 16, '" `Therefore, this is what the LORD says: I have returned to show mercy to Jerusalem. My Temple will be rebuilt, says the LORD Almighty, and plans will be made for the reconstruction of Jerusalem. ''', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 17, 'Say this also: `This is what the LORD Almighty says: The towns of Israel will again overflow with prosperity, and the LORD will again comfort Zion and choose Jerusalem as his own.''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 18, 'Then I looked up and saw four animal horns.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 19, '"What are these?" I asked the angel who was talking with me. He replied, "These horns represent the world powers that scattered Judah, Israel, and Jerusalem."', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 20, 'Then the LORD showed me four blacksmiths.', 'NLT'),
(42, 1, 21, '"What are these men coming to do?" I asked. The angel replied, "The blacksmiths have come to terrify the four horns that scattered and humbled Judah. They will throw them down and destroy them."', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 1, 'When I looked around me again, I saw a man with a measuring line in his hand.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 2, '"Where are you going?" I asked. He replied, "I am going to measure Jerusalem, to see how wide and how long it is."', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 3, 'Then the angel who was with me went to meet a second angel who was coming toward him.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 4, 'The other angel said, "Hurry, and say to that young man, `Jerusalem will someday be so full of people that it won''t have room enough for everyone! Many will live outside the city walls, with all their livestock--and yet they will be safe.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 5, 'For I, myself, will be a wall of fire around Jerusalem, says the LORD. And I will be the glory inside the city!''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 6, 'The LORD says, "Come away! Flee from the north, for I have scattered you to the four winds.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 7, 'Come away! Escape to Jerusalem, you who are exiled in Babylon!"', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 8, '"After a period of glory, the LORD Almighty sent me against the nations who oppressed you. For he said, `Anyone who harms you harms my most precious possession.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 9, 'I will raise my fist to crush them, and their own slaves will plunder them.'' Then you will know that the LORD Almighty has sent me."', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 10, 'The LORD says, "Shout and rejoice, O Jerusalem, for I am coming to live among you.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 11, 'Many nations will join themselves to the LORD on that day, and they, too, will be my people. I will live among you, and you will know that the LORD Almighty sent me to you.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 12, 'The land of Judah will be the LORD''s inheritance in the holy land, and he will once again choose Jerusalem to be his own city.', 'NLT'),
(42, 2, 13, 'Be silent before the LORD, all humanity, for he is springing into action from his holy dwelling."', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 1, 'Then the angel showed me Jeshua the high priest standing before the angel of the LORD. Satan was there at the angel''s right hand, accusing Jeshua of many things.', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 2, 'And the LORD said to Satan, "I, the LORD, reject your accusations, Satan. Yes, the LORD, who has chosen Jerusalem, rebukes you. This man is like a burning stick that has been snatched from a fire."', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 3, 'Jeshua''s clothing was filthy as he stood there before the angel.', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 4, 'So the angel said to the others standing there, "Take off his filthy clothes." And turning to Jeshua he said, "See, I have taken away your sins, and now I am giving you these fine new clothes."', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 5, 'Then I said, "Please, could he also have a clean turban on his head?" So they put a clean priestly turban on his head and dressed him in new clothes while the angel of the LORD stood by.', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 6, 'Then the angel of the LORD spoke very solemnly to Jeshua and said,', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 7, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: If you follow my ways and obey my requirements, then you will be given authority over my Temple and its courtyards. I will let you walk in and out of my presence along with these others standing here.', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 8, 'Listen to me, O Jeshua the high priest, and all you other priests. You are symbols of the good things to come. Soon I am going to bring my servant, the Branch.', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 9, 'Now look at the jewel I have set before Jeshua, a single stone with seven facets. I will engrave an inscription on it, says the LORD Almighty, and I will remove the sins of this land in a single day.', 'NLT'),
(42, 3, 10, 'And on that day, says the LORD Almighty, each of you will invite your neighbor into your home to share your peace and prosperity."', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 1, 'Then the angel who had been talking with me returned and woke me, as though I had been asleep.', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 2, '"What do you see now?" he asked. I answered, "I see a solid gold lampstand with a bowl of oil on top of it. Around the bowl are seven lamps, each one having seven spouts with wicks.', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 3, 'And I see two olive trees, one on each side of the bowl."', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 4, 'Then I asked the angel, "What are these, my lord? What do they mean?"', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 5, '"Don''t you know?" the angel asked. "No, my lord," I replied.', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 6, 'Then he said to me, "This is what the LORD says to Zerubbabel: It is not by force nor by strength, but by my Spirit, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 7, 'Nothing, not even a mighty mountain, will stand in Zerubbabel''s way; it will flatten out before him! Then Zerubbabel will set the final stone of the Temple in place, and the people will shout: `May God bless it! May God bless it!''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 8, 'Then another message came to me from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 9, '"Zerubbabel is the one who laid the foundation of this Temple, and he will complete it. Then you will know that the LORD Almighty has sent me.', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 10, 'Do not despise these small beginnings, for the LORD rejoices to see the work begin, to see the plumb line in Zerubbabel''s hand. For these seven lamps represent the eyes of the LORD that search all around the world."', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 11, 'Then I asked the angel, "What are these two olive trees on each side of the lampstand,', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 12, 'and what are the two olive branches that pour out golden oil through two gold tubes?"', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 13, '"Don''t you know?" he asked. "No, my lord," I replied.', 'NLT'),
(42, 4, 14, 'Then he said to me, "They represent the two anointed ones who assist the Lord of all the earth."', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 1, 'I looked up again and saw a scroll flying through the air.', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 2, '"What do you see?" the angel asked. "I see a flying scroll," I replied. "It appears to be about thirty feet long and fifteen feet wide. "', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 3, 'Then he said to me, "This scroll contains the curse that is going out over the entire land. One side says that those who steal will be banished from the land; the other side says that those who swear falsely will be banished from the land.', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 4, 'And this is what the LORD Almighty says: I am sending this curse into the house of every thief and into the house of everyone who swears falsely by my name. And my curse will remain in that house until it is completely destroyed--even its timbers and stones."', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 5, 'Then the angel who was talking with me came forward and said, "Look up! Something is appearing in the sky."', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 6, '"What is it?" I asked. He replied, "It is a basket for measuring grain, and it is filled with the sins of everyone throughout the land."', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 7, 'When the heavy lead cover was lifted off the basket, there was a woman sitting inside it.', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 8, 'The angel said, "The woman''s name is Wickedness," and he pushed her back into the basket and closed the heavy lid again.', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 9, 'Then I looked up and saw two women flying toward us, with wings gliding on the wind. Their wings were like those of a stork, and they picked up the basket and flew with it into the sky.', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 10, '"Where are they taking the basket?" I asked the angel.', 'NLT'),
(42, 5, 11, 'He replied, "To the land of Babylonia, where they will build a temple for the basket. And when the temple is ready, they will set the basket there on its pedestal."', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 1, 'Then I looked up again and saw four chariots coming from between two bronze mountains.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 2, 'The first chariot was pulled by red horses, the second by black horses,', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 3, 'the third by white horses, and the fourth by dappled-gray horses.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 4, '"And what are these, my lord?" I asked the angel who was talking with me.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 5, 'He replied, "These are the four spirits of heaven who stand before the Lord of all the earth. They are going out to do his work.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 6, 'The chariot with black horses is going north, the chariot with white horses is going west, and the chariot with dappled-gray horses is going south."', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 7, 'The powerful horses were eager to be off, to patrol back and forth across the earth. And the LORD said, "Go and patrol the earth!" So they left at once on their patrol.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 8, 'Then the LORD summoned me and said, "Those who went north have vented the anger of my Spirit there."', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 9, 'Then I received another message from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 10, '"Heldai, Tobijah, and Jedaiah will bring gifts of silver and gold from the Jews exiled in Babylon. As soon as they arrive, meet them at the home of Josiah son of Zephaniah.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 11, 'Accept their gifts and make a crown from the silver and gold. Then put the crown on the head of Jeshua son of Jehozadak, the high priest.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 12, 'Tell him that the LORD Almighty says: Here is the man called the Branch. He will branch out where he is and build the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 13, 'He will build the LORD''s Temple, and he will receive royal honor and will rule as king from his throne. He will also serve as priest from his throne, and there will be perfect harmony between the two.', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 14, '"The crown will be a memorial in the Temple of the LORD to honor those who gave it--Heldai, Tobijah, Jedaiah, and Josiah son of Zephaniah."', 'NLT'),
(42, 6, 15, 'Many will come from distant lands to rebuild the Temple of the LORD. And when this happens, you will know my messages have been from the LORD Almighty. All this will happen if you carefully obey the commands of the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 1, 'On December 7 of the fourth year of King Darius''s reign, another message came to Zechariah from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 2, 'The people of Bethel had sent Sharezer and Regemmelech, along with their men, to seek the LORD''s favor.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 3, 'They were to ask this question of the prophets and of the priests at the Temple of the LORD Almighty: "Should we continue to mourn and fast each summer on the anniversary of the Temple''s destruction, as we have done for so many years?"', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 4, 'The LORD Almighty sent me this message:', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 5, '"Say to all your people and your priests, `During those seventy years of exile, when you fasted and mourned in the summer and at the festival in early autumn, was it really for me that you were fasting?', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 6, 'And even now in your holy festivals, you don''t think about me but only of pleasing yourselves.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 7, 'Isn''t this the same message the LORD proclaimed through the prophets years ago when Jerusalem and the towns of Judah were bustling with people, and the Negev and the foothills of Judah were populated areas?''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 8, 'Then this message came to Zechariah from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 9, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: Judge fairly and honestly, and show mercy and kindness to one another.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 10, 'Do not oppress widows, orphans, foreigners, and poor people. And do not make evil plans to harm each other.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 11, '"Your ancestors would not listen to this message. They turned stubbornly away and put their fingers in their ears to keep from hearing.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 12, 'They made their hearts as hard as stone, so they could not hear the law or the messages that the LORD Almighty had sent them by his Spirit through the earlier prophets. That is why the LORD Almighty was so angry with them.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 13, '"Since they refused to listen when I called to them, I would not listen when they called to me, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(42, 7, 14, 'I scattered them as with a whirlwind among the distant nations, where they lived as strangers. Their land became so desolate that no one even traveled through it. The land that had been so pleasant became a desert."', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 1, 'Then another message came to me from the LORD Almighty:', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 2, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: My love for Mount Zion is passionate and strong; I am consumed with passion for Jerusalem!', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 3, 'And now the LORD says: I am returning to Mount Zion, and I will live in Jerusalem. Then Jerusalem will be called the Faithful City; the mountain of the LORD Almighty will be called the Holy Mountain.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 4, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: Once again old men and women will walk Jerusalem''s streets with a cane and sit together in the city squares.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 5, 'And the streets of the city will be filled with boys and girls at play.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 6, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: All this may seem impossible to you now, a small and discouraged remnant of God''s people. But do you think this is impossible for me, the LORD Almighty?', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 7, 'This is what the LORD Almighty says: You can be sure that I will rescue my people from the east and from the west.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 8, 'I will bring them home again to live safely in Jerusalem. They will be my people, and I will be faithful and just toward them as their God.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 9, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: Take heart and finish the task! You have heard what the prophets have been saying about building the Temple of the LORD Almighty ever since the foundation was laid.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 10, 'Before the work on the Temple began, there were no jobs and no wages for either people or animals. No traveler was safe from the enemy, for there were enemies on all sides. I had turned everyone against each other.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 11, 'But now I will not treat the remnant of my people as I treated them before, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 12, 'For I am planting seeds of peace and prosperity among you. The grapevines will be heavy with fruit. The earth will produce its crops, and the sky will release the dew. Once more I will make the remnant in Judah and Israel the heirs of these blessings.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 13, 'Among the nations, Judah and Israel had become symbols of what it means to be cursed. But no longer! Now I will rescue you and make you both a symbol and a source of blessing! So don''t be afraid or discouraged, but instead get on with rebuilding the Temple!', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 14, '"For this is what the LORD Almighty says: I did not change my mind when your ancestors angered me and I promised to punish them, says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 15, 'Neither will I change my decision to bless Jerusalem and the people of Judah. So don''t be afraid.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 16, 'But this is what you must do: Tell the truth to each other. Render verdicts in your courts that are just and that lead to peace.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 17, 'Do not make evil plots to harm each other. And stop this habit of swearing to things that are false. I hate all these things, says the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 18, 'Here is another message that came to me from the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 19, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: The traditional fasts and times of mourning you have kept in early summer, midsummer, autumn, and winter are now ended. They will become festivals of joy and celebration for the people of Judah. So love truth and peace.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 20, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: People from nations and cities around the world will travel to Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 21, 'The people of one city will say to the people in another, `Let us go to Jerusalem to ask the LORD to bless us and to seek the LORD Almighty. We are planning to go ourselves.''', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 22, 'People from many nations, even powerful nations, will come to Jerusalem to seek the LORD Almighty and to ask the LORD to bless them.', 'NLT'),
(42, 8, 23, '"This is what the LORD Almighty says: In those days ten people from nations and languages around the world will clutch at the hem of one Jew''s robe. And they will say, `Please let us walk with you, for we have heard that God is with you.''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 1, 'This is the message from the LORD against the land of Aram and the city of Damascus, for the eyes of all humanity, including the people of Israel, are on the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 2, 'Doom is certain for Hamath, near Damascus, and for the cities of Tyre and Sidon, too, though they are so clever.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 3, 'Tyre has built a strong fortress and has piled up so much silver and gold that it is as common as dust in the streets!', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 4, 'But now the Lord will strip away Tyre''s possessions and hurl its fortifications into the Mediterranean Sea. Tyre will be set on fire and burned to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 5, 'The city of Ashkelon will see Tyre fall and will be filled with fear. Gaza will shake with terror, and so will Ekron, for their hopes will be dashed. Gaza will be conquered and its king killed, and Ashkelon will be completely deserted.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 6, 'Foreigners will occupy the city of Ashdod. Thus, I will destroy the pride of the Philistines.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 7, 'They will no longer eat meat with blood in it or feed on other forbidden foods. All the surviving Philistines will worship our God and be adopted as a new clan in Judah. And the Philistines of Ekron will join my people, just as the Jebusites once did.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 8, 'I will guard my Temple and protect it from invading armies. I am closely watching their movements. No foreign oppressor will ever again overrun my people''s land.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 9, 'Rejoice greatly, O people of Zion! Shout in triumph, O people of Jerusalem! Look, your king is coming to you. He is righteous and victorious, yet he is humble, riding on a donkey--even on a donkey''s colt.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 10, 'I will remove the battle chariots from Israel and the warhorses from Jerusalem, and I will destroy all the weapons used in battle. Your king will bring peace to the nations. His realm will stretch from sea to sea and from the Euphrates River to the ends of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 11, 'Because of the covenant I made with you, sealed with blood, I will free your prisoners from death in a waterless dungeon.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 12, 'Come back to the place of safety, all you prisoners, for there is yet hope! I promise this very day that I will repay you two mercies for each of your woes!', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 13, 'Judah is my bow, and Israel is my arrow! Jerusalem is my sword, and like a warrior, I will brandish it against the Greeks.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 14, 'The LORD will appear above his people; his arrows will fly like lightning! The Sovereign LORD will sound the trumpet; he will go out against his enemies like a whirlwind from the southern desert.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 15, 'The LORD Almighty will protect his people, and they will subdue their enemies with sling stones. They will shout in battle as though drunk with wine, shedding the blood of their enemies. They will be filled with blood like a bowl, drenched with blood like the corners of the altar.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 16, 'When that day arrives, the LORD their God will rescue his people, just as a shepherd rescues his sheep. They will sparkle in his land like jewels in a crown.', 'NLT'),
(42, 9, 17, 'How wonderful and beautiful they will be! The young men and women will thrive on the abundance of grain and new wine.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 1, 'Ask the LORD for rain in the spring, and he will give it. It is the LORD who makes storm clouds that drop showers of rain so that every field becomes a lush pasture.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 2, 'Household gods give false advice, fortune-tellers predict only lies, and interpreters of dreams pronounce comfortless falsehoods. So my people are wandering like lost sheep, without a shepherd to protect and guide them.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 3, '"My anger burns against your shepherds, and I will punish these leaders. For the LORD Almighty has arrived to look after his flock of Judah; he will make them strong and glorious, like a proud warhorse in battle.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 4, 'From Judah will come the cornerstone, the tent peg, the battle bow, and all the rulers.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 5, 'They will be like mighty warriors in battle, trampling their enemies in the mud under their feet. Since the LORD is with them as they fight, they will overthrow even the horsemen of the enemy.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 6, '"I will strengthen Judah and save Israel; I will reestablish them because I love them. It will be as though I had never rejected them, for I am the LORD their God, who will hear their cries.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 7, 'The people of Israel will become like mighty warriors, and their hearts will be happy as if by wine. Their children, too, will see it all and be glad; their hearts will rejoice in the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 8, 'When I whistle to them, they will come running, for I have redeemed them. From the few that are left, their population will grow again to its former size.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 9, 'Though I have scattered them like seeds among the nations, still they will remember me in distant lands. With their children, they will survive and come home again to Israel.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 10, 'I will bring them back from Egypt and Assyria and resettle them in Gilead and Lebanon. There won''t be enough room for them all!', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 11, 'They will pass safely through the sea of distress, for the waves of the sea will be held back. And the waters of the Nile will become dry. The pride of Assyria will be crushed, and the rule of Egypt will end.', 'NLT'),
(42, 10, 12, 'I will make my people strong in my power, and they will go wherever they wish by my authority. I, the LORD, have spoken!"', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 1, 'Open your doors, Lebanon, so that fire may sweep through your cedar forests.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 2, 'Weep, you cypress trees, for all the ruined cedars; the tallest and most beautiful of them are fallen. Weep, you oaks of Bashan, as you watch the thickest forests being felled.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 3, 'Listen to the wailing of the shepherds, for their wealth is gone. Hear the young lions roaring, for their thickets in the Jordan Valley have been destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 4, 'This is what the LORD my God says: "Go and care for a flock that is intended for slaughter.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 5, 'The buyers will slaughter their sheep without remorse. The sellers will say, `Praise the LORD, I am now rich!'' Even the shepherds have no compassion for them.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 6, 'And likewise, I will no longer have pity on the inhabitants of the land," says the LORD. "I will let them fall into each other''s clutches, as well as into the clutches of their king. They will turn the land into a wilderness, and I will not protect them."', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 7, 'So I cared for the flock intended for slaughter--the flock that was oppressed. Then I took two shepherd''s staffs and named one Favor and the other Union.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 8, 'I got rid of their three evil shepherds in a single month. But I became impatient with these sheep--this nation--and they hated me, too.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 9, 'So I told them, "I won''t be your shepherd any longer. If you die, you die. If you are killed, you are killed. And those who remain will devour each other!"', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 10, 'Then I took my staff called Favor and snapped it in two, showing that I had revoked the covenant I had made with all the nations.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 11, 'That was the end of my covenant with them. Those who bought and sold sheep were watching me, and they knew that the LORD was speaking to them through my actions.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 12, 'And I said to them, "If you like, give me my wages, whatever I am worth; but only if you want to." So they counted out for my wages thirty pieces of silver.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 13, 'And the LORD said to me, "Throw it to the potters "--this magnificent sum at which they valued me! So I took the thirty coins and threw them to the potters in the Temple of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 14, 'Then I broke my other staff, Union, to show that the bond of unity between Judah and Israel was broken.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 15, 'Then the LORD said to me, "Go again and play the part of a worthless shepherd.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 16, 'This will illustrate how I will give this nation a shepherd who will not care for the sheep that are threatened by death, nor look after the young, nor heal the injured, nor feed the healthy. Instead, this shepherd will eat the meat of the fattest sheep and tear off their hooves.', 'NLT'),
(42, 11, 17, 'Doom is certain for this worthless shepherd who abandons the flock! The sword will cut his arm and pierce his right eye! His arm will become useless, and his right eye completely blind!"', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 1, 'This message concerning the fate of Israel came from the LORD: "This message is from the LORD, who stretched out the heavens, laid the foundations of the earth, and formed the spirit within humans.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 2, 'I will make Jerusalem and Judah like an intoxicating drink to all the nearby nations that send their armies to besiege Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 3, 'On that day I will make Jerusalem a heavy stone, a burden for the world. None of the nations who try to lift it will escape unscathed.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 4, '"On that day, says the LORD, I will cause every horse to panic and every rider to lose his nerve. I will watch over the people of Judah, but I will blind the horses of her enemies.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 5, 'And the clans of Judah will say to themselves, `The people of Jerusalem have found strength in the LORD Almighty, their God.''', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 6, '"On that day I will make the clans of Judah like a brazier that sets a woodpile ablaze or like a burning torch among sheaves of grain. They will burn up all the neighboring nations right and left, while the people living in Jerusalem remain secure.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 7, 'The LORD will give victory to the rest of Judah first, before Jerusalem, so that the people of Jerusalem and the royal line of David will not have greater honor than the rest of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 8, 'On that day the LORD will defend the people of Jerusalem; the weakest among them will be as mighty as King David! And the royal descendants will be like God, like the angel of the LORD who goes before them!', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 9, 'For my plan is to destroy all the nations that come against Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 10, '"Then I will pour out a spirit of grace and prayer on the family of David and on all the people of Jerusalem. They will look on me whom they have pierced and mourn for him as for an only son. They will grieve bitterly for him as for a firstborn son who has died.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 11, 'The sorrow and mourning in Jerusalem on that day will be like the grievous mourning of Hadad-rimmon in the valley of Megiddo.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 12, '"All Israel will weep in profound sorrow, each family by itself, with the husbands and wives in separate groups. The family of David will mourn, along with the family of Nathan,', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 13, 'the family of Levi, and the family of Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(42, 12, 14, 'Each of the surviving families from Judah will mourn separately, husbands and wives apart.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 1, '"On that day a fountain will be opened for the dynasty of David and for the people of Jerusalem, a fountain to cleanse them from all their sins and defilement.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 2, '"And on that day, says the LORD Almighty, I will get rid of every trace of idol worship throughout the land, so that even the names of the idols will be forgotten. I will remove from the land all false prophets and the unclean spirits that inspire them.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 3, 'If anyone begins prophesying again, his own father and mother will tell him, `You must die, for you have prophesied lies in the name of the LORD.'' Then his own father and mother will stab him.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 4, '"No one will be boasting then of a prophetic gift! No one will wear prophet''s clothes to try to fool the people.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 5, '`No,'' he will say. `I''m not a prophet; I''m a farmer. The soil has been my means of livelihood from my earliest youth.''', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 6, 'And if someone asks, `Then what are those scars on your chest?'' he will say, `I was wounded at the home of friends!''', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 7, '"Awake, O sword, against my shepherd, the man who is my partner, says the LORD Almighty. Strike down the shepherd, and the sheep will be scattered, and I will turn against the lambs.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 8, 'Two-thirds of the people in the land will be cut off and die, says the LORD. But a third will be left in the land.', 'NLT'),
(42, 13, 9, 'I will bring that group through the fire and make them pure, just as gold and silver are refined and purified by fire. They will call on my name, and I will answer them. I will say, `These are my people,'' and they will say, `The LORD is our God.''"', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 1, 'Watch, for the day of the LORD is coming when your possessions will be plundered right in front of you!', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 2, 'On that day I will gather all the nations to fight against Jerusalem. The city will be taken, the houses plundered, and the women raped. Half the population will be taken away into captivity, and half will be left among the ruins of the city.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 3, 'Then the LORD will go out to fight against those nations, as he has fought in times past.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 4, 'On that day his feet will stand on the Mount of Olives, which faces Jerusalem on the east. And the Mount of Olives will split apart, making a wide valley running from east to west, for half the mountain will move toward the north and half toward the south.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 5, 'You will flee through this valley, for it will reach across to Azal. Yes, you will flee as you did from the earthquake in the days of King Uzziah of Judah. Then the LORD my God will come, and all his holy ones with him.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 6, 'On that day the sources of light will no longer shine,', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 7, 'yet there will be continuous day! Only the LORD knows how this could happen! There will be no normal day and night, for at evening time it will still be light.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 8, 'On that day life-giving waters will flow out from Jerusalem, half toward the Dead Sea and half toward the Mediterranean, flowing continuously both in summer and in winter.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 9, 'And the LORD will be king over all the earth. On that day there will be one LORD--his name alone will be worshiped.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 10, 'All the land from Geba, north of Judah, to Rimmon, south of Jerusalem, will become one vast plain. But Jerusalem will be raised up in its original place and will be inhabited all the way from the Benjamin Gate over to the site of the old gate, then to the Corner Gate, and from the Tower of Hananel to the king''s winepresses.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 11, 'And Jerusalem will be filled, safe at last, never again to be cursed and destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 12, 'And the LORD will send a plague on all the nations that fought against Jerusalem. Their people will become like walking corpses, their flesh rotting away. Their eyes will shrivel in their sockets, and their tongues will decay in their mouths.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 13, 'On that day they will be terrified, stricken by the LORD with great panic. They will fight against each other in hand-to-hand combat;', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 14, 'Judah, too, will be fighting at Jerusalem. The wealth of all the neighboring nations will be captured--great quantities of gold and silver and fine clothing.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 15, 'This same plague will strike the horses, mules, camels, donkeys, and all the other animals in the enemy camps.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 16, 'In the end, the enemies of Jerusalem who survive the plague will go up to Jerusalem each year to worship the King, the LORD Almighty, and to celebrate the Festival of Shelters.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 17, 'And any nation anywhere in the world that refuses to come to Jerusalem to worship the King, the LORD Almighty, will have no rain.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 18, 'And if the people of Egypt refuse to attend the festival, the LORD will punish them with the same plague that he sends on the other nations who refuse to go.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 19, 'Egypt and the other nations will all be punished if they don''t go to celebrate the festival.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 20, 'On that day even the harness bells of the horses will be inscribed with these words: SET APART AS HOLY TO THE LORD. And the cooking pots in the Temple of the LORD will be as sacred as the basins used beside the altar.', 'NLT'),
(42, 14, 21, 'In fact, every cooking pot in Jerusalem and Judah will be set apart as holy to the LORD Almighty. All who come to worship will be free to use any of these pots to boil their sacrifices. And on that day there will no longer be traders in the Temple of the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 1, 'This is the message that the LORD gave to Israel through the prophet Malachi.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 2, '"I have loved you deeply," says the LORD. But you retort, "Really? How have you loved us?" And the LORD replies, "I showed my love for you by loving your ancestor Jacob. Yet Esau was Jacob''s brother,', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 3, 'and I rejected Esau and devastated his hill country. I turned Esau''s inheritance into a desert for jackals."', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 4, 'And Esau''s descendants in Edom may say, "We have been shattered, but we will rebuild the ruins." But this is what the LORD Almighty says: "They may try to rebuild, but I will demolish them again! Their country will be known as `The Land of Wickedness,'' and their people will be called `The People with Whom the LORD Is Forever Angry.''', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 5, 'When you see the destruction for yourselves, you will say, `Truly, the LORD''s great power reaches far beyond our borders!''"', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 6, 'The LORD Almighty says to the priests: "A son honors his father, and a servant respects his master. I am your father and master, but where are the honor and respect I deserve? You have despised my name! "But you ask, `How have we ever despised your name?''', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 7, '"You have despised my name by offering defiled sacrifices on my altar. "Then you ask, `How have we defiled the sacrifices?''"You defile them by saying the altar of the LORD deserves no respect.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 8, 'When you give blind animals as sacrifices, isn''t that wrong? And isn''t it wrong to offer animals that are crippled and diseased? Try giving gifts like that to your governor, and see how pleased he is!" says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 9, '"Go ahead, beg God to be merciful to you! But when you bring that kind of offering, why should he show you any favor at all?" asks the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 10, '"I wish that someone among you would shut the Temple doors so that these worthless sacrifices could not be offered! I am not at all pleased with you," says the LORD Almighty, "and I will not accept your offerings.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 11, 'But my name is honored by people of other nations from morning till night. All around the world they offer sweet incense and pure offerings in honor of my name. For my name is great among the nations," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 12, '"But you dishonor my name with your actions. By bringing contemptible food, you are saying it''s all right to defile the Lord''s table.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 13, 'You say, `It''s too hard to serve the LORD,'' and you turn up your noses at his commands," says the LORD Almighty. "Think of it! Animals that are stolen and mutilated, crippled and sick--presented as offerings! Should I accept from you such offerings as these?" asks the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(43, 1, 14, '"Cursed is the cheat who promises to give a fine ram from his flock but then sacrifices a defective one to the Lord. For I am a great king," says the LORD Almighty, "and my name is feared among the nations!', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 1, '"Listen, you priests; this command is for you!', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 2, 'Listen to me and take it to heart. Honor my name," says the LORD Almighty, "or I will bring a terrible curse against you. I will curse even the blessings you receive. Indeed, I have already cursed them, because you have not taken my warning seriously.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 3, 'I will rebuke your descendants and splatter your faces with the dung of your festival sacrifices, and I will add you to the dung heap.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 4, 'Then at last you will know it was I who sent you this warning so that my covenant with the Levites may continue," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 5, '"The purpose of my covenant with the Levites was to bring life and peace, and this is what I gave them. This called for reverence from them, and they greatly revered me and stood in awe of my name.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 6, 'They passed on to the people all the truth they received from me. They did not lie or cheat; they walked with me, living good and righteous lives, and they turned many from lives of sin.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 7, 'The priests'' lips should guard knowledge, and people should go to them for instruction, for the priests are the messengers of the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 8, 'But not you! You have left God''s paths. Your `guidance'' has caused many to stumble into sin. You have corrupted the covenant I made with the Levites," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 9, '"So I have made you despised and humiliated in the eyes of all the people. For you have not obeyed me but have shown partiality in your interpretation of the law."', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 10, 'Are we not all children of the same Father? Are we not all created by the same God? Then why are we faithless to each other, violating the covenant of our ancestors?', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 11, 'In Judah, in Israel, and in Jerusalem there is treachery, for the men of Judah have defiled the LORD''s beloved sanctuary by marrying women who worship idols.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 12, 'May the LORD cut off from the nation of Israel every last man who has done this and yet brings an offering to the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 13, 'Here is another thing you do. You cover the LORD''s altar with tears, weeping and groaning because he pays no attention to your offerings, and he doesn''t accept them with pleasure.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 14, 'You cry out, "Why has the LORD abandoned us?" I''ll tell you why! Because the LORD witnessed the vows you and your wife made to each other on your wedding day when you were young. But you have been disloyal to her, though she remained your faithful companion, the wife of your marriage vows.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 15, 'Didn''t the LORD make you one with your wife? In body and spirit you are his. And what does he want? Godly children from your union. So guard yourself; remain loyal to the wife of your youth.', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 16, '"For I hate divorce!" says the LORD, the God of Israel. "It is as cruel as putting on a victim''s bloodstained coat," says the LORD Almighty. "So guard yourself; always remain loyal to your wife."', 'NLT'),
(43, 2, 17, 'You have wearied the LORD with your words. "Wearied him?" you ask. "How have we wearied him?" You have wearied him by suggesting that the LORD favors evildoers since he does not punish them. You have wearied him by asking, "Where is the God of justice?"', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 1, '"Look! I am sending my messenger, and he will prepare the way before me. Then the Lord you are seeking will suddenly come to his Temple. The messenger of the covenant, whom you look for so eagerly, is surely coming," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 2, '"But who will be able to endure it when he comes? Who will be able to stand and face him when he appears? For he will be like a blazing fire that refines metal or like a strong soap that whitens clothes.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 3, 'He will sit and judge like a refiner of silver, watching closely as the dross is burned away. He will purify the Levites, refining them like gold or silver, so that they may once again offer acceptable sacrifices to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 4, 'Then once more the LORD will accept the offerings brought to him by the people of Judah and Jerusalem, as he did in former times.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 5, 'At that time I will put you on trial. I will be a ready witness against all sorcerers and adulterers and liars. I will speak against those who cheat employees of their wages, who oppress widows and orphans, or who deprive the foreigners living among you of justice, for these people do not fear me," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 6, '"I am the LORD, and I do not change. That is why you descendants of Jacob are not already completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 7, 'Ever since the days of your ancestors, you have scorned my laws and failed to obey them. Now return to me, and I will return to you," says the LORD Almighty. "But you ask, `How can we return when we have never gone away?''', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 8, '"Should people cheat God? Yet you have cheated me! "But you ask, `What do you mean? When did we ever cheat you?''"You have cheated me of the tithes and offerings due to me.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 9, 'You are under a curse, for your whole nation has been cheating me.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 10, 'Bring all the tithes into the storehouse so there will be enough food in my Temple. If you do," says the LORD Almighty, "I will open the windows of heaven for you. I will pour out a blessing so great you won''t have enough room to take it in! Try it! Let me prove it to you!', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 11, 'Your crops will be abundant, for I will guard them from insects and disease. Your grapes will not shrivel before they are ripe," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 12, '"Then all nations will call you blessed, for your land will be such a delight," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 13, '"You have said terrible things about me," says the LORD. "But you say, `What do you mean? How have we spoken against you?''', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 14, '"You have said, `What''s the use of serving God? What have we gained by obeying his commands or by trying to show the LORD Almighty that we are sorry for our sins?', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 15, 'From now on we will say, "Blessed are the arrogant." For those who do evil get rich, and those who dare God to punish them go free of harm.''"', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 16, 'Then those who feared the LORD spoke with each other, and the LORD listened to what they said. In his presence, a scroll of remembrance was written to record the names of those who feared him and loved to think about him.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 17, '"They will be my people," says the LORD Almighty. "On the day when I act, they will be my own special treasure. I will spare them as a father spares an obedient and dutiful child.', 'NLT'),
(43, 3, 18, 'Then you will again see the difference between the righteous and the wicked, between those who serve God and those who do not."', 'NLT'),
(43, 4, 1, 'The LORD Almighty says, "The day of judgment is coming, burning like a furnace. The arrogant and the wicked will be burned up like straw on that day. They will be consumed like a tree--roots and all.', 'NLT'),
(43, 4, 2, '"But for you who fear my name, the Sun of Righteousness will rise with healing in his wings. And you will go free, leaping with joy like calves let out to pasture.', 'NLT'),
(43, 4, 3, 'On the day when I act, you will tread upon the wicked as if they were dust under your feet," says the LORD Almighty.', 'NLT'),
(43, 4, 4, '"Remember to obey the instructions of my servant Moses, all the laws and regulations that I gave him on Mount Sinai for all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(43, 4, 5, '"Look, I am sending you the prophet Elijah before the great and dreadful day of the LORD arrives.', 'NLT'),
(43, 4, 6, 'His preaching will turn the hearts of parents to their children, and the hearts of children to their parents. Otherwise I will come and strike the land with a curse."', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 1, 'This is a record of the ancestors of Jesus the Messiah, a descendant of King David and of Abraham:', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 2, 'Abraham was the father of Isaac. Isaac was the father of Jacob. Jacob was the father of Judah and his brothers.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 3, 'Judah was the father of Perez and Zerah (their mother was Tamar). Perez was the father of Hezron. Hezron was the father of Ram.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 4, 'Ram was the father of Amminadab. Amminadab was the father of Nahshon. Nahshon was the father of Salmon.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 5, 'Salmon was the father of Boaz (his mother was Rahab). Boaz was the father of Obed (his mother was Ruth). Obed was the father of Jesse.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 6, 'Jesse was the father of King David. David was the father of Solomon (his mother was Bathsheba, the widow of Uriah).', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 7, 'Solomon was the father of Rehoboam. Rehoboam was the father of Abijah. Abijah was the father of Asaph.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 8, 'Asaph was the father of Jehoshaphat. Jehoshaphat was the father of Jehoram. Jehoram was the father of Uzziah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 9, 'Uzziah was the father of Jotham. Jotham was the father of Ahaz. Ahaz was the father of Hezekiah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 10, 'Hezekiah was the father of Manasseh. Manasseh was the father of Amos. Amos was the father of Josiah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 11, 'Josiah was the father of Jehoiachin and his brothers (born at the time of the exile to Babylon).', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 12, 'After the Babylonian exile: Jehoiachin was the father of Shealtiel. Shealtiel was the father of Zerubbabel.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 13, 'Zerubbabel was the father of Abiud. Abiud was the father of Eliakim. Eliakim was the father of Azor.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 14, 'Azor was the father of Zadok. Zadok was the father of Akim. Akim was the father of Eliud.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 15, 'Eliud was the father of Eleazar. Eleazar was the father of Matthan. Matthan was the father of Jacob.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 16, 'Jacob was the father of Joseph, the husband of Mary. Mary was the mother of Jesus, who is called the Messiah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 17, 'All those listed above include fourteen generations from Abraham to King David, and fourteen from David''s time to the Babylonian exile, and fourteen from the Babylonian exile to the Messiah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 18, 'Now this is how Jesus the Messiah was born. His mother, Mary, was engaged to be married to Joseph. But while she was still a virgin, she became pregnant by the Holy Spirit.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 19, 'Joseph, her fiance, being a just man, decided to break the engagement quietly, so as not to disgrace her publicly.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 20, 'As he considered this, he fell asleep, and an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream. "Joseph, son of David," the angel said, "do not be afraid to go ahead with your marriage to Mary. For the child within her has been conceived by the Holy Spirit.', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 21, 'And she will have a son, and you are to name him Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins."', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 22, 'All of this happened to fulfill the Lord''s message through his prophet:', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 23, '"Look! The virgin will conceive a child! She will give birth to a son, and he will be called Immanuel (meaning, God is with us)."', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 24, 'When Joseph woke up, he did what the angel of the Lord commanded. He brought Mary home to be his wife,', 'NLT'),
(44, 1, 25, 'but she remained a virgin until her son was born. And Joseph named him Jesus.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 1, 'Jesus was born in the town of Bethlehem in Judea, during the reign of King Herod. About that time some wise men from eastern lands arrived in Jerusalem, asking,', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 2, '"Where is the newborn king of the Jews? We have seen his star as it arose, and we have come to worship him."', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 3, 'Herod was deeply disturbed by their question, as was all of Jerusalem.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 4, 'He called a meeting of the leading priests and teachers of religious law. "Where did the prophets say the Messiah would be born?" he asked them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 5, '"In Bethlehem," they said, "for this is what the prophet wrote:', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 6, '''O Bethlehem of Judah, you are not just a lowly village in Judah, for a ruler will come from you who will be the shepherd for my people Israel.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 7, 'Then Herod sent a private message to the wise men, asking them to come see him. At this meeting he learned the exact time when they first saw the star.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 8, 'Then he told them, "Go to Bethlehem and search carefully for the child. And when you find him, come back and tell me so that I can go and worship him, too!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 9, 'After this interview the wise men went their way. Once again the star appeared to them, guiding them to Bethlehem. It went ahead of them and stopped over the place where the child was.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 10, 'When they saw the star, they were filled with joy!', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 11, 'They entered the house where the child and his mother, Mary, were, and they fell down before him and worshiped him. Then they opened their treasure chests and gave him gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 12, 'But when it was time to leave, they went home another way, because God had warned them in a dream not to return to Herod.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 13, 'After the wise men were gone, an angel of the Lord appeared to Joseph in a dream. "Get up and flee to Egypt with the child and his mother," the angel said. "Stay there until I tell you to return, because Herod is going to try to kill the child."', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 14, 'That night Joseph left for Egypt with the child and Mary, his mother,', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 15, 'and they stayed there until Herod''s death. This fulfilled what the Lord had spoken through the prophet: "I called my Son out of Egypt."', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 16, 'Herod was furious when he learned that the wise men had outwitted him. He sent soldiers to kill all the boys in and around Bethlehem who were two years old and under, because the wise men had told him the star first appeared to them about two years earlier.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 17, 'Herod''s brutal action fulfilled the prophecy of Jeremiah:', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 18, '"A cry of anguish is heard in Ramah--weeping and mourning unrestrained. Rachel weeps for her children, refusing to be comforted--for they are dead."', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 19, 'When Herod died, an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph in Egypt and told him,', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 20, '"Get up and take the child and his mother back to the land of Israel, because those who were trying to kill the child are dead."', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 21, 'So Joseph returned immediately to Israel with Jesus and his mother.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 22, 'But when he learned that the new ruler was Herod''s son Archelaus, he was afraid. Then, in another dream, he was warned to go to Galilee.', 'NLT'),
(44, 2, 23, 'So they went and lived in a town called Nazareth. This fulfilled what was spoken by the prophets concerning the Messiah: "He will be called a Nazarene."', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 1, 'In those days John the Baptist began preaching in the Judean wilderness. His message was,', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 2, '"Turn from your sins and turn to God, because the Kingdom of Heaven is near. "', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 3, 'Isaiah had spoken of John when he said, "He is a voice shouting in the wilderness: ''Prepare a pathway for the Lord''s coming! Make a straight road for him!''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 4, 'John''s clothes were woven from camel hair, and he wore a leather belt; his food was locusts and wild honey.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 5, 'People from Jerusalem and from every section of Judea and from all over the Jordan Valley went out to the wilderness to hear him preach.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 6, 'And when they confessed their sins, he baptized them in the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 7, 'But when he saw many Pharisees and Sadducees coming to be baptized, he denounced them. "You brood of snakes!" he exclaimed. "Who warned you to flee God''s coming judgment?', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 8, 'Prove by the way you live that you have really turned from your sins and turned to God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 9, 'Don''t just say, ''We''re safe--we''re the descendants of Abraham.'' That proves nothing. God can change these stones here into children of Abraham.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 10, 'Even now the ax of God''s judgment is poised, ready to sever your roots. Yes, every tree that does not produce good fruit will be chopped down and thrown into the fire.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 11, '"I baptize with water those who turn from their sins and turn to God. But someone is coming soon who is far greater than I am--so much greater that I am not even worthy to be his slave. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and with fire.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 12, 'He is ready to separate the chaff from the grain with his winnowing fork. Then he will clean up the threshing area, storing the grain in his barn but burning the chaff with never-ending fire."', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 13, 'Then Jesus went from Galilee to the Jordan River to be baptized by John.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 14, 'But John didn''t want to baptize him. "I am the one who needs to be baptized by you," he said, "so why are you coming to me?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 15, 'But Jesus said, "It must be done, because we must do everything that is right. "So then John baptized him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 16, 'After his baptism, as Jesus came up out of the water, the heavens were opened and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove and settling on him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 3, 17, 'And a voice from heaven said, "This is my beloved Son, and I am fully pleased with him."', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 1, 'Then Jesus was led out into the wilderness by the Holy Spirit to be tempted there by the Devil.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 2, 'For forty days and forty nights he ate nothing and became very hungry.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 3, 'Then the Devil came and said to him, "If you are the Son of God, change these stones into loaves of bread."', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 4, 'But Jesus told him, "No! The Scriptures say, ''People need more than bread for their life; they must feed on every word of God.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 5, 'Then the Devil took him to Jerusalem, to the highest point of the Temple,', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 6, 'and said, "If you are the Son of God, jump off! For the Scriptures say, ''He orders his angels to protect you. And they will hold you with their hands to keep you from striking your foot on a stone.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 7, 'Jesus responded, "The Scriptures also say, ''Do not test the Lord your God.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 8, 'Next the Devil took him to the peak of a very high mountain and showed him the nations of the world and all their glory.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 9, '"I will give it all to you," he said, "if you will only kneel down and worship me."', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 10, '"Get out of here, Satan," Jesus told him. "For the Scriptures say, ''You must worship the Lord your God; serve only him.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 11, 'Then the Devil went away, and angels came and cared for Jesus.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 12, 'When Jesus heard that John had been arrested, he left Judea and returned to Galilee.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 13, 'But instead of going to Nazareth, he went to Capernaum, beside the Sea of Galilee, in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 14, 'This fulfilled Isaiah''s prophecy:', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 15, '"In the land of Zebulun and of Naphtali, beside the sea, beyond the Jordan River--in Galilee where so many Gentiles live--', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 16, 'the people who sat in darkness have seen a great light. And for those who lived in the land where death casts its shadow, a light has shined."', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 17, 'From then on, Jesus began to preach, "Turn from your sins and turn to God, because the Kingdom of Heaven is near. "', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 18, 'One day as Jesus was walking along the shore beside the Sea of Galilee, he saw two brothers--Simon, also called Peter, and Andrew--fishing with a net, for they were commercial fishermen.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 19, 'Jesus called out to them, "Come, be my disciples, and I will show you how to fish for people!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 20, 'And they left their nets at once and went with him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 21, 'A little farther up the shore he saw two other brothers, James and John, sitting in a boat with their father, Zebedee, mending their nets. And he called them to come, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 22, 'They immediately followed him, leaving the boat and their father behind.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 23, 'Jesus traveled throughout Galilee teaching in the synagogues, preaching everywhere the Good News about the Kingdom. And he healed people who had every kind of sickness and disease.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 24, 'News about him spread far beyond the borders of Galilee so that the sick were soon coming to be healed from as far away as Syria. And whatever their illness and pain, or if they were possessed by demons, or were epileptics, or were paralyzed--he healed them all.', 'NLT'),
(44, 4, 25, 'Large crowds followed him wherever he went--people from Galilee, the Ten Towns, Jerusalem, from all over Judea, and from east of the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 1, 'One day as the crowds were gathering, Jesus went up the mountainside with his disciples and sat down to teach them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 2, 'This is what he taught them:', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 3, '"God blesses those who realize their need for him, for the Kingdom of Heaven is given to them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 4, 'God blesses those who mourn, for they will be comforted.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 5, 'God blesses those who are gentle and lowly, for the whole earth will belong to them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 6, 'God blesses those who are hungry and thirsty for justice, for they will receive it in full.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 7, 'God blesses those who are merciful, for they will be shown mercy.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 8, 'God blesses those whose hearts are pure, for they will see God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 9, 'God blesses those who work for peace, for they will be called the children of God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 10, 'God blesses those who are persecuted because they live for God, for the Kingdom of Heaven is theirs.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 11, '"God blesses you when you are mocked and persecuted and lied about because you are my followers.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 12, 'Be happy about it! Be very glad! For a great reward awaits you in heaven. And remember, the ancient prophets were persecuted, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 13, '"You are the salt of the earth. But what good is salt if it has lost its flavor? Can you make it useful again? It will be thrown out and trampled underfoot as worthless.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 14, 'You are the light of the world--like a city on a mountain, glowing in the night for all to see.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 15, 'Don''t hide your light under a basket! Instead, put it on a stand and let it shine for all.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 16, 'In the same way, let your good deeds shine out for all to see, so that everyone will praise your heavenly Father.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 17, '"Don''t misunderstand why I have come. I did not come to abolish the law of Moses or the writings of the prophets. No, I came to fulfill them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 18, 'I assure you, until heaven and earth disappear, even the smallest detail of God''s law will remain until its purpose is achieved.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 19, 'So if you break the smallest commandment and teach others to do the same, you will be the least in the Kingdom of Heaven. But anyone who obeys God''s laws and teaches them will be great in the Kingdom of Heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 20, '"But I warn you--unless you obey God better than the teachers of religious law and the Pharisees do, you can''t enter the Kingdom of Heaven at all!', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 21, '"You have heard that the law of Moses says, ''Do not murder. If you commit murder, you are subject to judgment.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 22, 'But I say, if you are angry with someone, you are subject to judgment! If you call someone an idiot, you are in danger of being brought before the high council. And if you curse someone, you are in danger of the fires of hell.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 23, '"So if you are standing before the altar in the Temple, offering a sacrifice to God, and you suddenly remember that someone has something against you,', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 24, 'leave your sacrifice there beside the altar. Go and be reconciled to that person. Then come and offer your sacrifice to God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 25, 'Come to terms quickly with your enemy before it is too late and you are dragged into court, handed over to an officer, and thrown in jail.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 26, 'I assure you that you won''t be free again until you have paid the last penny.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 27, '"You have heard that the law of Moses says, ''Do not commit adultery.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 28, 'But I say, anyone who even looks at a woman with lust in his eye has already committed adultery with her in his heart.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 29, 'So if your eye--even if it is your good eye--causes you to lust, gouge it out and throw it away. It is better for you to lose one part of your body than for your whole body to be thrown into hell.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 30, 'And if your hand--even if it is your stronger hand--causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it away. It is better for you to lose one part of your body than for your whole body to be thrown into hell.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 31, '"You have heard that the law of Moses says, ''A man can divorce his wife by merely giving her a letter of divorce.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 32, 'But I say that a man who divorces his wife, unless she has been unfaithful, causes her to commit adultery. And anyone who marries a divorced woman commits adultery.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 33, '"Again, you have heard that the law of Moses says, ''Do not break your vows; you must carry out the vows you have made to the Lord.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 34, 'But I say, don''t make any vows! If you say, ''By heaven!'' it is a sacred vow because heaven is God''s throne.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 35, 'And if you say, ''By the earth!'' it is a sacred vow because the earth is his footstool. And don''t swear, ''By Jerusalem!'' for Jerusalem is the city of the great King.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 36, 'Don''t even swear, ''By my head!'' for you can''t turn one hair white or black.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 37, 'Just say a simple, ''Yes, I will,'' or ''No, I won''t.'' Your word is enough. To strengthen your promise with a vow shows that something is wrong.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 38, '"You have heard that the law of Moses says, ''If an eye is injured, injure the eye of the person who did it. If a tooth gets knocked out, knock out the tooth of the person who did it.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 39, 'But I say, don''t resist an evil person! If you are slapped on the right cheek, turn the other, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 40, 'If you are ordered to court and your shirt is taken from you, give your coat, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 41, 'If a soldier demands that you carry his gear for a mile, carry it two miles.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 42, 'Give to those who ask, and don''t turn away from those who want to borrow.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 43, '"You have heard that the law of Moses says, ''Love your neighbor'' and hate your enemy.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 44, 'But I say, love your enemies! Pray for those who persecute you!', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 45, 'In that way, you will be acting as true children of your Father in heaven. For he gives his sunlight to both the evil and the good, and he sends rain on the just and on the unjust, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 46, 'If you love only those who love you, what good is that? Even corrupt tax collectors do that much.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 47, 'If you are kind only to your friends, how are you different from anyone else? Even pagans do that.', 'NLT'),
(44, 5, 48, 'But you are to be perfect, even as your Father in heaven is perfect.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 1, '"Take care! Don''t do your good deeds publicly, to be admired, because then you will lose the reward from your Father in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 2, 'When you give a gift to someone in need, don''t shout about it as the hypocrites do--blowing trumpets in the synagogues and streets to call attention to their acts of charity! I assure you, they have received all the reward they will ever get.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 3, 'But when you give to someone, don''t tell your left hand what your right hand is doing.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 4, 'Give your gifts in secret, and your Father, who knows all secrets, will reward you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 5, '"And now about prayer. When you pray, don''t be like the hypocrites who love to pray publicly on street corners and in the synagogues where everyone can see them. I assure you, that is all the reward they will ever get.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 6, 'But when you pray, go away by yourself, shut the door behind you, and pray to your Father secretly. Then your Father, who knows all secrets, will reward you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 7, '"When you pray, don''t babble on and on as people of other religions do. They think their prayers are answered only by repeating their words again and again.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 8, 'Don''t be like them, because your Father knows exactly what you need even before you ask him!', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 9, 'Pray like this: Our Father in heaven, may your name be honored.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 10, 'May your Kingdom come soon. May your will be done here on earth, just as it is in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 11, 'Give us our food for today,', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 12, 'and forgive us our sins, just as we have forgiven those who have sinned against us.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 13, 'And don''t let us yield to temptation, but deliver us from the evil one.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 14, '"If you forgive those who sin against you, your heavenly Father will forgive you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 15, 'But if you refuse to forgive others, your Father will not forgive your sins.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 16, '"And when you fast, don''t make it obvious, as the hypocrites do, who try to look pale and disheveled so people will admire them for their fasting. I assure you, that is the only reward they will ever get.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 17, 'But when you fast, comb your hair and wash your face.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 18, 'Then no one will suspect you are fasting, except your Father, who knows what you do in secret. And your Father, who knows all secrets, will reward you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 19, '"Don''t store up treasures here on earth, where they can be eaten by moths and get rusty, and where thieves break in and steal.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 20, 'Store your treasures in heaven, where they will never become moth-eaten or rusty and where they will be safe from thieves.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 21, 'Wherever your treasure is, there your heart and thoughts will also be.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 22, '"Your eye is a lamp for your body. A pure eye lets sunshine into your soul.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 23, 'But an evil eye shuts out the light and plunges you into darkness. If the light you think you have is really darkness, how deep that darkness will be!', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 24, '"No one can serve two masters. For you will hate one and love the other, or be devoted to one and despise the other. You cannot serve both God and money.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 25, '"So I tell you, don''t worry about everyday life--whether you have enough food, drink, and clothes. Doesn''t life consist of more than food and clothing?', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 26, 'Look at the birds. They don''t need to plant or harvest or put food in barns because your heavenly Father feeds them. And you are far more valuable to him than they are.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 27, 'Can all your worries add a single moment to your life? Of course not.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 28, '"And why worry about your clothes? Look at the lilies and how they grow. They don''t work or make their clothing,', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 29, 'yet Solomon in all his glory was not dressed as beautifully as they are.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 30, 'And if God cares so wonderfully for flowers that are here today and gone tomorrow, won''t he more surely care for you? You have so little faith!', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 31, '"So don''t worry about having enough food or drink or clothing.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 32, 'Why be like the pagans who are so deeply concerned about these things? Your heavenly Father already knows all your needs,', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 33, 'and he will give you all you need from day to day if you live for him and make the Kingdom of God your primary concern.', 'NLT'),
(44, 6, 34, '"So don''t worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow will bring its own worries. Today''s trouble is enough for today.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 1, '"Stop judging others, and you will not be judged.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 2, 'For others will treat you as you treat them. Whatever measure you use in judging others, it will be used to measure how you are judged.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 3, 'And why worry about a speck in your friend''s eye when you have a log in your own?', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 4, 'How can you think of saying, ''Let me help you get rid of that speck in your eye,'' when you can''t see past the log in your own eye?', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 5, 'Hypocrite! First get rid of the log from your own eye; then perhaps you will see well enough to deal with the speck in your friend''s eye.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 6, '"Don''t give what is holy to unholy people. Don''t give pearls to swine! They will trample the pearls, then turn and attack you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 7, '"Keep on asking, and you will be given what you ask for. Keep on looking, and you will find. Keep on knocking, and the door will be opened.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 8, 'For everyone who asks, receives. Everyone who seeks, finds. And the door is opened to everyone who knocks.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 9, 'You parents--if your children ask for a loaf of bread, do you give them a stone instead?', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 10, 'Or if they ask for a fish, do you give them a snake? Of course not!', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 11, 'If you sinful people know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your heavenly Father give good gifts to those who ask him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 12, '"Do for others what you would like them to do for you. This is a summary of all that is taught in the law and the prophets.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 13, '"You can enter God''s Kingdom only through the narrow gate. The highway to hell is broad, and its gate is wide for the many who choose the easy way.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 14, 'But the gateway to life is small, and the road is narrow, and only a few ever find it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 15, '"Beware of false prophets who come disguised as harmless sheep, but are really wolves that will tear you apart.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 16, 'You can detect them by the way they act, just as you can identify a tree by its fruit. You don''t pick grapes from thornbushes, or figs from thistles.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 17, 'A healthy tree produces good fruit, and an unhealthy tree produces bad fruit.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 18, 'A good tree can''t produce bad fruit, and a bad tree can''t produce good fruit.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 19, 'So every tree that does not produce good fruit is chopped down and thrown into the fire.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 20, 'Yes, the way to identify a tree or a person is by the kind of fruit that is produced.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 21, '"Not all people who sound religious are really godly. They may refer to me as ''Lord,'' but they still won''t enter the Kingdom of Heaven. The decisive issue is whether they obey my Father in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 22, 'On judgment day many will tell me, ''Lord, Lord, we prophesied in your name and cast out demons in your name and performed many miracles in your name.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 23, 'But I will reply, ''I never knew you. Go away; the things you did were unauthorized. ''', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 24, '"Anyone who listens to my teaching and obeys me is wise, like a person who builds a house on solid rock.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 25, 'Though the rain comes in torrents and the floodwaters rise and the winds beat against that house, it won''t collapse, because it is built on rock.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 26, 'But anyone who hears my teaching and ignores it is foolish, like a person who builds a house on sand.', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 27, 'When the rains and floods come and the winds beat against that house, it will fall with a mighty crash."', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 28, 'After Jesus finished speaking, the crowds were amazed at his teaching,', 'NLT'),
(44, 7, 29, 'for he taught as one who had real authority--quite unlike the teachers of religious law.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 1, 'Large crowds followed Jesus as he came down the mountainside.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 2, 'Suddenly, a man with leprosy approached Jesus. He knelt before him, worshiping. "Lord," the man said, "if you want to, you can make me well again."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 3, 'Jesus touched him. "I want to," he said. "Be healed!" And instantly the leprosy disappeared.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 4, 'Then Jesus said to him, "Go right over to the priest and let him examine you. Don''t talk to anyone along the way. Take along the offering required in the law of Moses for those who have been healed of leprosy, so everyone will have proof of your healing."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 5, 'When Jesus arrived in Capernaum, a Roman officer came and pleaded with him,', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 6, '"Lord, my young servant lies in bed, paralyzed and racked with pain."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 7, 'Jesus said, "I will come and heal him."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 8, 'Then the officer said, "Lord, I am not worthy to have you come into my home. Just say the word from where you are, and my servant will be healed!', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 9, 'I know, because I am under the authority of my superior officers and I have authority over my soldiers. I only need to say, ''Go,'' and they go, or ''Come,'' and they come. And if I say to my slaves, ''Do this or that,'' they do it."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 10, 'When Jesus heard this, he was amazed. Turning to the crowd, he said, "I tell you the truth, I haven''t seen faith like this in all the land of Israel!', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 11, 'And I tell you this, that many Gentiles will come from all over the world and sit down with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob at the feast in the Kingdom of Heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 12, 'But many Israelites--those for whom the Kingdom was prepared--will be cast into outer darkness, where there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 13, 'Then Jesus said to the Roman officer, "Go on home. What you have believed has happened." And the young servant was healed that same hour.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 14, 'When Jesus arrived at Peter''s house, Peter''s mother-in-law was in bed with a high fever.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 15, 'But when Jesus touched her hand, the fever left her. Then she got up and prepared a meal for him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 16, 'That evening many demon-possessed people were brought to Jesus. All the spirits fled when he commanded them to leave; and he healed all the sick.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 17, 'This fulfilled the word of the Lord through Isaiah, who said, "He took our sicknesses and removed our diseases."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 18, 'When Jesus noticed how large the crowd was growing, he instructed his disciples to cross to the other side of the lake.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 19, 'Then one of the teachers of religious law said to him, "Teacher, I will follow you no matter where you go!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 20, 'But Jesus said, "Foxes have dens to live in, and birds have nests, but I, the Son of Man, have no home of my own, not even a place to lay my head."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 21, 'Another of his disciples said, "Lord, first let me return home and bury my father."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 22, 'But Jesus told him, "Follow me now! Let those who are spiritually dead care for their own dead."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 23, 'Then Jesus got into the boat and started across the lake with his disciples.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 24, 'Suddenly, a terrible storm came up, with waves breaking into the boat. But Jesus was sleeping.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 25, 'The disciples went to him and woke him up, shouting, "Lord, save us! We''re going to drown!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 26, 'And Jesus answered, "Why are you afraid? You have so little faith!" Then he stood up and rebuked the wind and waves, and suddenly all was calm.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 27, 'The disciples just sat there in awe. "Who is this?" they asked themselves. "Even the wind and waves obey him!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 28, 'When Jesus arrived on the other side of the lake in the land of the Gadarenes, two men who were possessed by demons met him. They lived in a cemetery and were so dangerous that no one could go through that area.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 29, 'They began screaming at him, "Why are you bothering us, Son of God? You have no right to torture us before God''s appointed time!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 30, 'A large herd of pigs was feeding in the distance,', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 31, 'so the demons begged, "If you cast us out, send us into that herd of pigs."', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 32, '"All right, go!" Jesus commanded them. So the demons came out of the men and entered the pigs, and the whole herd plunged down the steep hillside into the lake and drowned in the water.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 33, 'The herdsmen fled to the nearby city, telling everyone what happened to the demon-possessed men.', 'NLT'),
(44, 8, 34, 'The entire town came out to meet Jesus, but they begged him to go away and leave them alone.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 1, 'Jesus climbed into a boat and went back across the lake to his own town.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 2, 'Some people brought to him a paralyzed man on a mat. Seeing their faith, Jesus said to the paralyzed man, "Take heart, son! Your sins are forgiven."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 3, '"Blasphemy! This man talks like he is God!" some of the teachers of religious law said among themselves.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 4, 'Jesus knew what they were thinking, so he asked them, "Why are you thinking such evil thoughts?', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 5, 'Is it easier to say, ''Your sins are forgiven'' or ''Get up and walk''?', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 6, 'I will prove that I, the Son of Man, have the authority on earth to forgive sins." Then Jesus turned to the paralyzed man and said, "Stand up, take your mat, and go on home, because you are healed!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 7, 'And the man jumped up and went home!', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 8, 'Fear swept through the crowd as they saw this happen right before their eyes. They praised God for sending a man with such great authority.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 9, 'As Jesus was going down the road, he saw Matthew sitting at his tax-collection booth. "Come, be my disciple," Jesus said to him. So Matthew got up and followed him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 10, 'That night Matthew invited Jesus and his disciples to be his dinner guests, along with his fellow tax collectors and many other notorious sinners.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 11, 'The Pharisees were indignant. "Why does your teacher eat with such scum?" they asked his disciples.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 12, 'When he heard this, Jesus replied, "Healthy people don''t need a doctor--sick people do."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 13, 'Then he added, "Now go and learn the meaning of this Scripture: ''I want you to be merciful; I don''t want your sacrifices.'' For I have come to call sinners, not those who think they are already good enough."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 14, 'One day the disciples of John the Baptist came to Jesus and asked him, "Why do we and the Pharisees fast, but your disciples don''t fast?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 15, 'Jesus responded, "Should the wedding guests mourn while celebrating with the groom? Someday he will be taken from them, and then they will fast.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 16, 'And who would patch an old garment with unshrunk cloth? For the patch shrinks and pulls away from the old cloth, leaving an even bigger hole than before.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 17, 'And no one puts new wine into old wineskins. The old skins would burst from the pressure, spilling the wine and ruining the skins. New wine must be stored in new wineskins. That way both the wine and the wineskins are preserved."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 18, 'As Jesus was saying this, the leader of a synagogue came and knelt down before him. "My daughter has just died," he said, "but you can bring her back to life again if you just come and lay your hand upon her."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 19, 'As Jesus and the disciples were going to the official''s home,', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 20, 'a woman who had had a hemorrhage for twelve years came up behind him. She touched the fringe of his robe,', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 21, 'for she thought, "If I can just touch his robe, I will be healed."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 22, 'Jesus turned around and said to her, "Daughter, be encouraged! Your faith has made you well." And the woman was healed at that moment.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 23, 'When Jesus arrived at the official''s home, he noticed the noisy crowds and heard the funeral music.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 24, 'He said, "Go away, for the girl isn''t dead; she''s only asleep." But the crowd laughed at him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 25, 'When the crowd was finally outside, Jesus went in and took the girl by the hand, and she stood up!', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 26, 'The report of this miracle swept through the entire countryside.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 27, 'After Jesus left the girl''s home, two blind men followed along behind him, shouting, "Son of David, have mercy on us!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 28, 'They went right into the house where he was staying, and Jesus asked them, "Do you believe I can make you see?Yes, Lord," they told him, "we do."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 29, 'Then he touched their eyes and said, "Because of your faith, it will happen."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 30, 'And suddenly they could see! Jesus sternly warned them, "Don''t tell anyone about this."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 31, 'But instead, they spread his fame all over the region.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 32, 'When they left, some people brought to him a man who couldn''t speak because he was possessed by a demon.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 33, 'So Jesus cast out the demon, and instantly the man could talk. The crowds marveled. "Nothing like this has ever happened in Israel!" they exclaimed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 34, 'But the Pharisees said, "He can cast out demons because he is empowered by the prince of demons."', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 35, 'Jesus traveled through all the cities and villages of that area, teaching in the synagogues and announcing the Good News about the Kingdom. And wherever he went, he healed people of every sort of disease and illness.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 36, 'He felt great pity for the crowds that came, because their problems were so great and they didn''t know where to go for help. They were like sheep without a shepherd.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 37, 'He said to his disciples, "The harvest is so great, but the workers are so few.', 'NLT'),
(44, 9, 38, 'So pray to the Lord who is in charge of the harvest; ask him to send out more workers for his fields."', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 1, 'Jesus called his twelve disciples to him and gave them authority to cast out evil spirits and to heal every kind of disease and illness.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 2, 'Here are the names of the twelve apostles: first Simon (also called Peter), then Andrew (Peter''s brother), James (son of Zebedee), John (James''s brother),', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 3, 'Philip, Bartholomew, Thomas, Matthew (the tax collector), James (son of Alphaeus), Thaddaeus,', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 4, 'Simon (the Zealot ), Judas Iscariot (who later betrayed him).', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 5, 'Jesus sent the twelve disciples out with these instructions: "Don''t go to the Gentiles or the Samaritans,', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 6, 'but only to the people of Israel--God''s lost sheep.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 7, 'Go and announce to them that the Kingdom of Heaven is near.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 8, 'Heal the sick, raise the dead, cure those with leprosy, and cast out demons. Give as freely as you have received!', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 9, '"Don''t take any money with you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 10, 'Don''t carry a traveler''s bag with an extra coat and sandals or even a walking stick. Don''t hesitate to accept hospitality, because those who work deserve to be fed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 11, 'Whenever you enter a city or village, search for a worthy man and stay in his home until you leave for the next town.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 12, 'When you are invited into someone''s home, give it your blessing.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 13, 'If it turns out to be a worthy home, let your blessing stand; if it is not, take back the blessing.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 14, 'If a village doesn''t welcome you or listen to you, shake off the dust of that place from your feet as you leave.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 15, 'I assure you, the wicked cities of Sodom and Gomorrah will be better off on the judgment day than that place will be.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 16, '"Look, I am sending you out as sheep among wolves. Be as wary as snakes and harmless as doves.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 17, 'But beware! For you will be handed over to the courts and beaten in the synagogues.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 18, 'And you must stand trial before governors and kings because you are my followers. This will be your opportunity to tell them about me--yes, to witness to the world.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 19, 'When you are arrested, don''t worry about what to say in your defense, because you will be given the right words at the right time.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 20, 'For it won''t be you doing the talking--it will be the Spirit of your Father speaking through you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 21, '"Brother will betray brother to death, fathers will betray their own children, and children will rise against their parents and cause them to be killed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 22, 'And everyone will hate you because of your allegiance to me. But those who endure to the end will be saved.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 23, 'When you are persecuted in one town, flee to the next. I assure you that I, the Son of Man, will return before you have reached all the towns of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 24, '"A student is not greater than the teacher. A servant is not greater than the master.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 25, 'The student shares the teacher''s fate. The servant shares the master''s fate. And since I, the master of the household, have been called the prince of demons, how much more will it happen to you, the members of the household!', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 26, 'But don''t be afraid of those who threaten you. For the time is coming when everything will be revealed; all that is secret will be made public.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 27, 'What I tell you now in the darkness, shout abroad when daybreak comes. What I whisper in your ears, shout from the housetops for all to hear!', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 28, '"Don''t be afraid of those who want to kill you. They can only kill your body; they cannot touch your soul. Fear only God, who can destroy both soul and body in hell.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 29, 'Not even a sparrow, worth only half a penny, can fall to the ground without your Father knowing it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 30, 'And the very hairs on your head are all numbered.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 31, 'So don''t be afraid; you are more valuable to him than a whole flock of sparrows.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 32, '"If anyone acknowledges me publicly here on earth, I will openly acknowledge that person before my Father in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 33, 'But if anyone denies me here on earth, I will deny that person before my Father in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 34, '"Don''t imagine that I came to bring peace to the earth! No, I came to bring a sword.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 35, 'I have come to set a man against his father, and a daughter against her mother, and a daughter-in-law against her mother-in-law.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 36, 'Your enemies will be right in your own household!', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 37, 'If you love your father or mother more than you love me, you are not worthy of being mine; or if you love your son or daughter more than me, you are not worthy of being mine.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 38, 'If you refuse to take up your cross and follow me, you are not worthy of being mine.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 39, 'If you cling to your life, you will lose it; but if you give it up for me, you will find it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 40, '"Anyone who welcomes you is welcoming me, and anyone who welcomes me is welcoming the Father who sent me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 41, 'If you welcome a prophet as one who speaks for God, you will receive the same reward a prophet gets. And if you welcome good and godly people because of their godliness, you will be given a reward like theirs.', 'NLT'),
(44, 10, 42, 'And if you give even a cup of cold water to one of the least of my followers, you will surely be rewarded."', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 1, 'When Jesus had finished giving these instructions to his twelve disciples, he went off teaching and preaching in towns throughout the country.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 2, 'John the Baptist, who was now in prison, heard about all the things the Messiah was doing. So he sent his disciples to ask Jesus,', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 3, '"Are you really the Messiah we''ve been waiting for, or should we keep looking for someone else?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 4, 'Jesus told them, "Go back to John and tell him about what you have heard and seen--', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 5, 'the blind see, the lame walk, the lepers are cured, the deaf hear, the dead are raised to life, and the Good News is being preached to the poor.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 6, 'And tell him: ''God blesses those who are not offended by me. ''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 7, 'When John''s disciples had gone, Jesus began talking about him to the crowds. "Who is this man in the wilderness that you went out to see? Did you find him weak as a reed, moved by every breath of wind?', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 8, 'Or were you expecting to see a man dressed in expensive clothes? Those who dress like that live in palaces, not out in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 9, 'Were you looking for a prophet? Yes, and he is more than a prophet.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 10, 'John is the man to whom the Scriptures refer when they say, ''Look, I am sending my messenger before you, and he will prepare your way before you.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 11, '"I assure you, of all who have ever lived, none is greater than John the Baptist. Yet even the most insignificant person in the Kingdom of Heaven is greater than he is!', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 12, 'And from the time John the Baptist began preaching and baptizing until now, the Kingdom of Heaven has been forcefully advancing, and violent people attack it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 13, 'For before John came, all the teachings of the Scriptures looked forward to this present time.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 14, 'And if you are willing to accept what I say, he is Elijah, the one the prophets said would come.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 15, 'Anyone who is willing to hear should listen and understand!', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 16, '"How shall I describe this generation? These people are like a group of children playing a game in the public square. They complain to their friends,', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 17, '''We played wedding songs, and you weren''t happy, so we played funeral songs, but you weren''t sad.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 18, 'For John the Baptist didn''t drink wine and he often fasted, and you say, ''He''s demon possessed.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 19, 'And I, the Son of Man, feast and drink, and you say, ''He''s a glutton and a drunkard, and a friend of the worst sort of sinners!'' But wisdom is shown to be right by what results from it."', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 20, 'Then Jesus began to denounce the cities where he had done most of his miracles, because they hadn''t turned from their sins and turned to God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 21, '"What horrors await you, Korazin and Bethsaida! For if the miracles I did in you had been done in wicked Tyre and Sidon, their people would have sat in deep repentance long ago, clothed in sackcloth and throwing ashes on their heads to show their remorse.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 22, 'I assure you, Tyre and Sidon will be better off on the judgment day than you!', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 23, 'And you people of Capernaum, will you be exalted to heaven? No, you will be brought down to the place of the dead. For if the miracles I did for you had been done in Sodom, it would still be here today.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 24, 'I assure you, Sodom will be better off on the judgment day than you."', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 25, 'Then Jesus prayed this prayer: "O Father, Lord of heaven and earth, thank you for hiding the truth from those who think themselves so wise and clever, and for revealing it to the childlike.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 26, 'Yes, Father, it pleased you to do it this way!', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 27, '"My Father has given me authority over everything. No one really knows the Son except the Father, and no one really knows the Father except the Son and those to whom the Son chooses to reveal him."', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 28, 'Then Jesus said, "Come to me, all of you who are weary and carry heavy burdens, and I will give you rest.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 29, 'Take my yoke upon you. Let me teach you, because I am humble and gentle, and you will find rest for your souls.', 'NLT'),
(44, 11, 30, 'For my yoke fits perfectly, and the burden I give you is light."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 1, 'At about that time Jesus was walking through some grainfields on the Sabbath. His disciples were hungry, so they began breaking off heads of wheat and eating the grain.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 2, 'Some Pharisees saw them do it and protested, "Your disciples shouldn''t be doing that! It''s against the law to work by harvesting grain on the Sabbath."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 3, 'But Jesus said to them, "Haven''t you ever read in the Scriptures what King David did when he and his companions were hungry?', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 4, 'He went into the house of God, and they ate the special bread reserved for the priests alone. That was breaking the law, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 5, 'And haven''t you ever read in the law of Moses that the priests on duty in the Temple may work on the Sabbath?', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 6, 'I tell you, there is one here who is even greater than the Temple!', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 7, 'But you would not have condemned those who aren''t guilty if you knew the meaning of this Scripture: ''I want you to be merciful; I don''t want your sacrifices.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 8, 'For I, the Son of Man, am master even of the Sabbath."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 9, 'Then he went over to the synagogue,', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 10, 'where he noticed a man with a deformed hand. The Pharisees asked Jesus, "Is it legal to work by healing on the Sabbath day?" (They were, of course, hoping he would say yes, so they could bring charges against him.)', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 11, 'And he answered, "If you had one sheep, and it fell into a well on the Sabbath, wouldn''t you get to work and pull it out? Of course you would.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 12, 'And how much more valuable is a person than a sheep! Yes, it is right to do good on the Sabbath."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 13, 'Then he said to the man, "Reach out your hand." The man reached out his hand, and it became normal, just like the other one.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 14, 'Then the Pharisees called a meeting and discussed plans for killing Jesus.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 15, 'But Jesus knew what they were planning. He left that area, and many people followed him. He healed all the sick among them,', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 16, 'but he warned them not to say who he was.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 17, 'This fulfilled the prophecy of Isaiah concerning him:', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 18, '"Look at my Servant, whom I have chosen. He is my Beloved, and I am very pleased with him. I will put my Spirit upon him, and he will proclaim justice to the nations.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 19, 'He will not fight or shout; he will not raise his voice in public.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 20, 'He will not crush those who are weak, or quench the smallest hope, until he brings full justice with his final victory.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 21, 'And his name will be the hope of all the world."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 22, 'Then a demon-possessed man, who was both blind and unable to talk, was brought to Jesus. He healed the man so that he could both speak and see.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 23, 'The crowd was amazed. "Could it be that Jesus is the Son of David, the Messiah?" they wondered out loud.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 24, 'But when the Pharisees heard about the miracle, they said, "No wonder he can cast out demons. He gets his power from Satan, the prince of demons."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 25, 'Jesus knew their thoughts and replied, "Any kingdom at war with itself is doomed. A city or home divided against itself is doomed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 26, 'And if Satan is casting out Satan, he is fighting against himself. His own kingdom will not survive.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 27, 'And if I am empowered by the prince of demons, what about your own followers? They cast out demons, too, so they will judge you for what you have said.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 28, 'But if I am casting out demons by the Spirit of God, then the Kingdom of God has arrived among you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 29, 'Let me illustrate this. You can''t enter a strong man''s house and rob him without first tying him up. Only then can his house be robbed!', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 30, 'Anyone who isn''t helping me opposes me, and anyone who isn''t working with me is actually working against me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 31, '"Every sin or blasphemy can be forgiven--except blasphemy against the Holy Spirit, which can never be forgiven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 32, 'Anyone who blasphemes against me, the Son of Man, can be forgiven, but blasphemy against the Holy Spirit will never be forgiven, either in this world or in the world to come.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 33, '"A tree is identified by its fruit. Make a tree good, and its fruit will be good. Make a tree bad, and its fruit will be bad.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 34, 'You brood of snakes! How could evil men like you speak what is good and right? For whatever is in your heart determines what you say.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 35, 'A good person produces good words from a good heart, and an evil person produces evil words from an evil heart.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 36, 'And I tell you this, that you must give an account on judgment day of every idle word you speak.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 37, 'The words you say now reflect your fate then; either you will be justified by them or you will be condemned."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 38, 'One day some teachers of religious law and Pharisees came to Jesus and said, "Teacher, we want you to show us a miraculous sign to prove that you are from God."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 39, 'But Jesus replied, "Only an evil, faithless generation would ask for a miraculous sign; but the only sign I will give them is the sign of the prophet Jonah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 40, 'For as Jonah was in the belly of the great fish for three days and three nights, so I, the Son of Man, will be in the heart of the earth for three days and three nights.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 41, 'The people of Nineveh will rise up against this generation on judgment day and condemn it, because they repented at the preaching of Jonah. And now someone greater than Jonah is here--and you refuse to repent.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 42, 'The queen of Sheba will also rise up against this generation on judgment day and condemn it, because she came from a distant land to hear the wisdom of Solomon. And now someone greater than Solomon is here--and you refuse to listen to him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 43, '"When an evil spirit leaves a person, it goes into the desert, seeking rest but finding none.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 44, 'Then it says, ''I will return to the person I came from.'' So it returns and finds its former home empty, swept, and clean.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 45, 'Then the spirit finds seven other spirits more evil than itself, and they all enter the person and live there. And so that person is worse off than before. That will be the experience of this evil generation."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 46, 'As Jesus was speaking to the crowd, his mother and brothers were outside, wanting to talk with him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 47, 'Someone told Jesus, "Your mother and your brothers are outside, and they want to speak to you."', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 48, 'Jesus asked, "Who is my mother? Who are my brothers?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 49, 'Then he pointed to his disciples and said, "These are my mother and brothers.', 'NLT'),
(44, 12, 50, 'Anyone who does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 1, 'Later that same day, Jesus left the house and went down to the shore,', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 2, 'where an immense crowd soon gathered. He got into a boat, where he sat and taught as the people listened on the shore.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 3, 'He told many stories such as this one: "A farmer went out to plant some seed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 4, 'As he scattered it across his field, some seeds fell on a footpath, and the birds came and ate them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 5, 'Other seeds fell on shallow soil with underlying rock. The plants sprang up quickly,', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 6, 'but they soon wilted beneath the hot sun and died because the roots had no nourishment in the shallow soil.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 7, 'Other seeds fell among thorns that shot up and choked out the tender blades.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 8, 'But some seeds fell on fertile soil and produced a crop that was thirty, sixty, and even a hundred times as much as had been planted.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 9, 'Anyone who is willing to hear should listen and understand!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 10, 'His disciples came and asked him, "Why do you always tell stories when you talk to the people?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 11, 'Then he explained to them, "You have been permitted to understand the secrets of the Kingdom of Heaven, but others have not.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 12, 'To those who are open to my teaching, more understanding will be given, and they will have an abundance of knowledge. But to those who are not listening, even what they have will be taken away from them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 13, 'That is why I tell these stories, because people see what I do, but they don''t really see. They hear what I say, but they don''t really hear, and they don''t understand.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 14, 'This fulfills the prophecy of Isaiah, which says: ''You will hear my words, but you will not understand; you will see what I do, but you will not perceive its meaning.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 15, 'For the hearts of these people are hardened, and their ears cannot hear, and they have closed their eyes--so their eyes cannot see, and their ears cannot hear, and their hearts cannot understand, and they cannot turn to me and let me heal them.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 16, '"But blessed are your eyes, because they see; and your ears, because they hear.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 17, 'I assure you, many prophets and godly people have longed to see and hear what you have seen and heard, but they could not.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 18, '"Now here is the explanation of the story I told about the farmer sowing grain:', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 19, 'The seed that fell on the hard path represents those who hear the Good News about the Kingdom and don''t understand it. Then the evil one comes and snatches the seed away from their hearts.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 20, 'The rocky soil represents those who hear the message and receive it with joy.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 21, 'But like young plants in such soil, their roots don''t go very deep. At first they get along fine, but they wilt as soon as they have problems or are persecuted because they believe the word.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 22, 'The thorny ground represents those who hear and accept the Good News, but all too quickly the message is crowded out by the cares of this life and the lure of wealth, so no crop is produced.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 23, 'The good soil represents the hearts of those who truly accept God''s message and produce a huge harvest--thirty, sixty, or even a hundred times as much as had been planted."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 24, 'Here is another story Jesus told: "The Kingdom of Heaven is like a farmer who planted good seed in his field.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 25, 'But that night as everyone slept, his enemy came and planted weeds among the wheat.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 26, 'When the crop began to grow and produce grain, the weeds also grew.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 27, 'The farmer''s servants came and told him, ''Sir, the field where you planted that good seed is full of weeds!''', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 28, '"''An enemy has done it!'' the farmer exclaimed. "''Shall we pull out the weeds?'' they asked.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 29, '"He replied, ''No, you''ll hurt the wheat if you do.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 30, 'Let both grow together until the harvest. Then I will tell the harvesters to sort out the weeds and burn them and to put the wheat in the barn.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 31, 'Here is another illustration Jesus used: "The Kingdom of Heaven is like a mustard seed planted in a field.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 32, 'It is the smallest of all seeds, but it becomes the largest of garden plants and grows into a tree where birds can come and find shelter in its branches."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 33, 'Jesus also used this illustration: "The Kingdom of Heaven is like yeast used by a woman making bread. Even though she used a large amount of flour, the yeast permeated every part of the dough."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 34, 'Jesus always used stories and illustrations like these when speaking to the crowds. In fact, he never spoke to them without using such parables.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 35, 'This fulfilled the prophecy that said, "I will speak to you in parables. I will explain mysteries hidden since the creation of the world."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 36, 'Then, leaving the crowds outside, Jesus went into the house. His disciples said, "Please explain the story of the weeds in the field."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 37, '"All right," he said. "I, the Son of Man, am the farmer who plants the good seed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 38, 'The field is the world, and the good seed represents the people of the Kingdom. The weeds are the people who belong to the evil one.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 39, 'The enemy who planted the weeds among the wheat is the Devil. The harvest is the end of the world, and the harvesters are the angels.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 40, '"Just as the weeds are separated out and burned, so it will be at the end of the world.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 41, 'I, the Son of Man, will send my angels, and they will remove from my Kingdom everything that causes sin and all who do evil,', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 42, 'and they will throw them into the furnace and burn them. There will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 43, 'Then the godly will shine like the sun in their Father''s Kingdom. Anyone who is willing to hear should listen and understand!', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 44, '"The Kingdom of Heaven is like a treasure that a man discovered hidden in a field. In his excitement, he hid it again and sold everything he owned to get enough money to buy the field--and to get the treasure, too!', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 45, '"Again, the Kingdom of Heaven is like a pearl merchant on the lookout for choice pearls.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 46, 'When he discovered a pearl of great value, he sold everything he owned and bought it!', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 47, '"Again, the Kingdom of Heaven is like a fishing net that is thrown into the water and gathers fish of every kind.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 48, 'When the net is full, they drag it up onto the shore, sit down, sort the good fish into crates, and throw the bad ones away.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 49, 'That is the way it will be at the end of the world. The angels will come and separate the wicked people from the godly,', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 50, 'throwing the wicked into the fire. There will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 51, 'Do you understand?Yes," they said, "we do."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 52, 'Then he added, "Every teacher of religious law who has become a disciple in the Kingdom of Heaven is like a person who brings out of the storehouse the new teachings as well as the old."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 53, 'When Jesus had finished telling these stories, he left that part of the country.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 54, 'He returned to Nazareth, his hometown. When he taught there in the synagogue, everyone was astonished and said, "Where does he get his wisdom and his miracles?', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 55, 'He''s just a carpenter''s son, and we know Mary, his mother, and his brothers--James, Joseph, Simon, and Judas.', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 56, 'All his sisters live right here among us. What makes him so great?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 57, 'And they were deeply offended and refused to believe in him. Then Jesus told them, "A prophet is honored everywhere except in his own hometown and among his own family."', 'NLT'),
(44, 13, 58, 'And so he did only a few miracles there because of their unbelief.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 1, 'When Herod Antipas heard about Jesus,', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 2, 'he said to his advisers, "This must be John the Baptist come back to life again! That is why he can do such miracles."', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 3, 'For Herod had arrested and imprisoned John as a favor to his wife Herodias (the former wife of Herod''s brother Philip).', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 4, 'John kept telling Herod, "It is illegal for you to marry her."', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 5, 'Herod would have executed John, but he was afraid of a riot, because all the people believed John was a prophet.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 6, 'But at a birthday party for Herod, Herodias''s daughter performed a dance that greatly pleased him,', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 7, 'so he promised with an oath to give her anything she wanted.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 8, 'At her mother''s urging, the girl asked, "I want the head of John the Baptist on a tray!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 9, 'The king was sorry, but because of his oath and because he didn''t want to back down in front of his guests, he issued the necessary orders.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 10, 'So John was beheaded in the prison,', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 11, 'and his head was brought on a tray and given to the girl, who took it to her mother.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 12, 'John''s disciples came for his body and buried it. Then they told Jesus what had happened.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 13, 'As soon as Jesus heard the news, he went off by himself in a boat to a remote area to be alone. But the crowds heard where he was headed and followed by land from many villages.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 14, 'A vast crowd was there as he stepped from the boat, and he had compassion on them and healed their sick.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 15, 'That evening the disciples came to him and said, "This is a desolate place, and it is getting late. Send the crowds away so they can go to the villages and buy food for themselves."', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 16, 'But Jesus replied, "That isn''t necessary--you feed them."', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 17, '"Impossible!" they exclaimed. "We have only five loaves of bread and two fish!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 18, '"Bring them here," he said.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 19, 'Then he told the people to sit down on the grass. And he took the five loaves and two fish, looked up toward heaven, and asked God''s blessing on the food. Breaking the loaves into pieces, he gave some of the bread and fish to each disciple, and the disciples gave them to the people.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 20, 'They all ate as much as they wanted, and they picked up twelve baskets of leftovers.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 21, 'About five thousand men had eaten from those five loaves, in addition to all the women and children!', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 22, 'Immediately after this, Jesus made his disciples get back into the boat and cross to the other side of the lake while he sent the people home.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 23, 'Afterward he went up into the hills by himself to pray. Night fell while he was there alone.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 24, 'Meanwhile, the disciples were in trouble far away from land, for a strong wind had risen, and they were fighting heavy waves.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 25, 'About three o''clock in the morning Jesus came to them, walking on the water.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 26, 'When the disciples saw him, they screamed in terror, thinking he was a ghost.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 27, 'But Jesus spoke to them at once. "It''s all right," he said. "I am here! Don''t be afraid."', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 28, 'Then Peter called to him, "Lord, if it''s really you, tell me to come to you by walking on water."', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 29, '"All right, come," Jesus said. So Peter went over the side of the boat and walked on the water toward Jesus.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 30, 'But when he looked around at the high waves, he was terrified and began to sink. "Save me, Lord!" he shouted.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 31, 'Instantly Jesus reached out his hand and grabbed him. "You don''t have much faith," Jesus said. "Why did you doubt me?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 32, 'And when they climbed back into the boat, the wind stopped.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 33, 'Then the disciples worshiped him. "You really are the Son of God!" they exclaimed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 34, 'After they had crossed the lake, they landed at Gennesaret.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 35, 'The news of their arrival spread quickly throughout the whole surrounding area, and soon people were bringing all their sick to be healed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 14, 36, 'The sick begged him to let them touch even the fringe of his robe, and all who touched it were healed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 1, 'Some Pharisees and teachers of religious law now arrived from Jerusalem to interview Jesus.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 2, '"Why do your disciples disobey our age-old traditions?" they demanded. "They ignore our tradition of ceremonial hand washing before they eat."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 3, 'Jesus replied, "And why do you, by your traditions, violate the direct commandments of God?', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 4, 'For instance, God says, ''Honor your father and mother,'' and ''Anyone who speaks evil of father or mother must be put to death.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 5, 'But you say, ''You don''t need to honor your parents by caring for their needs if you give the money to God instead.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 6, 'And so, by your own tradition, you nullify the direct commandment of God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 7, 'You hypocrites! Isaiah was prophesying about you when he said,', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 8, '''These people honor me with their lips, but their hearts are far away.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 9, 'Their worship is a farce, for they replace God''s commands with their own man-made teachings.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 10, 'Then Jesus called to the crowds and said, "Listen to what I say and try to understand.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 11, 'You are not defiled by what you eat; you are defiled by what you say and do. "', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 12, 'Then the disciples came to him and asked, "Do you realize you offended the Pharisees by what you just said?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 13, 'Jesus replied, "Every plant not planted by my heavenly Father will be rooted up,', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 14, 'so ignore them. They are blind guides leading the blind, and if one blind person guides another, they will both fall into a ditch."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 15, 'Then Peter asked Jesus, "Explain what you meant when you said people aren''t defiled by what they eat."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 16, '"Don''t you understand?" Jesus asked him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 17, '"Anything you eat passes through the stomach and then goes out of the body.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 18, 'But evil words come from an evil heart and defile the person who says them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 19, 'For from the heart come evil thoughts, murder, adultery, all other sexual immorality, theft, lying, and slander.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 20, 'These are what defile you. Eating with unwashed hands could never defile you and make you unacceptable to God!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 21, 'Jesus then left Galilee and went north to the region of Tyre and Sidon.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 22, 'A Gentile woman who lived there came to him, pleading, "Have mercy on me, O Lord, Son of David! For my daughter has a demon in her, and it is severely tormenting her."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 23, 'But Jesus gave her no reply--not even a word. Then his disciples urged him to send her away. "Tell her to leave," they said. "She is bothering us with all her begging."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 24, 'Then he said to the woman, "I was sent only to help the people of Israel--God''s lost sheep--not the Gentiles."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 25, 'But she came and worshiped him and pleaded again, "Lord, help me!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 26, '"It isn''t right to take food from the children and throw it to the dogs," he said.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 27, '"Yes, Lord," she replied, "but even dogs are permitted to eat crumbs that fall beneath their master''s table."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 28, '"Woman," Jesus said to her, "your faith is great. Your request is granted." And her daughter was instantly healed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 29, 'Jesus returned to the Sea of Galilee and climbed a hill and sat down.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 30, 'A vast crowd brought him the lame, blind, crippled, mute, and many others with physical difficulties, and they laid them before Jesus. And he healed them all.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 31, 'The crowd was amazed! Those who hadn''t been able to speak were talking, the crippled were made well, the lame were walking around, and those who had been blind could see again! And they praised the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 32, 'Then Jesus called his disciples to him and said, "I feel sorry for these people. They have been here with me for three days, and they have nothing left to eat. I don''t want to send them away hungry, or they will faint along the road."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 33, 'The disciples replied, "And where would we get enough food out here in the wilderness for all of them to eat?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 34, 'Jesus asked, "How many loaves of bread do you have?" They replied, "Seven, and a few small fish."', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 35, 'So Jesus told all the people to sit down on the ground.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 36, 'Then he took the seven loaves and the fish, thanked God for them, broke them into pieces, and gave them to the disciples, who distributed the food to the crowd.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 37, 'They all ate until they were full, and when the scraps were picked up, there were seven large baskets of food left over!', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 38, 'There were four thousand men who were fed that day, in addition to all the women and children.', 'NLT'),
(44, 15, 39, 'Then Jesus sent the people home, and he got into a boat and crossed over to the region of Magadan.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 1, 'One day the Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus'' claims by asking him to show them a miraculous sign from heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 2, 'He replied, "You know the saying, ''Red sky at night means fair weather tomorrow,', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 3, 'red sky in the morning means foul weather all day.'' You are good at reading the weather signs in the sky, but you can''t read the obvious signs of the times!', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 4, 'Only an evil, faithless generation would ask for a miraculous sign, but the only sign I will give them is the sign of the prophet Jonah." Then Jesus left them and went away.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 5, 'Later, after they crossed to the other side of the lake, the disciples discovered they had forgotten to bring any food.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 6, '"Watch out!" Jesus warned them. "Beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees."', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 7, 'They decided he was saying this because they hadn''t brought any bread.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 8, 'Jesus knew what they were thinking, so he said, "You have so little faith! Why are you worried about having no food?', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 9, 'Won''t you ever understand? Don''t you remember the five thousand I fed with five loaves, and the baskets of food that were left over?', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 10, 'Don''t you remember the four thousand I fed with seven loaves, with baskets of food left over?', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 11, 'How could you even think I was talking about food? So again I say, ''Beware of the yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 12, 'Then at last they understood that he wasn''t speaking about yeast or bread but about the false teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 13, 'When Jesus came to the region of Caesarea Philippi, he asked his disciples, "Who do people say that the Son of Man is?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 14, '"Well," they replied, "some say John the Baptist, some say Elijah, and others say Jeremiah or one of the other prophets."', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 15, 'Then he asked them, "Who do you say I am?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 16, 'Simon Peter answered, "You are the Messiah, the Son of the living God."', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 17, 'Jesus replied, "You are blessed, Simon son of John, because my Father in heaven has revealed this to you. You did not learn this from any human being.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 18, 'Now I say to you that you are Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church, and all the powers of hell will not conquer it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 19, 'And I will give you the keys of the Kingdom of Heaven. Whatever you lock on earth will be locked in heaven, and whatever you open on earth will be opened in heaven."', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 20, 'Then he sternly warned them not to tell anyone that he was the Messiah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 21, 'From then on Jesus began to tell his disciples plainly that he had to go to Jerusalem, and he told them what would happen to him there. He would suffer at the hands of the leaders and the leading priests and the teachers of religious law. He would be killed, and he would be raised on the third day.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 22, 'But Peter took him aside and corrected him. "Heaven forbid, Lord," he said. "This will never happen to you!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 23, 'Jesus turned to Peter and said, "Get away from me, Satan! You are a dangerous trap to me. You are seeing things merely from a human point of view, and not from God''s."', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 24, 'Then Jesus said to the disciples, "If any of you wants to be my follower, you must put aside your selfish ambition, shoulder your cross, and follow me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 25, 'If you try to keep your life for yourself, you will lose it. But if you give up your life for me, you will find true life.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 26, 'And how do you benefit if you gain the whole world but lose your own soul in the process? Is anything worth more than your soul?', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 27, 'For I, the Son of Man, will come in the glory of my Father with his angels and will judge all people according to their deeds.', 'NLT'),
(44, 16, 28, 'And I assure you that some of you standing here right now will not die before you see me, the Son of Man, coming in my Kingdom."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 1, 'Six days later Jesus took Peter and the two brothers, James and John, and led them up a high mountain.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 2, 'As the men watched, Jesus'' appearance changed so that his face shone like the sun, and his clothing became dazzling white.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 3, 'Suddenly, Moses and Elijah appeared and began talking with Jesus.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 4, 'Peter blurted out, "Lord, this is wonderful! If you want me to, I''ll make three shrines, one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 5, 'But even as he said it, a bright cloud came over them, and a voice from the cloud said, "This is my beloved Son, and I am fully pleased with him. Listen to him."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 6, 'The disciples were terrified and fell face down on the ground.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 7, 'Jesus came over and touched them. "Get up," he said, "don''t be afraid."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 8, 'And when they looked, they saw only Jesus with them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 9, 'As they descended the mountain, Jesus commanded them, "Don''t tell anyone what you have seen until I, the Son of Man, have been raised from the dead."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 10, 'His disciples asked, "Why do the teachers of religious law insist that Elijah must return before the Messiah comes?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 11, 'Jesus replied, "Elijah is indeed coming first to set everything in order.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 12, 'But I tell you, he has already come, but he wasn''t recognized, and he was badly mistreated. And soon the Son of Man will also suffer at their hands."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 13, 'Then the disciples realized he had been speaking of John the Baptist.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 14, 'When they arrived at the foot of the mountain, a huge crowd was waiting for them. A man came and knelt before Jesus and said,', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 15, '"Lord, have mercy on my son, because he has seizures and suffers terribly. He often falls into the fire or into the water.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 16, 'So I brought him to your disciples, but they couldn''t heal him."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 17, 'Jesus replied, "You stubborn, faithless people! How long must I be with you until you believe? How long must I put up with you? Bring the boy to me."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 18, 'Then Jesus rebuked the demon in the boy, and it left him. From that moment the boy was well.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 19, 'Afterward the disciples asked Jesus privately, "Why couldn''t we cast out that demon?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 20, '"You didn''t have enough faith," Jesus told them. "I assure you, even if you had faith as small as a mustard seed you could say to this mountain, ''Move from here to there,'' and it would move. Nothing would be impossible."', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 21, 'See Footnote', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 22, 'One day after they had returned to Galilee, Jesus told them, "The Son of Man is going to be betrayed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 23, 'He will be killed, but three days later he will be raised from the dead." And the disciples'' hearts were filled with grief.', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 24, 'On their arrival in Capernaum, the tax collectors for the Temple tax came to Peter and asked him, "Doesn''t your teacher pay the Temple tax?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 25, '"Of course he does," Peter replied. Then he went into the house to talk to Jesus about it. But before he had a chance to speak, Jesus asked him, "What do you think, Peter? Do kings tax their own people or the foreigners they have conquered?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 26, '"They tax the foreigners," Peter replied. "Well, then," Jesus said, "the citizens are free!', 'NLT'),
(44, 17, 27, 'However, we don''t want to offend them, so go down to the lake and throw in a line. Open the mouth of the first fish you catch, and you will find a coin. Take the coin and pay the tax for both of us."', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 1, 'About that time the disciples came to Jesus and asked, "Which of us is greatest in the Kingdom of Heaven?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 2, 'Jesus called a small child over to him and put the child among them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 3, 'Then he said, "I assure you, unless you turn from your sins and become as little children, you will never get into the Kingdom of Heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 4, 'Therefore, anyone who becomes as humble as this little child is the greatest in the Kingdom of Heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 5, 'And anyone who welcomes a little child like this on my behalf is welcoming me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 6, 'But if anyone causes one of these little ones who trusts in me to lose faith, it would be better for that person to be thrown into the sea with a large millstone tied around the neck.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 7, '"How terrible it will be for anyone who causes others to sin. Temptation to do wrong is inevitable, but how terrible it will be for the person who does the tempting.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 8, 'So if your hand or foot causes you to sin, cut it off and throw it away. It is better to enter heaven crippled or lame than to be thrown into the unquenchable fire with both of your hands and feet.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 9, 'And if your eye causes you to sin, gouge it out and throw it away. It is better to enter heaven half blind than to have two eyes and be thrown into hell.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 10, '"Beware that you don''t despise a single one of these little ones. For I tell you that in heaven their angels are always in the presence of my heavenly Father.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 11, 'See Footnote', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 12, '"If a shepherd has one hundred sheep, and one wanders away and is lost, what will he do? Won''t he leave the ninety-nine others and go out into the hills to search for the lost one?', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 13, 'And if he finds it, he will surely rejoice over it more than over the ninety-nine that didn''t wander away!', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 14, 'In the same way, it is not my heavenly Father''s will that even one of these little ones should perish.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 15, '"If another believer sins against you, go privately and point out the fault. If the other person listens and confesses it, you have won that person back.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 16, 'But if you are unsuccessful, take one or two others with you and go back again, so that everything you say may be confirmed by two or three witnesses.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 17, 'If that person still refuses to listen, take your case to the church. If the church decides you are right, but the other person won''t accept it, treat that person as a pagan or a corrupt tax collector.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 18, 'I tell you this: Whatever you prohibit on earth is prohibited in heaven, and whatever you allow on earth is allowed in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 19, '"I also tell you this: If two of you agree down here on earth concerning anything you ask, my Father in heaven will do it for you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 20, 'For where two or three gather together because they are mine, I am there among them."', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 21, 'Then Peter came to him and asked, "Lord, how often should I forgive someone who sins against me? Seven times?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 22, '"No!" Jesus replied, "seventy times seven!', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 23, '"For this reason, the Kingdom of Heaven can be compared to a king who decided to bring his accounts up to date with servants who had borrowed money from him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 24, 'In the process, one of his debtors was brought in who owed him millions of dollars.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 25, 'He couldn''t pay, so the king ordered that he, his wife, his children, and everything he had be sold to pay the debt.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 26, 'But the man fell down before the king and begged him, ''Oh, sir, be patient with me, and I will pay it all.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 27, 'Then the king was filled with pity for him, and he released him and forgave his debt.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 28, '"But when the man left the king, he went to a fellow servant who owed him a few thousand dollars. He grabbed him by the throat and demanded instant payment.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 29, 'His fellow servant fell down before him and begged for a little more time. ''Be patient and I will pay it,'' he pleaded.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 30, 'But his creditor wouldn''t wait. He had the man arrested and jailed until the debt could be paid in full.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 31, '"When some of the other servants saw this, they were very upset. They went to the king and told him what had happened.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 32, 'Then the king called in the man he had forgiven and said, ''You evil servant! I forgave you that tremendous debt because you pleaded with me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 33, 'Shouldn''t you have mercy on your fellow servant, just as I had mercy on you?''', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 34, 'Then the angry king sent the man to prison until he had paid every penny.', 'NLT'),
(44, 18, 35, '"That''s what my heavenly Father will do to you if you refuse to forgive your brothers and sisters in your heart."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 1, 'After Jesus had finished saying these things, he left Galilee and went southward to the region of Judea and into the area east of the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 2, 'Vast crowds followed him there, and he healed their sick.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 3, 'Some Pharisees came and tried to trap him with this question: "Should a man be allowed to divorce his wife for any reason?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 4, '"Haven''t you read the Scriptures?" Jesus replied. "They record that from the beginning ''God made them male and female.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 5, 'And he said, ''This explains why a man leaves his father and mother and is joined to his wife, and the two are united into one.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 6, 'Since they are no longer two but one, let no one separate them, for God has joined them together."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 7, '"Then why did Moses say a man could merely write an official letter of divorce and send her away?" they asked.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 8, 'Jesus replied, "Moses permitted divorce as a concession to your hard-hearted wickedness, but it was not what God had originally intended.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 9, 'And I tell you this, a man who divorces his wife and marries another commits adultery--unless his wife has been unfaithful. "', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 10, 'Jesus'' disciples then said to him, "Then it is better not to marry!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 11, '"Not everyone can accept this statement," Jesus said. "Only those whom God helps.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 12, 'Some are born as eunuchs, some have been made that way by others, and some choose not to marry for the sake of the Kingdom of Heaven. Let anyone who can, accept this statement."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 13, 'Some children were brought to Jesus so he could lay his hands on them and pray for them. The disciples told them not to bother him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 14, 'But Jesus said, "Let the children come to me. Don''t stop them! For the Kingdom of Heaven belongs to such as these."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 15, 'And he put his hands on their heads and blessed them before he left.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 16, 'Someone came to Jesus with this question: "Teacher, what good things must I do to have eternal life?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 17, '"Why ask me about what is good?" Jesus replied. "Only God is good. But to answer your question, you can receive eternal life if you keep the commandments."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 18, '"Which ones?" the man asked. And Jesus replied: "''Do not murder. Do not commit adultery. Do not steal. Do not testify falsely.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 19, 'Honor your father and mother. Love your neighbor as yourself.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 20, '"I''ve obeyed all these commandments," the young man replied. "What else must I do?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 21, 'Jesus told him, "If you want to be perfect, go and sell all you have and give the money to the poor, and you will have treasure in heaven. Then come, follow me."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 22, 'But when the young man heard this, he went sadly away because he had many possessions.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 23, 'Then Jesus said to his disciples, "I tell you the truth, it is very hard for a rich person to get into the Kingdom of Heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 24, 'I say it again--it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a rich person to enter the Kingdom of God!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 25, 'The disciples were astounded. "Then who in the world can be saved?" they asked.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 26, 'Jesus looked at them intently and said, "Humanly speaking, it is impossible. But with God everything is possible."', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 27, 'Then Peter said to him, "We''ve given up everything to follow you. What will we get out of it?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 28, 'And Jesus replied, "I assure you that when I, the Son of Man, sit upon my glorious throne in the Kingdom, you who have been my followers will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 29, 'And everyone who has given up houses or brothers or sisters or father or mother or children or property, for my sake, will receive a hundred times as much in return and will have eternal life.', 'NLT'),
(44, 19, 30, 'But many who seem to be important now will be the least important then, and those who are considered least here will be the greatest then.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 1, '"For the Kingdom of Heaven is like the owner of an estate who went out early one morning to hire workers for his vineyard.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 2, 'He agreed to pay the normal daily wage and sent them out to work.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 3, '"At nine o''clock in the morning he was passing through the marketplace and saw some people standing around doing nothing.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 4, 'So he hired them, telling them he would pay them whatever was right at the end of the day.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 5, 'At noon and again around three o''clock he did the same thing.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 6, 'At five o''clock that evening he was in town again and saw some more people standing around. He asked them, ''Why haven''t you been working today?''', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 7, '"They replied, ''Because no one hired us.''"The owner of the estate told them, ''Then go on out and join the others in my vineyard.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 8, '"That evening he told the foreman to call the workers in and pay them, beginning with the last workers first.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 9, 'When those hired at five o''clock were paid, each received a full day''s wage.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 10, 'When those hired earlier came to get their pay, they assumed they would receive more. But they, too, were paid a day''s wage.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 11, 'When they received their pay, they protested,', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 12, '''Those people worked only one hour, and yet you''ve paid them just as much as you paid us who worked all day in the scorching heat.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 13, '"He answered one of them, ''Friend, I haven''t been unfair! Didn''t you agree to work all day for the usual wage?', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 14, 'Take it and go. I wanted to pay this last worker the same as you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 15, 'Is it against the law for me to do what I want with my money? Should you be angry because I am kind?''', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 16, '"And so it is, that many who are first now will be last then; and those who are last now will be first then."', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 17, 'As Jesus was on the way to Jerusalem, he took the twelve disciples aside privately and told them what was going to happen to him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 18, '"When we get to Jerusalem," he said, "the Son of Man will be betrayed to the leading priests and the teachers of religious law. They will sentence him to die.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 19, 'Then they will hand him over to the Romans to be mocked, whipped, and crucified. But on the third day he will be raised from the dead."', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 20, 'Then the mother of James and John, the sons of Zebedee, came to Jesus with her sons. She knelt respectfully to ask a favor.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 21, '"What is your request?" he asked. She replied, "In your Kingdom, will you let my two sons sit in places of honor next to you, one at your right and the other at your left?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 22, 'But Jesus told them, "You don''t know what you are asking! Are you able to drink from the bitter cup of sorrow I am about to drink?Oh yes," they replied, "we are able!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 23, '"You will indeed drink from it," he told them. "But I have no right to say who will sit on the thrones next to mine. My Father has prepared those places for the ones he has chosen."', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 24, 'When the ten other disciples heard what James and John had asked, they were indignant.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 25, 'But Jesus called them together and said, "You know that in this world kings are tyrants, and officials lord it over the people beneath them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 26, 'But among you it should be quite different. Whoever wants to be a leader among you must be your servant,', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 27, 'and whoever wants to be first must become your slave.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 28, 'For even I, the Son of Man, came here not to be served but to serve others, and to give my life as a ransom for many."', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 29, 'As Jesus and the disciples left the city of Jericho, a huge crowd followed behind.', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 30, 'Two blind men were sitting beside the road. When they heard that Jesus was coming that way, they began shouting, "Lord, Son of David, have mercy on us!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 31, 'The crowd told them to be quiet, but they only shouted louder, "Lord, Son of David, have mercy on us!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 32, 'Jesus stopped in the road and called, "What do you want me to do for you?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 33, '"Lord," they said, "we want to see!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 20, 34, 'Jesus felt sorry for them and touched their eyes. Instantly they could see! Then they followed him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 1, 'As Jesus and the disciples approached Jerusalem, they came to the town of Bethphage on the Mount of Olives. Jesus sent two of them on ahead.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 2, '"Go into the village over there," he said, "and you will see a donkey tied there, with its colt beside it. Untie them and bring them here.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 3, 'If anyone asks what you are doing, just say, ''The Lord needs them,'' and he will immediately send them."', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 4, 'This was done to fulfill the prophecy,', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 5, '"Tell the people of Israel, ''Look, your King is coming to you. He is humble, riding on a donkey--even on a donkey''s colt.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 6, 'The two disciples did as Jesus said.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 7, 'They brought the animals to him and threw their garments over the colt, and he sat on it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 8, 'Most of the crowd spread their coats on the road ahead of Jesus, and others cut branches from the trees and spread them on the road.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 9, 'He was in the center of the procession, and the crowds all around him were shouting, "Praise God for the Son of David! Bless the one who comes in the name of the Lord! Praise God in highest heaven!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 10, 'The entire city of Jerusalem was stirred as he entered. "Who is this?" they asked.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 11, 'And the crowds replied, "It''s Jesus, the prophet from Nazareth in Galilee."', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 12, 'Jesus entered the Temple and began to drive out the merchants and their customers. He knocked over the tables of the money changers and the stalls of those selling doves.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 13, 'He said, "The Scriptures declare, ''My Temple will be called a place of prayer,'' but you have turned it into a den of thieves!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 14, 'The blind and the lame came to him, and he healed them there in the Temple.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 15, 'The leading priests and the teachers of religious law saw these wonderful miracles and heard even the little children in the Temple shouting, "Praise God for the Son of David." But they were indignant', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 16, 'and asked Jesus, "Do you hear what these children are saying?Yes," Jesus replied. "Haven''t you ever read the Scriptures? For they say, ''You have taught children and infants to give you praise.''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 17, 'Then he returned to Bethany, where he stayed overnight.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 18, 'In the morning, as Jesus was returning to Jerusalem, he was hungry,', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 19, 'and he noticed a fig tree beside the road. He went over to see if there were any figs on it, but there were only leaves. Then he said to it, "May you never bear fruit again!" And immediately the fig tree withered up.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 20, 'The disciples were amazed when they saw this and asked, "How did the fig tree wither so quickly?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 21, 'Then Jesus told them, "I assure you, if you have faith and don''t doubt, you can do things like this and much more. You can even say to this mountain, ''May God lift you up and throw you into the sea,'' and it will happen.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 22, 'If you believe, you will receive whatever you ask for in prayer."', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 23, 'When Jesus returned to the Temple and began teaching, the leading priests and other leaders came up to him. They demanded, "By whose authority did you drive out the merchants from the Temple? Who gave you such authority?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 24, '"I''ll tell you who gave me the authority to do these things if you answer one question," Jesus replied.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 25, '"Did John''s baptism come from heaven or was it merely human?" They talked it over among themselves. "If we say it was from heaven, he will ask why we didn''t believe him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 26, 'But if we say it was merely human, we''ll be mobbed, because the people think he was a prophet."', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 27, 'So they finally replied, "We don''t know." And Jesus responded, "Then I won''t answer your question either.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 28, '"But what do you think about this? A man with two sons told the older boy, ''Son, go out and work in the vineyard today.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 29, 'The son answered, ''No, I won''t go,'' but later he changed his mind and went anyway.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 30, 'Then the father told the other son, ''You go,'' and he said, ''Yes, sir, I will.'' But he didn''t go.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 31, 'Which of the two was obeying his father?" They replied, "The first, of course." Then Jesus explained his meaning: "I assure you, corrupt tax collectors and prostitutes will get into the Kingdom of God before you do.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 32, 'For John the Baptist came and showed you the way to life, and you didn''t believe him, while tax collectors and prostitutes did. And even when you saw this happening, you refused to turn from your sins and believe him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 33, '"Now listen to this story. A certain landowner planted a vineyard, built a wall around it, dug a pit for pressing out the grape juice, and built a lookout tower. Then he leased the vineyard to tenant farmers and moved to another country.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 34, 'At the time of the grape harvest he sent his servants to collect his share of the crop.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 35, 'But the farmers grabbed his servants, beat one, killed one, and stoned another.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 36, 'So the landowner sent a larger group of his servants to collect for him, but the results were the same.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 37, '"Finally, the owner sent his son, thinking, ''Surely they will respect my son.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 38, '"But when the farmers saw his son coming, they said to one another, ''Here comes the heir to this estate. Come on, let''s kill him and get the estate for ourselves!''', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 39, 'So they grabbed him, took him out of the vineyard, and murdered him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 40, '"When the owner of the vineyard returns," Jesus asked, "what do you think he will do to those farmers?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 41, 'The religious leaders replied, "He will put the wicked men to a horrible death and lease the vineyard to others who will give him his share of the crop after each harvest."', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 42, 'Then Jesus asked them, "Didn''t you ever read this in the Scriptures? ''The stone rejected by the builders has now become the cornerstone. This is the Lord''s doing, and it is marvelous to see.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 43, 'What I mean is that the Kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a nation that will produce the proper fruit.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 44, 'Anyone who stumbles over that stone will be broken to pieces, and it will crush anyone on whom it falls. "', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 45, 'When the leading priests and Pharisees heard Jesus, they realized he was pointing at them--that they were the farmers in his story.', 'NLT'),
(44, 21, 46, 'They wanted to arrest him, but they were afraid to try because the crowds considered Jesus to be a prophet.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 1, 'Jesus told them several other stories to illustrate the Kingdom. He said,', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 2, '"The Kingdom of Heaven can be illustrated by the story of a king who prepared a great wedding feast for his son.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 3, 'Many guests were invited, and when the banquet was ready, he sent his servants to notify everyone that it was time to come. But they all refused!', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 4, 'So he sent other servants to tell them, ''The feast has been prepared, and choice meats have been cooked. Everything is ready. Hurry!''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 5, 'But the guests he had invited ignored them and went about their business, one to his farm, another to his store.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 6, 'Others seized his messengers and treated them shamefully, even killing some of them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 7, '"Then the king became furious. He sent out his army to destroy the murderers and burn their city.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 8, 'And he said to his servants, ''The wedding feast is ready, and the guests I invited aren''t worthy of the honor.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 9, 'Now go out to the street corners and invite everyone you see.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 10, '"So the servants brought in everyone they could find, good and bad alike, and the banquet hall was filled with guests.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 11, 'But when the king came in to meet the guests, he noticed a man who wasn''t wearing the proper clothes for a wedding.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 12, '''Friend,'' he asked, ''how is it that you are here without wedding clothes?'' And the man had no reply.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 13, 'Then the king said to his aides, ''Bind him hand and foot and throw him out into the outer darkness, where there is weeping and gnashing of teeth.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 14, 'For many are called, but few are chosen."', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 15, 'Then the Pharisees met together to think of a way to trap Jesus into saying something for which they could accuse him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 16, 'They decided to send some of their disciples, along with the supporters of Herod, to ask him this question: "Teacher, we know how honest you are. You teach about the way of God regardless of the consequences. You are impartial and don''t play favorites.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 17, 'Now tell us what you think about this: Is it right to pay taxes to the Roman government or not?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 18, 'But Jesus knew their evil motives. "You hypocrites!" he said. "Whom are you trying to fool with your trick questions?', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 19, 'Here, show me the Roman coin used for the tax." When they handed him the coin,', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 20, 'he asked, "Whose picture and title are stamped on it?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 21, '"Caesar''s," they replied. "Well, then," he said, "give to Caesar what belongs to him. But everything that belongs to God must be given to God."', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 22, 'His reply amazed them, and they went away.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 23, 'That same day some Sadducees stepped forward--a group of Jews who say there is no resurrection after death. They posed this question:', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 24, '"Teacher, Moses said, ''If a man dies without children, his brother should marry the widow and have a child who will be the brother''s heir.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 25, 'Well, there were seven brothers. The oldest married and then died without children, so the second brother married the widow.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 26, 'This brother also died without children, and the wife was married to the next brother, and so on until she had been the wife of each of them.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 27, 'And then she also died.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 28, 'So tell us, whose wife will she be in the resurrection? For she was the wife of all seven of them!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 29, 'Jesus replied, "Your problem is that you don''t know the Scriptures, and you don''t know the power of God.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 30, 'For when the dead rise, they won''t be married. They will be like the angels in heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 31, 'But now, as to whether there will be a resurrection of the dead--haven''t you ever read about this in the Scriptures? Long after Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob had died, God said,', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 32, '''I am the God of Abraham, the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob.'' So he is the God of the living, not the dead."', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 33, 'When the crowds heard him, they were impressed with his teaching.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 34, 'But when the Pharisees heard that he had silenced the Sadducees with his reply, they thought up a fresh question of their own to ask him.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 35, 'One of them, an expert in religious law, tried to trap him with this question:', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 36, '"Teacher, which is the most important commandment in the law of Moses?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 37, 'Jesus replied, "''You must love the Lord your God with all your heart, all your soul, and all your mind.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 38, 'This is the first and greatest commandment.', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 39, 'A second is equally important: ''Love your neighbor as yourself.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 40, 'All the other commandments and all the demands of the prophets are based on these two commandments."', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 41, 'Then, surrounded by the Pharisees, Jesus asked them a question:', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 42, '"What do you think about the Messiah? Whose son is he?" They replied, "He is the son of David."', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 43, 'Jesus responded, "Then why does David, speaking under the inspiration of the Holy Spirit, call him Lord? For David said,', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 44, '''The LORD said to my Lord, Sit in honor at my right hand until I humble your enemies beneath your feet.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 45, 'Since David called him Lord, how can he be his son at the same time?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 22, 46, 'No one could answer him. And after that, no one dared to ask him any more questions.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 1, 'Then Jesus said to the crowds and to his disciples,', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 2, '"The teachers of religious law and the Pharisees are the official interpreters of the Scriptures.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 3, 'So practice and obey whatever they say to you, but don''t follow their example. For they don''t practice what they teach.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 4, 'They crush you with impossible religious demands and never lift a finger to help ease the burden.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 5, '"Everything they do is for show. On their arms they wear extra wide prayer boxes with Scripture verses inside, and they wear extra long tassels on their robes.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 6, 'And how they love to sit at the head table at banquets and in the most prominent seats in the synagogue!', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 7, 'They enjoy the attention they get on the streets, and they enjoy being called ''Rabbi.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 8, 'Don''t ever let anyone call you ''Rabbi,'' for you have only one teacher, and all of you are on the same level as brothers and sisters.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 9, 'And don''t address anyone here on earth as ''Father,'' for only God in heaven is your spiritual Father.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 10, 'And don''t let anyone call you ''Master,'' for there is only one master, the Messiah.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 11, 'The greatest among you must be a servant.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 12, 'But those who exalt themselves will be humbled, and those who humble themselves will be exalted.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 13, '"How terrible it will be for you teachers of religious law and you Pharisees. Hypocrites! For you won''t let others enter the Kingdom of Heaven, and you won''t go in yourselves.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 14, 'See Footnote', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 15, 'Yes, how terrible it will be for you teachers of religious law and you Pharisees. For you cross land and sea to make one convert, and then you turn him into twice the son of hell as you yourselves are.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 16, '"Blind guides! How terrible it will be for you! For you say that it means nothing to swear ''by God''s Temple''--you can break that oath. But then you say that it is binding to swear ''by the gold in the Temple.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 17, 'Blind fools! Which is greater, the gold, or the Temple that makes the gold sacred?', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 18, 'And you say that to take an oath ''by the altar'' can be broken, but to swear ''by the gifts on the altar'' is binding!', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 19, 'How blind! For which is greater, the gift on the altar, or the altar that makes the gift sacred?', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 20, 'When you swear ''by the altar,'' you are swearing by it and by everything on it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 21, 'And when you swear ''by the Temple,'' you are swearing by it and by God, who lives in it.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 22, 'And when you swear ''by heaven,'' you are swearing by the throne of God and by God, who sits on the throne.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 23, '"How terrible it will be for you teachers of religious law and you Pharisees. Hypocrites! For you are careful to tithe even the tiniest part of your income, but you ignore the important things of the law--justice, mercy, and faith. You should tithe, yes, but you should not leave undone the more important things.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 24, 'Blind guides! You strain your water so you won''t accidentally swallow a gnat; then you swallow a camel!', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 25, '"How terrible it will be for you teachers of religious law and you Pharisees. Hypocrites! You are so careful to clean the outside of the cup and the dish, but inside you are filthy--full of greed and self-indulgence!', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 26, 'Blind Pharisees! First wash the inside of the cup, and then the outside will become clean, too.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 27, '"How terrible it will be for you teachers of religious law and you Pharisees. Hypocrites! You are like whitewashed tombs--beautiful on the outside but filled on the inside with dead people''s bones and all sorts of impurity.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 28, 'You try to look like upright people outwardly, but inside your hearts are filled with hypocrisy and lawlessness.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 29, '"How terrible it will be for you teachers of religious law and you Pharisees. Hypocrites! For you build tombs for the prophets your ancestors killed and decorate the graves of the godly people your ancestors destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 30, 'Then you say, ''We never would have joined them in killing the prophets.''', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 31, '"In saying that, you are accusing yourselves of being the descendants of those who murdered the prophets.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 32, 'Go ahead. Finish what they started.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 33, 'Snakes! Sons of vipers! How will you escape the judgment of hell?', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 34, 'I will send you prophets and wise men and teachers of religious law. You will kill some by crucifixion and whip others in your synagogues, chasing them from city to city.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 35, 'As a result, you will become guilty of murdering all the godly people from righteous Abel to Zechariah son of Barachiah, whom you murdered in the Temple between the altar and the sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 36, 'I assure you, all the accumulated judgment of the centuries will break upon the heads of this very generation.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 37, '"O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets and stones God''s messengers! How often I have wanted to gather your children together as a hen protects her chicks beneath her wings, but you wouldn''t let me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 38, 'And now look, your house is left to you, empty and desolate.', 'NLT'),
(44, 23, 39, 'For I tell you this, you will never see me again until you say, ''Bless the one who comes in the name of the Lord!''"', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 1, 'As Jesus was leaving the Temple grounds, his disciples pointed out to him the various Temple buildings.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 2, 'But he told them, "Do you see all these buildings? I assure you, they will be so completely demolished that not one stone will be left on top of another!"', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 3, 'Later, Jesus sat on the slopes of the Mount of Olives. His disciples came to him privately and asked, "When will all this take place? And will there be any sign ahead of time to signal your return and the end of the world?"', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 4, 'Jesus told them, "Don''t let anyone mislead you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 5, 'For many will come in my name, saying, ''I am the Messiah.'' They will lead many astray.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 6, 'And wars will break out near and far, but don''t panic. Yes, these things must come, but the end won''t follow immediately.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 7, 'The nations and kingdoms will proclaim war against each other, and there will be famines and earthquakes in many parts of the world.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 8, 'But all this will be only the beginning of the horrors to come.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 9, '"Then you will be arrested, persecuted, and killed. You will be hated all over the world because of your allegiance to me.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 10, 'And many will turn away from me and betray and hate each other.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 11, 'And many false prophets will appear and will lead many people astray.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 12, 'Sin will be rampant everywhere, and the love of many will grow cold.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 13, 'But those who endure to the end will be saved.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 14, 'And the Good News about the Kingdom will be preached throughout the whole world, so that all nations will hear it; and then, finally, the end will come.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 15, '"The time will come when you will see what Daniel the prophet spoke about: the sacrilegious object that causes desecration standing in the Holy Place"--reader, pay attention!', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 16, '"Then those in Judea must flee to the hills.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 17, 'A person outside the house must not go inside to pack.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 18, 'A person in the field must not return even to get a coat.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 19, 'How terrible it will be for pregnant women and for mothers nursing their babies in those days.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 20, 'And pray that your flight will not be in winter or on the Sabbath.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 21, 'For that will be a time of greater horror than anything the world has ever seen or will ever see again.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 22, 'In fact, unless that time of calamity is shortened, the entire human race will be destroyed. But it will be shortened for the sake of God''s chosen ones.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 23, '"Then if anyone tells you, ''Look, here is the Messiah,'' or ''There he is,'' don''t pay any attention.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 24, 'For false messiahs and false prophets will rise up and perform great miraculous signs and wonders so as to deceive, if possible, even God''s chosen ones.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 25, 'See, I have warned you.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 26, '"So if someone tells you, ''Look, the Messiah is out in the desert,'' don''t bother to go and look. Or, ''Look, he is hiding here,'' don''t believe it!', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 27, 'For as the lightning lights up the entire sky, so it will be when the Son of Man comes.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 28, 'Just as the gathering of vultures shows there is a carcass nearby, so these signs indicate that the end is near.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 29, '"Immediately after those horrible days end, the sun will be darkened, the moon will not give light, the stars will fall from the sky, and the powers of heaven will be shaken.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 30, 'And then at last, the sign of the coming of the Son of Man will appear in the heavens, and there will be deep mourning among all the nations of the earth. And they will see the Son of Man arrive on the clouds of heaven with power and great glory.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 31, 'And he will send forth his angels with the sound of a mighty trumpet blast, and they will gather together his chosen ones from the farthest ends of the earth and heaven.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 32, '"Now learn a lesson from the fig tree. When its buds become tender and its leaves begin to sprout, you know without being told that summer is near.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 33, 'Just so, when you see the events I''ve described beginning to happen, you can know his return is very near, right at the door.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 34, 'I assure you, this generation will not pass from the scene before all these things take place.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 35, 'Heaven and earth will disappear, but my words will remain forever.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 36, '"However, no one knows the day or the hour when these things will happen, not even the angels in heaven or the Son himself. Only the Father knows.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 37, '"When the Son of Man returns, it will be like it was in Noah''s day.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 38, 'In those days before the Flood, the people were enjoying banquets and parties and weddings right up to the time Noah entered his boat.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 39, 'People didn''t realize what was going to happen until the Flood came and swept them all away. That is the way it will be when the Son of Man comes.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 40, '"Two men will be working together in the field; one will be taken, the other left.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 41, 'Two women will be grinding flour at the mill; one will be taken, the other left.', 'NLT'),
(44, 24, 42, 'So be prepared, because you don''t know what day your Lord is coming.', 'NLT');
